<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE> AN OPEN LETTER TO THE PRESIDENT OF THE PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF CHINA</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>
 
<P> June 9th, 1996
<P><B>AN OPEN LETTER TO THE PRESIDENT OF THE PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF CHINA</B>


<P>TO:       
<BR> Jiang Zemin
       <BR>President of the People's Republic of China
             <BR>c/o State Science and Technology Commission (please forward)
        <BR>Fax 86 10 6851 2163
 
<P>CC:        <BR>  Yu Pengnian and Guo Qiyuan
                <BR>c/o Foreign Affairs Office
         <BR>Shanghai Municipal People's Government
               <BR>Fax 86 21 6255 2761
 

<P>From:       <BR> MV Greenpeace
        <BR>FAX:  872-130-0311
 
 

<P><B>Dear Mr. President,</B>
 
<P>We are writing to you on behalf of Greenpeace.  As you may know, Greenpeace is
an independent, popularly supported non-governmental organization that has
worked for 25 years to convince the nuclear weapons states to stop testing.  As
of this year, the United States, Russia, France and the United Kingdom have
stopped nuclear testing and the world is on the verge of achieving a
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
 
<P>On the evening of June 8, the MV Greenpeace departed from Manila to continue
its voyage of peace to China.  We bear a message about the need to end nuclear
testing and agree to a genuine CTBT by the end of June.
 
<P>The June 8 nuclear weapons test at Lop Nor, and your country's announcement
that another test is planned by September,  have underscored the urgency of our
visit to Shanghai. These additional tests, aside from the environmental
contamination they will cause, could sabotage the CTBT talks underway in
Geneva.  China's continued testing is also impeding progress towards complete
global nuclear disarmament, of which a CTBT is the first step. 
 
<P>There are less than three weeks remaining to reach agreement on a CTBT if the
treaty is to be ready for signing this year.  There is an urgent need for China
to take steps to support a meaningful CTBT now, including cancelling further
tests and dropping all references to so-called peaceful nuclear explosions. 
 
<P>Although the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Beijing has expressed reservations
about the MV Greenpeace's visit, we hope you, the Ministry, and other members
of government will appreciate its importance and welcome us to Shanghai.
Additionally, we hope that when we reach Chinese waters around June 12 the
reception will be cordial.  While in Shanghai, we look forward to meeting with
representatives of the People's Republic of China to discuss these serious
matters of nuclear disarmament and an immediate end to nuclear testing.
 
<P>On behalf of the millions of people around the world who want an end to nuclear
testing and a meaningful Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, we look forward to
hearing from you at your earliest convenience.
 
<B><P>Respectfully,
<BR>Ulf Birgander, 
<BR>Master
Xavier Pastor, Campaigner</B>
<BR><BR>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML> 
