<HEAD><TITLE> AN OPEN LETTER TO SHANGHAI MUNICIPAL AUTHORITIES
 </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>
 
<P><B> AN OPEN LETTER TO SHANGHAI MUNICIPAL AUTHORITIES
 </B>


<P> June 9th, 1996
 
<P>TO:         <BR> Yu Pengnian and Guo Qiyuan
                <BR>c/o Foreign Affairs Office
        <BR> Shanghai Municipal People's Government
               <BR> Fax 86 21 6255 2761
 
<P>CC:       <BR> Jiang Zemin
        <BR>President of the People's Republic of China
            <BR>  c/o State Science and Technology Commission (please forward)
       <BR> Fax 86 10 6851 2163
 
<P>From:        <BR>MV Greenpeace
        <BR>FAX:  872-130-0311
 

 
 
<P><B>Gentlemen,</B>
 
<P>On the evening of June 8 the MV Greenpeace departed from Manila to continue its
voyage of peace to China.  We bear a message about the need to end nuclear
testing and agree to a truly comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty (CTBT) by
the end of June.
 
<P>As you know, Greenpeace is an independent, popularly supported non-governmental
organization that has worked for 25 years to convince the nuclear weapons
states to stop testing.  As of  this year, the United States, Russia, France
and the United Kingdom have stopped nuclear testing and the world is on the
verge of achieving a CTBT.
 
<P>China's June 8 nuclear weapons test at Lop Nor, and your country's announcement
that another test is planned by September,  have underscored the urgency of our
visit to Shanghai. These additional tests, aside from the environmental
contamination they will cause, could sabotage the CTBT talks underway in
Geneva.  China's continued testing is also impeding progress towards complete
global nuclear disarmament, of which a CTBT is the first step. 
 
<P>There are less than three weeks remaining to reach agreement on a CTBT if the
treaty is to be ready for signing this year.  There is an urgent need for China
to take steps to support a meaningful CTBT now, including cancelling further
tests and dropping all references to peaceful nuclear explosions. 
 
<P>Although you have expressed reservations about the MV Greenpeace's visit, we
hope you and your government will appreciate its importance and welcome us to
Shanghai.  Additionally, we hope that when we reach Chinese waters around  June
12 the reception will be cordial and you will be able to facilitate our
arrival.  While in Shanghai, we look forward to meeting with you and other
officials to discuss these serious matters of nuclear disarmament and an
immediate end to nuclear testing.
 
<P>On behalf of the millions of people around the world who want an end to nuclear
testing and a meaningful Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, we look forward to
hearing from you soon.
 
<B><P>Sincerely,
<BR>Ulf Birgander, Master
<BR>Xavier Pastor, Campaigner</B>

<BR><BR>

</TD>
