<H3>PRESS CONFERENCE ON-BOARD THE ANTI-NUCLEAR
    CAMPAIGN SHIP  MV GREENPEACE' IN NAGASAKI, 27 JUNE 1996:</H3>
 



<P> In a final attempt to achieve a
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which would end all nuclear
blasts and be a first step towards total nuclear disarmament,
the anti-nuclear campaign ship MV Greenpeace will visit
Nagasaki on the eve of the deadline for the final treaty to be
completed in Geneva.  Nagasaki witnessed the dawn of the
nuclear age when it was destroyed by an atomic bomb on August
9, 1945.
 

<P>All interested press are invited to a press conference on-board
the ship MV Greenpeace, at the Matsugae pier in Nagasaki, on 
June 27th at 1400h (2:00 pm). 
 

<P>During their stay, Greenpeace representatives will meet with 
the Mayor of Nagasaki and local non-governmental organisations, 
and visit the city's Peace Park on the final day of the CTBT 
talks in Geneva.
 
 

<P>The ship was recently expelled from Chinese waters off Shanghai 
while campaigning against China's position in the treaty 
negotiations, which threatens to undermine the intent of the 
test ban.  
 

<B><P>Time:               1400h

<P>Date:               27 June 1996

<P>Place:         Aboard MV Greenpeace, Matsugae Pier, Nagasaki

<P>Speakers:      Ulf Birgander, Captain of the MV Greenpeace
               Kazue Suzuki, Greenpeace Japan
 

<P>Schedule:
 

<P>26 June 1996 0800h, ship arrives at Port of Nagasaki
 
<P>27 June 1996 1400h, press conference on final stages of CTBT negotiations 
      1530h, Greenpeace meeting with Mayor Ito
      1800h, symposium with Nagasaki non-governmental organisations    
<P>28 June 1996 1400h, ceremony of remembrance of victims of 
        atomic weapons at Nagasaki Peace Park
<P>29 June 1996 1030h - 1730h, public open boat
<P>30 June 1996 1030h - 1730h, public open boat</B>
 
                        
 

<B><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: 


<P>John Willis (English)/Noriko Oyama (Japanese) 
                      5351 5400 or 030 216 8214 (mobile)</B>
 

