<HEAD><TITLE>ONLY ONE WEEK LEFT TO THE END OF THE GENEVA CONFERENCE OF DISARMAMENT NEGOTIATIONS FOR A CTBT :</TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>ONLY ONE WEEK LEFT TO THE END OF THE GENEVA CONFERENCE OF DISARMAMENT NEGOTIATIONS FOR A CTBT :</H3>
 

<P><B>Chinese President JIANG ZEMIN is visiting Spain: GREENPEACE will actively protest to demand the end of nuclear testing

<P>GENEVA, 22nd June 1996</B>  



<P>Greenpeace stated today, in a press conference held in Majorca (Spain), that it will peacefully protest during the official visit to Spain of the President of the People’s Republic of China, Jiang ZEMIN, in order to force the Chinese Government to sign a truly Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) based on the  Zero Yield  option. 

<P>Greenpeace spokespersons also denounced the irresponsible position of the Spanish Government and its Prime Minister, Jose Maria Aznar, who is yet to condemn the June 8th Chinese nuclear  test at Lop Nor and has not officially rejected the Chinese proposal of leaving the door open to  Peaceful Nuclear Explosions.

<P>The Chinese President’s visit  to Spain starts on Sunday, 23 when he arrives in Majorca. Then, he will fly to Madrid for two days, and then spent another day (Wed, 26) in Barcelona. Greenpeace will be protesting during the whole visit.

<P>Xavier Pastor, Executive Director of Greenpeace Spain, who has just returned to Spain after heading up a peaceful protest voyage to China on board the MV Greenpeace, and  Carlos Bravo, GP Spain anti-nuclear campaigner,  denounced the irresponsible position of the Spanish Government who is silent about the nuclear testing programme of China and its unjustifiable position on PNEs in Geneva.

"Spain is now a full member of the Conference of Disarmament,"Mr Bravo said. “Unjustifiable commercial Spanish interests are the reason behind Spain’s official silence."

In particular, the interests of the Spanish Government, at present negotiating several contracts to sell aircraft carriers to China and the intent of a desperate Spanish nuclear industry to obtain some contracts in China, are forcing the Aznar Government to keep completely quiet about the Chinese  position in the CTBT negotiations.

"An absolute and immense majority of the Spanish population is in favour of banning  all nuclear tests or nuclear explosions forever. The attitude of the Spanish Government of favouring particular commercial interests is clearly opposed to the wish of the Spanish society" , stated Bravo.


 

<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: 


<P>Kate Johnston in Amsterdam +31.20.523.62.16
<P> or
<P> Simon Carroll in Geneva on mobile +41.79.213.70.67.
</B>
<BR><BR>

</TD>
