<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>GREENPEACE RESPONSE TO INDIA’S STATEMENT TO THE CONFERENCE ON DISARMAMENT:</H3>
 

<P><B> "Special Treatment"
would undermine test-ban.

<P>GENEVA, 20th June 1996</B>
 




<P> India will not achieve its “quest for world peace” by blocking progress at  talks to negotiate a Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty or threatening to opt out of the treaty, Greenpeace said today.

<P>A Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty that prohibits all nuclear tests is the first step to total nuclear disarmament and any delay to the signing of the treaty is a delay on the road to a nuclear free world.

<P>Greenpeace applauds India’s sentiments expressed in today’s speech, but deplores any veiled threats that it would refuse to sign a CTBT.  Greenpeace believes it is essential to ban all nuclear weapons explosions and that all countries, including India, should join a Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty to achieve that goal.

<P>If the five Nuclear Weapons States (China, France, UK, Russia, USA) want India to support the treaty they should make a commitment not to develop, produce or deploy new nuclear weapons and to seek greater nuclear disarmament -  instead of using Entry Into Force requirements to bully India into joining the CTBT.




<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: 


<P>Kate Johnston in Amsterdam +31.20.523.62.16
<P> or
<P> Simon Carroll in Geneva on mobile +41.79.213.70.67.
</B>
