<HEAD><TITLE>RENEWED PROTEST AGAINST CHINAS ATOMIC EXPLOSIONS:</TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>RENEWED PROTEST AGAINST CHINAS ATOMIC EXPLOSIONS
</H3>
 

<B>

<P>GENEVA, 20th June 1996</B>



<P> Greenpeace members handed 30, 000 signatures from Switzerland, Italy, Germany and Tunisia to the Chinese UN-mission in Geneva today and demanded that China agree to a total ban on all nuclear tests


<P>In contrast to other delegations to the Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty  negotiations in Geneva, China is not ready to declare a total nuclear test ban, proposing on a ten-year moratorium for so-called “Peaceful” nuclear explosions. 


<P>World-wide Greenpeace has collected almost 700,000 signatures calling for an immediate prohibition of all nuclear explosions. Most of the signatures have been handed to the respective Chinese embassies in the countries they were collected.  Greenpeace Switzerland today handed 30, 000 signatures and photographs to the Chinese UN-mission in Geneva, fastened to a 30 metre rope and carried by 25 activists.


<P>For 25 years Greenpeace has fought for a complete ban of all nuclear tests. Until last year the nuclear weapon states would only commit to restraints on the size of explosions. A complete ban first became possible at the peak of the campaign against the French nuclear tests in the South Pacific when France, the USA and Great Britain announced they would sign a zero-yield. Russia joined this group in the spring 1996. 


<P>China is alone in insisting that Peaceful nuclear explosions be included in the treaty and on Tuesday (June 18), made a formal proposal that PNEs be reviewed in 10 years and that review be automatic unless a majority of countries vote against it.


<P>China remains the main obstacle to the signing of a total nuclear testing ban Greenpeace is appealing to the members the UN-Conference not to make weak compromises to the treaty, and to ban both military and "civil" atomic bomb tests once and for all.


<B><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<P> Clemens Tolusso, Press officer Greenpeace Switzerland 

<P>or  

<P>Peter Metzinger, campaign director Greenpeace Switzerland, ++41-1- 295 94 39
</B>

<BR><BR>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML> 
