<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>GREENPEACE CALLS ON CTBT DELEGATES TO OPPOSE CHINA's
'PEACEFUL' NUCLEAR EXPLOSIONS' PROPOSAL:</TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>GREENPEACE CALLS ON CTBT DELEGATES TO OPPOSE CHINA's
'PEACEFUL' NUCLEAR EXPLOSIONS' PROPOSAL:</H3>
 

<P><B> "Special Treatment"
would undermine test-ban.

<P>GENEVA, 19 June 1996</B>
 

<P> China formally introduced its proposal
to include so-called "Peaceful" Nuclear Explosions in the
final wording of the Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty, at
a `closed-door' meeting in Geneva last night (Tuesday June18).
 
<P>Greenpeace is calling on CTBT delegations to join Mexico,
Canada, Japan and Australia in strongly opposing the Chinese
proposal and to call for a test ban that prohibits all nuclear
tests for all time.
 
<P>Under China's proposal, Peaceful Nuclear Explosions (PNEs)
would be reconsidered at  a review conference 10 years after
the CTBT enters into force. Review would be AUTOMATIC unless a
majority of parties voted against it.
 
<P>On 6 June, China unofficially suggested at a plenary session
that China would accept a zero-yield CTBT but ONLY IF
countries accepted China's idea that PNEs should be
specifically reviewed in the treaty in 10 years time.
 
<P>"Any nuclear explosion can be used to gather information for
building nuclear weapons - the Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban
Treaty must ban all nuclear tests of any kind if the true
intention of the treaty is to rid the world of nuclear tests,"
Greenpeace spokesperson Josh Handler said.
 
<P>"China's proposal on PNEs has been widely mis-reported as a
concession or compromise that clears the way for getting a
CTBT by the end of June, but China has conceded nothing.
Acceptance of a zero-yield treaty is still being held hostage
to China's insistence that PNEs be legitimized in the treaty
in some form."
 
<P>The U.S. and the Soviet Union conducted some 150 nuclear
explosions for peaceful purposes between 1961 and 1988 before
they were abandoned as unnecessary and dangerous technology.
 
<P><B>FURTHER INFORMATION:
<P>Simon Carroll in Geneva on
+41.21.728.52.25; mobile +41.79.213.70.67 
<P>or
<P>Kate Johnston in
Amsterdam on +31.20.523.62.16; mobile +31.653.41.79.47.


<P>Peaceful Nuclear Explosion factsheet available on request.

<P><a href="upjun19b.html">GREENPEACE PNE
BRIEFING PAPER</a> 19th June 1996</B>

 <BR><BR>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
