<HEAD><TITLE>MV GREENPEACE ARRIVES IN HONG KONG :</TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>MV GREENPEACE ARRIVES IN HONG KONG AFTER EXPULSION FROM CHINESE WATERS DURING ANTI-NUCLEAR PEACE VOYAGE</H3>
 
<P><B>HONG KONG, 16th June 1996: 12 noon</B>


<P>The MV Greenpeace sailed into Hong Kong this
morning, three days after campaigners met People's Republic of China officials
and called on China to commit to a total nuclear test ban.
 
<P>"We successfully delivered our message to the Chinese government," said Xavier
Pastor, the senior campaigner on board the MV Greenpeace.  "The Chinese
government cannot escape the fact that their ongoing nuclear weapons tests are
jeopardizing the talks for an end to nuclear testing.  The world is calling for
an end to all nuclear tests for all time and China is currently the major
obstacle to achieving that."
 
<P>China's obstinate position that a review of so-called "Peaceful" Nuclear
Explosions be written into the Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty, threatens
to destabilize treaty discussions, taking place in Geneva until June 28.  Less
than two weeks remain for delegates to negotiate a treaty that could be ready
for signing in 1996.
 
<P>Earlier this month China announced it would agree to a CTBT only if a ban on
so-called "Peaceful" Nuclear Explosion (PNEs) would be reviewed in 10 years.
 
<P>"Any nuclear test can be used to gain information for the development of
nuclear weapons," Mr Pastor said.  "China is being hypocritical to say it
supports a CTBT while insisting on a review that could allow them to detonate
'peaceful' nuclear explosions in the future."
 
<P>China is the only declared nuclear weapons state with an active nuclear testing
program and on June 8, detonated its 44th nuclear test, provoking world-wide
condemnation, including protests from the governments of at least 17 countries
and some of China's neighbors: Japan, Kazakhstan, Mongolia, New Zealand,
Australia, the Philippines and South Korea.  China plans to explode another
nuclear weapons test before September.
 
<P>The crew of the MV Greenpeace - 32 people from 16 nations - endured a tense
four hours in Chinese territorial waters off Shanghai on Wednesday, June 12,
when approximately 70 Chinese soldiers, outnumbering the crew by two to one,
boarded the ship and cut its communications.
 
<P>Mr Pastor added: "This campaign is not over.   With just two weeks to go before
the CTBT negotiations fail or succeed, Greenpeace will continue to press all
countries to join together in taking this historic step towards ending the
nuclear arms race.  We have a way to go before ridding the world of all nuclear
weapons, but such a journey must begin with the decisive first step - an end to
nuclear testing."
 
<P>The MV Greenpeace will be moored in Hong Kong until the evening of Thursday
June 20.  It will be open to the public on Wednesday June 19 from 12pm to 8pm
and on Thursday from 10am to 4pm.  Launches will run to and from the Tsim Sha
Tsui public pier at regular intervals throughout both days.  There will be
exhibitions on board the ship explaining the work of Greenpeace, and everything
is free of charge.
 

<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT GREENPEACE INTERNATIONAL IN HONG KONG </B>


<P><B>ANNE DINGWALL or CLEMENT LAM HAU-KEEN</B>

<P><B>Tel : </B>(852) 2745 6914 or 2745 6017

<P><B>Fax :</B> (852) 2745 2426

 <BR><BR>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
