<HEAD><TITLE>MV GREENPEACE EXPELLED FROM CHINESE WATERS: </TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 

 
<H3>MV GREENPEACE EXPELLED FROM CHINESE WATERS: SETS COURSE TO HONG KONG</H3>



<P>East China Sea, June 12th 1996


<P>The MV Greenpeace set a course for Hong Kong today after being boarded by approximately 70 unarmed Chinese soldiers, who took control of the ship and expelled it from Chinese waters.

<P>Speaking from on-board the MV Greenpeace, nuclear campaigner Xavier Pastor said: "We believe we have achieved what we came here to do - before the ship was expelled the Chinese officials received our message to stop nuclear testing and commit to a total nuclear test ban and agreed to deliver it to the authorities in Beijing."

<P>In a ceremony held on board the heli-deck of the MV Greenpeace, the crew  - representing 16 nations -  presented the Chinese officials with anti-nuclear testing gifts from around the world.

<P>The peaceful voyage was timed to coincide with talks in Geneva to negotiate a Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).  There are now less than three weeks left if delegates are to agree a treaty to be ready for signing before the end of 1996. 

<P>China's position at the CTBT talks and it's nuclear testing programme remain major obstacles to  achieving a nuclear testing ban in 1996. China announced last week that it would agree to a CTBT ONLY IF a ban on so-called "Peaceful" Nuclear Explosions (PNEs) could be reviewed in 10 years.
    
<P>On Saturday, June 8th, China detonated its 44th nuclear test, provoking world-wide condemnation, including protests from many of it's neighbours: Australia, Japan, Kazakhstan, Mongolia, New Zealand, the Philippines and South Korea. China plans to explode another nuclear weapon test before September.

<P>"We have achieved what we could on this voyage and we now call on world leaders to take up the protest and demand that China stop nuclear testing and commit to a truly Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty, without compromise for so-called "peaceful" nuclear explosions," Mr Pastor said.

<P>The MV Greenpeace is approximately three days sailing time from Hong Kong.  A press conference will be held in Hong Kong when the boat arrives.

<BR>

<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:</B>


<P> <B>Damon Moglen or Clement Lam in Hong Kong</B> on +852 2745 6914 or 2745 6017 


<P><B>or</B>


<P> <B>Xavier Pastor on board the MV Greenpeace</B>  on +872 130 0310 (SATPHONE:US$10 per min).



<P><B>Kate Johnston or Josh Handler in Amsterdam</B> +31 20 523 6216/6267

<BR><BR>

</TD>
