<H3>GREENPEACE BOAT ARRIVES OFF CHINESE COAST TO DELIVER 'STOP NUCLEAR TESTING'
MESSAGE</H3>
 
<P><B>HONG KONG, 12th June 1996: 12 noon</B>



 

<P>The MV Greenpeace arrived off the Chinese
coast today at 11.34am local time.
 
<P>No attempt has been made to prevent the ship from entering Chinese territorial
waters and there are no Chinese naval vessels in sight.
 
<P>The ship is heading to an anchorage area near Changjiang Kou buoy, near the
mouth of the Yangtze river which leads to the port of Shanghai.  The vessel is
signaling for a pilot to continue its entry into the port of Shanghai.
 
<P>The peaceful voyage of the MV Greenpeace has been timed to coincide with talks
in Geneva to negotiate a Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT). There
are now less than three weeks left if delegates are to agree a treaty to be
ready for signing before the end of 1996.
 
<P>Speaking from on board the MV Greenpeace, senior campaigner Xavier Pastor said:
"We bear a message which is supported by millions of people around the planet -
China must stop nuclear testing immediately and commit to a truly Comprehensive
nuclear Test Ban."
 
<P>China's position at the CTBT talks and its nuclear testing programme remain
major obstacles to achieving a nuclear testing ban in 1996. China announced
last week that it would agree to a CTBT ONLY IF a ban on so-called "Peaceful"
Nuclear Explosions (PNEs) could be reviewed in 10 years.
 
<P>On Saturday, June 8, China detonated its 44th nuclear test, provoking
world-wide condemnation, including protests from many of its neighbors:
Australia, Japan, Kazakhstan, Mongolia, New Zealand, the Philippines and South
Korea. China plans another nuclear weapons test by September.



<BR>
<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: </B>

<P>Damon Moglen and Clement Lam in
Hong Kong on +852 2745 6914 or 2745 6017,
<P><B> or</B>
<P> Xavier Pastor on board
the MV Greenpeace  on +872 130 0310 (SATPHONE: costs US$10 per
min).

