<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>MV GREENPEACE NEARS CHINESE WATERS:
REITERATES NEED FOR IMMEDIATE NUCLEAR TEST BAN</H3>
 
<P><B>HONG KONG, 11th June 1996</B>
<P>The MV Greenpeace is one day's sail from
Chinese national waters off Shanghai on its voyage to deliver a
peaceful message to China to stop nuclear testing and commit to a
total nuclear test ban.

<P>At midday the ship reported it was approximately 100 miles off
Wenzhou, a coastal city in the Chinese province of Zhejiang.  It is
estimated the MV Greenpeace will approach Chinese territorial
waters off Shanghai tomorrow (WEDNESDAY) morning.

<P>The voyage has been timed to coincide with talks in Geneva to
negotiate a Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).  There
are now less than three weeks left if delegates are to agree a
treaty that could be ready for signing before the end of 1996. 
China's position at the talks and nuclear testing program remain
major obstacles to achieving a CTBT in 1996.

<P>China announced last week that it would agree to a CTBT ONLY IF an
allowance was included in the treaty for a ban on so-called
"Peaceful" Nuclear Explosions (PNEs) to be reviewed in 10 years.

<P>Speaking from on board the MV Greenpeace, nuclear campaigner Xavier
Pastor said:  "ANY nuclear explosion - peaceful or otherwise - can
be used to gain information for developing nuclear weapons and the
CTBT should ban any and all nuclear tests.  China's position of
linking PNEs in the review to its support of a comprehensive test
ban is unacceptable.  China's position still remains a major
obstacle to getting an effective CTBT by the end of June."

<P>China detonated a nuclear weapon at its Lop Nor test site on
Saturday and announced it would test again before September. 
Saturday's test sparked condemnation around the world.  Sixteen
countries have criticized the renewed testing program, including
many of China's neighbors: Australia, Japan, Kazakhstan, Mongolia,
New Zealand, the Philippines and South Korea.

<P>"China's testing plan underscores the urgency of our peace visit,"
said Mr Pastor.  "The world wants an end to nuclear testing now. 
We are sailing to Shanghai to keep up the momentum for achieving a
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.  With less than three weeks of
negotiations to go, China needs to push for this historic treaty,
not conduct further nuclear tests."


<BR>
<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: </B>

<P>Damon Moglen and Clement Lam in
Hong Kong on +852 2745 6914 or 2745 6017,
<P><B> or</B>
<P> Xavier Pastor on board
the MV Greenpeace  on +872 130 0310 (SATPHONE: costs US$10 per
min).

 <BR><BR>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
