<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>MV GREENPEACE NEARS SOUTHERN TIP OF TAIWAN</H3>
 
<P><B>HONG KONG, 10th June 1996</B>
                                        
	
 

<P>At 4pm local time (0800GMT) the MV Greenpeace, on a peaceful voyage to China, reported that her position was 80 nautical miles northeast of O luan pi, the southern tip of Taiwan. 
 
<P>The Dutch flagged vessel, with 32 Greenpeace and other crew on board from 16 different nations, is sailing to Shanghai in a bid to open direct discussions with officials in China about nuclear disarmament and the crucial talks progressing in Geneva towards a Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT). 
 
<P>The Greenpeace vessel left Manila on Saturday, June 8, at 1810 local time, the same day that China conducted a nuclear weapons test which was condemned by a number of countries around the planet including Australia, Japan, New Zealand, the Philippines, South Korea and the United States. 

<P>China's 20 80 kiloton nuclear test was carried out even as CTBT talks are ongoing at the United Nations in Geneva.  Greenpeace has carried out protests at Chinese embassies and consulates in more than a dozen countries around the world. 
 
<P>The MV Greenpeace is expected to arrive in the waters off Shanghai on Wednesday, June 12. 
 
<P>Neither the MV Greenpeace nor Greenpeace International has yet had a reply to its message sent yesterday to Chinese President Jiang Zemin and senior Shanghai municipal authorities.  The letter advised the officials of the ship's progress and requested talks in Shanghai between Greenpeace and Chinese officials about nuclear disarmament and an immediate end to nuclear testing. 
                           
 <BR><BR>


<P><B>For further information please contact:</B>

<P>-Greenpeace Communications: +44171-833-0600

<P>-Greenpeace International (24-hours daily): +3120-523-6279, 6226 or 6216

<P>-Greenpeace in Hong Kong on +852 2745 6914, 

+852 2745 6017 or fax +852 2745 2426. 

<P>-Xavier Pastor on board the MV Greenpeace on INMARSAT: 
+872 130 0310 (US$10/min). 
 
 
<BR><BR>

</TD>
