<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>MV GREENPEACE SENDS MESSAGE TO CHINA,
 REQUESTS ENTRY TO SHANGHAI
 </H3>
 
<P><B>HONG KONG, 10th June 1996</B>
 

<P>The MV Greenpeace, a campaign ship of the
environmental group Greenpeace, today (SUNDAY) sent an open letter to Chinese
President Jiang Zemin requesting his assistance in facilitating the ship's
visit to Shanghai.  
 
<P>The international environmental organization has sent its flagship to Shanghai
in a bid to engage Chinese officials in a dialogue around ending nuclear tests.
 
<P>The message from the ship, which was faxed via satellite to President Jiang and
senior Shanghai municipal authorities, called for discussions with Chinese
leaders on the "serious matters of nuclear disarmament and an immediate end to
nuclear testing".
 
<P>Signed by Xavier Pastor, the senior Greenpeace campaigner on board the ship,
the letter voiced concern about China's ongoing nuclear weapons testing program
and its effect on crucial negotiations for a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT).
 
<P>"The June 8 nuclear weapons test at Lop Nor and your country's announcement
that another test is planned by September, have underscored the urgency of our
visit to Shanghai," Mr Pastor wrote.
 
<P>From the MV Greenpeace, Mr Pastor said: "China has long called for nuclear
disarmament. They now have the opportunity to provide leadership in assuring a
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.  They can either secure or sacrifice a ban on
nuclear tests for all time.
 
<P>"Ongoing testing neither complies with the intent nor the spirit of the CTBT.
The Chinese must choose between developing weapons and developing peace."
 

 
<P><B>For Further Information, please contact</B>
 
<P>Greenpeace International  in Hong Kong
 
<P>DAMON MOGLEN or CLEMENT LAM HAU-KEEN
Tel : (852) 2745 6914 or 2745 6017
Fax : (852) 2745 2426
 

<BR><BR>

</TD>
