<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>MV GREENPEACE SETS SAIL FOR SHANGHAI TO DELIVER STOP NUCLEAR 
TESTING MESSAGE </H3>
 
<P><B>MANILA, 7th June 1996</B>



<P>The ship MV Greenpeace will 
depart Manila tomorrow on the final leg of its journey to 
Shanghai to deliver a peaceful message to China to stop 
nuclear testing and commit to a total nuclear test ban. 
The peace voyage has been timed to coincide with talks 
taking place in Geneva to negotiate a Comprehensive nuclear Test 
Ban Treaty (CTBT). Only three weeks remain if CTBT 
delegates are to agree a treaty before the end of June. 

<P>China announced this week that it would only agree to a zero 
yield CTBT if an allowance was included in the treaty for a ban 
on so-called "Peaceful" Nuclear Explosions (PNEs) to be reviewed 
in 10 years. 

<P>"China is placing pre-conditions on a total nuclear test ban and 
is weakening the ban before it has even been agreed. We are 
calling on the govenments at thwe conference
delegation to the conference to strongly oppose China's 
proposal, " Greenpeace campaigner Josh Handler said. 
"Special treatment for PNEs is unnecessary because under the 
current draft of the treaty any issue can be raised at 
future review meetings. And yet by highlighting PNEs China raises 
the possibility that they could be conducted in the future. ANY 
nuclear explosion - peaceful or otherwise - can be used to gain 
information for developing nuclear weapons and the CTBT should 
ban any and all nuclear tests,"
<P>"The world is on the verge of agreeing a truly Comprehensive 
nuclear Test Ban Treaty and we are sailing to Shanghai to be sure 
that China knows that now is the time to secure a 
future free of all nuclear testing," Handler said. 





<P><B>NOTE:</B> China is the only nuclear weapons state with an active 
nuclear testing programme and is reportedly planning to 
conduct its 44th nuclear test within days. Other countries have 
conducted peaceful nuclear explosions in the past but the 
practice has been abandoned by all of them due to 
considerable environmental problems, the lack of any 
tangible benefits and major concerns about nuclear 
proliferation. 

<BR><BR>  
  

<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:</B>


<P> Atchena Ronquillo  in Manila +
63 2 527 9684 

<P><B>or</B>

<P> Kate Johnston in Amsterdam on +31 20 523 6216, mobile 
+653 417947. 

