<HEAD><TITLE>GREENPEACE REJECTS CHINA'S CONDITION ON NUCLEAR TREATY </TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>GREENPEACE REJECTS CHINA'S CONDITION ON NUCLEAR TREATY </H3>

<P> Calls "Insulting" Requests for Provisions in CTBT to Allow 
"Peaceful Nuclear Tests" 
<P><B>WASHINGTON, June 6th 1996</B>

 

<P>Greenpeace dismissed as "insulting" 
China s proposal today at the  Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty 
talks in Geneva that would leave open the possibility of 
conducting so-called 'peaceful nuclear explosions' in the future. 
 
<P>China announced Thursday that it would agree to a zero-yield CTBT 
only if the treaty would allow a ban on 'peaceful nuclear 
explosions' to be reviewed in 10-years. China's official 
announcement stated, "the Chinese delegation is now ready to go 
along with a temporary ban on peaceful nuclear 
explosions...[provided that] the possibility of permitting the 
conduct of peaceful nuclear explosions shall be considered by the 
review conferences of states parties." 
  
<P>The current draft treaty already states that any issue can be 
raised at a review conference in 10 years. "Giving special 
treatment to 'peaceful nuclear explosions' would substantially 
weaken the treaty," said Greenpeace disarmament campaigner Bruce 
Hall in Washington. He dismissed China's statement saying, "There 
is nothing peaceful about nuclear explosions. This is an insult 
to common sense and to all the nations of the world legitimately 
committed to nuclear disarmament."  
 
<P>Monitoring the CTBT talks in Geneva, Greenpeace's Simon Carroll 
said,  "Special treatment for peaceful nuclear explosions leaves 
open the possibility that they could be conducted in the future. 
ANY nuclear explosion can be used to gain information for 
developing nuclear weapons. The Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty 
should be just that: comprehensive. It should ban ANY and ALL 
nuclear explosions."  
 
<P>China is the only nation currently conducting nuclear tests, with 
preparations now underway for another blast. Greenpeace called 
on the Clinton administration to strongly oppose China's CTBT 
proposal and call on the Chinese to immediately join the 
worldwide testing moratorium.  
 
<P>Hall also said the U.S. should cancel its own  'subcritical' 
nuclear weapons tests, slated to begin June 18th at the Nevada 
Test Site.  In an article headlined, "US postpones nuclear 
tests,"  the Asia Times newspaper reported today, "an official 
announcement [from the U.S.] would be made by the weekend."   
 
<P>"Postponement is not good enough," said Greenpeace's Hall. "Just 
like China, the U.S. tests need to be cancelled and their test 
site shut down."                               ### 

<BR><BR>
 
<B>CONTACT: </B>
<P>Bruce Hall in Washington, 202-319-2514 
          
<P><B>or</B>
<P> Simon Carroll in Geneva, 011-41-21-728-52-25   


<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
