<HEAD><TITLE>GREENPEACE SLAMS CHINESE NON-COMPROMISE ON 'PEACEFUL'
NUCLEAR EXPLOSIONS </TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>

 
<H3>GREENPEACE SLAMS CHINESE NON-COMPROMISE ON 'PEACEFUL'
NUCLEAR EXPLOSIONS</H3>
 
<P><B>GENEVA, 6th June 1996</B>


<P>Greenpeace has slammed a proposal
put forward by China  at Comprehensive nuclear Test Ban
treaty talks in Geneva today,  that would allow for a ban
on  so-called 'peaceful nuclear explosions'  to be
reviewed in 10 years.
 
<P>The organisation called on delegations to the Conference
on Disarmament to strongly oppose China's proposal
because "special treatment" for peaceful nuclear
explosions would severely undermine the effectiveness of
a nuclear test-ban.
 
<P>"China is placing pre-conditions on a total nuclear test
ban, weakening the ban before it has even been agreed.
China is effectively holding the CTBT hostage,"
Greenpeace spokesperson Simon Carroll said.
 
<P>"The main purpose of a nuclear test-ban is to prohibit
ALL nuclear explosions of any size for any purpose
whatsoever and any door left open for peaceful nuclear
explosions (PNEs), is simply a quick exit from a true and
effective nuclear test-ban treaty. All countries should
reject China's non-compromise."
 
<P>China announced that it would agree to a zero yield CTBT
only if  "....the possibility of permitting the conduct
of PNEs shall be considered by the review conferences of
states parties".
 
<P>Greenpeace believes that giving special treatment to PNEs
is unnecessary because the current draft treaty already
states that any issue can be raised at a review
conference in 10 years.
 
<P>"Special treatment for PNEs leaves open the possibility
that they could be conducted in the future. ANY nuclear
explosion - peaceful or otherwise - can be used to gain
information for developing nuclear weapons and the CTBT
should ban ANY and ALL nuclear tests," Mr Carroll said.
 
<P><B>NOTE:</B> Other countries have conducted peaceful nuclear
explosions in the past but the practice has been
abandoned by all of them due to considerable
environmental problems, the lack of any tangible benefits
and major concerns about nuclear proliferation.
 
 <BR><BR>
<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:</B>
<P> Kate Johnston in Amsterdam on +31.20.523.62.16. or mobile +31.653.41.79.47

<P><B>or</B>

<P> Simon Carroll in Geneva on  +41.21.728.52.25.

