<HEAD><TITLE>GREENPEACE OPPOSES COMPROMISE ON 'PEACEFUL' NUCLEAR EXPLOSIONS</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">

<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60 VALIGN=TOP></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>
        
<H3>FOR IMMEDIATE  RELEASE<BR>
 
GREENPEACE OPPOSES COMPROMISE ON 'PEACEFUL' NUCLEAR EXPLOSIONS: "Special Treatment" would undermine test ban.
 </H3>
<B>GENEVA, 3 June 1996</B>    Greenpeace today expressed opposition to any special compromise that would leave open the possibility for so called 'peaceful nuclear explosions' under a Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty. The organisation called on all the nations taking part in the negotiations at the Conference on Disarmament to oppose such a move because "special treatment" for
peaceful nuclear explosions would undermine the effectiveness of the nuclear test ban.
 <P>
"The main purpose of a nuclear test ban is to prohibit all nuclear explosions of any size for any purpose whatsoever", said Greenpeace spokesperson Josh Handler.  "Any door left open for peaceful nuclear explosions (PNEs), is simply a quick
exit from a true and effective nuclear test ban treaty. All countries should reject any such compromise."
 <P>
Only China is insisting that peaceful nuclear explosions should not be prohibited. Recent reports indicate that China might accept a compromise that would prohibit PNEs for now, but would require the treaty to review PNEs in 10 years time.
 <P>
"Giving special treatment to PNEs in the treaty is unnecessary and dangerous.   Unnecessary because the current draft treaty already states that any issue can be brought up at the review conference in 10 years. Dangerous, because giving special status to PNEs and leaving open the possibility that they could be
conducted in the future, would undermine the effectiveness of the treaty    a peaceful nuclear explosion can be used to gain important information for developing nuclear weapons."
 <P>
China has stated that it does not want to ban peaceful nuclear explosions as it may need to conduct these in the future as part of its industrial development.  While other countries have conducted peaceful nuclear explosions in the past,
the practice has been abandoned by all of them due to considerable environmental problems, the lack of any tangible benefits and major concerns about nuclear proliferation.
 <P>
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:</B> <BR>
Kate Johnston in Amsterdam on<BR>
+31.20.523.62.16. or mobile +31.653.41.79.47 or Simon Carroll in Geneva on +41.21.728.52.25.
<P>
<B>GREENPEACE FACT SHEET ON PEACEFUL NUCLEAR EXPLOSIONS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST.</B>
