<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>


<H3>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>
 
GREENPEACE HEAD WELCOMES DRAFT NUCLEAR TEST BAN TREATY AND CALLS FOR RAPID
COMPLETION OF TALKS</H3>
<B>GENEVA, 28 May, 1996</B>    (GP) Greenpeace International Executive Director, Thilo
Bode, welcomed this afternoon's presentation of a complete draft nuclear
test ban treaty at the Conference on Disarmament as a 'major step' towards
completing the treaty on schedule by the end of June.<P>
Bode was especially pleased that the draft treaty ruled out all nuclear
explosions whatsoever, including so called Peaceful Nuclear Explosions (PNEs),
which China has been seeking to allow under the treaty.<P>
"A test ban treaty that allowed small nuclear tests or peaceful nuclear
explosions would not make any sense and could not be called 'comprehensive",
said Bode. "The draft presented today can form the basis of a treaty to end all
nuclear tests forever."<P>
Greenpeace considered that the introduction of the draft treaty by the Chairman
of the negotiations to be a very important development, he explained. 'With
this text as a starting point, it is possible to work towards completing the
treaty by the end of June', said Bode. 'Two things can undermine this   another
nuclear test by any country, or a failure of political will."<P>
Bode stated also that the environmental organisation's flagship,  the MV
Greenpeace, was continuing on its voyage to China. "At present our ship is
sailing to Manila, following a successful stopover in Sydney", said Bode. "From
Manila,  our ship intends to go to Shanghai with Greenpeace's message of peace
and a call to end all nuclear testing".<P>
 <HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:<BR> Simon Carroll in Geneva on  +41.21.728.52.25.<BR>
or Kate Johnston in Amsterdam on +31.20.523.62.16.<BR> or mobile +31.653.41.79.47.
 
</TD>
