<HEAD><TITLE>Selected Accidents Involving Nuclear Weapons 1950-1993</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60 VALIGN=TOP></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>
        



<H3>MV GREENPEACE TAKES ON NEW ANTI NUCLEAR CHALLENGE</H3>
 <P>
Sydney, Monday, 20 May 1996:   The MV Greenpeace, seized in 
protests against nuclear testing at Moruroa last year, 
arrived in Sydney this morning from New Zealand. The ship 
sails for China tomorrow on a new mission to urge China to 
end its nuclear testing programme.
<P> 
China is reported to be planning to conduct its 44th nuclear 
test imminently, and is blocking agreement of a ban on 
nuclear testing because of its insistence on  peaceful 
nuclear explosions  being excluded from the Comprehensive 
Test Ban Treaty currently being negotiated in Geneva.
 <P>
The MV Greenpeace sails as talks in Geneva reach crisis 
point with just seven weeks left to reach agreement on the 
treaty. Even if China does sign the treaty, Beijing has said 
it will continue to test until the treaty comes into force   
the timing of which is dependent on agreement between all 
the nuclear weapons states and other countries at the 
negotiating table. 
<P> 
Greenpeace nuclear campaigner Jean McSorley said:  China 
and the other nuclear powers must take responsibility for 
agreeing on a treaty. If Governments cannot agree to a 
treaty in June, we will not have a complete test ban this 
year,  she said.  They have only seven weeks left and our 
voyage to China aims to bring that urgency to world 
attention.
 <P>
 It is a timely mission for the ship as Greenpeace 
commemorates 25 years of campaigning against nuclear 
testing. We hope that this is the last time we have to set 
sail in order to achieve as end to nuclear testing,  said 
McSorley.
 <P>
There will be a media conference on board the MV Greenpeace 
at 10.30am today, Monday 20 May at Thames Street Wharf, Mort 
Bay, Balmain.
 <P>
The MV Greenpeace is then scheduled to depart Tuesday, May 
21, at approximately middy for Manila, en route to Shanghai 
on 13th/14th June.
 <P>
<B>Contact:<BR>
 Jean McSorley 568 3265 and 0419 745 547
<BR> Susan 
Cavanagh 04111 795 29.</B>
 <P>
Note: The ship will be open to the public.
 




</TABLE>
</TD>
</TR>
