<HEAD>
<TITLE>TIME RUNNING OUT FOR TEST BAN TREATY TALKS</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>


    <H3>GREENPEACE DECLARES UNITED NATIONS IN GENEVA A RADIOACTIVE
               EXCLUSION ZONE AS TEST BAN TALKS RESUME
</H3>
<B>GENEVA - 14 MAY 1996 (GP)</B> - Forty activists from Greenpeace
Switzerland established a 'radioactive exclusion zone' around the
Palais des Nations in Geneva this morning as the opening plenary
meeting of the second part of the Conference on Disarmament got
underway. Declaring the site 'contaminated by nuclear testing',
Greenpeace established a checkpoint at the entrance bearing the legend
"ALL NUCLEAR TESTS POLLUTE THE EARTH - BAN ALL TESTS NOW !".
<P>
The Conference on Disarmament resumes its talks on a
comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty this week, with just seven
weeks remaining for the negotiations if the treaty is to be
completed on schedule by the end of June. Unless this deadline
is met, the treaty will not be able to be signed this year. 
<P>
The Greenpeace 'checkpoint' with its mobile barrier established
an exclusion zone around the United Nations site which the
environmental organization declared "politically and
radioactively contaminated" in protest at the slow progress of
the negotiations.
<P>
"Because of nuclear weapons testing, numerous places around the
world are contaminated by radioactivity. Unless all nuclear
testing is stopped, this can only get worse.", said Wendl Hilti,
Greenpeace Switzerland's nuclear campaigner. "Here in Geneva the
diplomats are getting lost in the details and engage in endless
rhetoric. This approach risks failing to agree a treaty at all.
This cannot be allowed to happen - its time to complete a test
ban treaty which will prohibit all nuclear explosions." 
<P>
With the United States, United Kingdom, France and Russia
accepting that a ban should prohibit all nuclear tests,
Greenpeace sees the position of China and its plans to conduct
further nuclear tests as the single biggest barrier to the
completion of the negotiations.
<P>
Since 1964, China has exploded 43 nuclear tests at Lop Nor and
has developed the fourth largest nuclear arsenal in the world.
Its nuclear weapons have a combined power equivalent to 17,000 Hiroshima bombs.
<P>
<I>For further information:</I><BR>
Greenpeace Communications, London, +44.171.833.06.00<BR>
In Geneva: Wendl Hilti, Greenpeace Switzerland, 077-619.171
(mobile);<BR> Clement Tolusso, Greenpeace Switzerland, 079-213.41.06;<BR>
Joshua Handler, Greenpeace International, 022-732.80.95.<BR>

</TD>
