<HEAD><TITLE>TIME RUNNING OUT FOR TEST BAN TREATY TALKS</TITLE></HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="000000" TEXT="FFFFFF" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="00DEFF" ALINK="00FF00">
<A HREF="index.html"><FONT SIZE=2>[Home]</FONT></A>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=512 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=60></TD>
<TD WIDTH=462>





                                  

	<H3>TIME RUNNING OUT FOR TEST BAN TREATY TALKS<BR>
	Greenpeace Sails For China as China Prepares Next Nuclear Test</H3>
 
<B>GENEVA, 13 May 1996</B> -  (GP) Only seven weeks remain for an agreement on a ban on all nuclear weapons testing or the opportunity could be lost forever, Greenpeace said today at a press conference a day before the Geneva based Conference on Disarmament resumed.
<P>
With China remaining as the only country intending to conduct more nuclear tests -  the first of which is expected any day -  Greenpeace's Xavier Pastour announced that the organization will send its vessel, the MV Greenpeace, to China.  The vessel will depart on 15 May from Auckland, New Zealand, having completed repairs after its protests against French nuclear tests last year, he said.  Pastour, who lead the same vessel into the French nuclear testing site at Moruroa, will be aboard the vessel as Campaign Coordinator.
 <P>
"Millions of people around the world expect an end to nuclear tests now," said Josh Handler, Disarmament Coordinator for Greenpeace. "If Governments cannot agree to a treaty by June, we will not have a test ban this year. They have only seven weeks left. The clock is ticking."
<P>
According to Greenpeace, only a few obstacles remain to achieving the treaty, but a handful of countries, especially those with nuclear weapons, are refusing to make the compromises needed to gain agreement.  Of the declared nuclear weapons states, only China is planning  further underground test explosions. It is expected to conduct  its 44th nuclear test in May or June this year while CTBT talks are under way.
<P> 
"This treaty can be won or lost in discussions between the White House, the Kremlin and Beijing," said Handler. "It remains to be seen whether Governments make the commitments in Geneva that will match their rhetoric of recent months."
<P>
After leaving New Zealand, the MV Greenpeace will visit Sydney and Manila before arriving off the coast of Shanghai in early June to demonstrate the region's opposition to China's test plans.  This would mark Greenpeace's first ship visit to mainland China.<BR>
	ends<P>
<B>Contact:</B><BR>
Blair Palese, Greenpeace Communications, London: +44171-833-0600<BR>
In Geneva, Joshua Handler: +4121 732-8095, Simon Carroll +4121-728-5225, Michael Kuhn of Greenpeace Germany: +49 17238 18146<BR>
Clemens Tolusson, Greenpeace Switzerland: +4121-922-1222 or on mobile +4179213 4106
</TD>
