<center>
<h1>Join us and help save the natural world</h1>

If you would like <font color="#00AA00" size="+1">Greenpeace</font> to send you a subscription form, please
fill out the <a href="#form">form</a> below and submit it.<br>
<hr></center><br clear=all>
<p><hr>
<center>
<h2>A message from</h2>
<img alt="County Kildare Supporting Greenpeace" width=475 height=168 src="images/kildare.gif"></center>
<font size="+1">
Greenpeace Ireland is not wealthy. Greenpeace Ireland does not accept money from Government or Industry, and so it is a truly independent watchdog for the protection of the environment. Greenpeace Ireland does not recieve financial assistance from Greenpeace International, in order that the organisation can expand into new territories in the Far East. <i>It is only as strong as the support it gets in this country</i>.<p>

Greenpeace Ireland relies totally on us, the people of Ireland, to fund it's campaigns. Right now the campaign is the <a href="clean_water/index.html">Millennium Clean Water Campaign 2000</a>, to respond to the serious threat of pollution to Ireland's drinking water. Our waterways are polluted from many sources, including agricultural and industrial wastes, sewage effluent, leachate from dumps and runoff from forestry and peat harvesting practices.<p>

Greenpeace Ireland has called for our help to ensure that Ireland will have clean water for the year 2000 and beyond.<p>

The people of County Kildare are responding to that call with the launch of the scheme &quot;County Kildare Supporting Greenpeace&quot;, whereby small groups of active members throughout the county will organise celebrations, fundraisers and special events in support of Greenpeace Ireland. Please support our scheme and become an active member of Greenpeace.<p></font>
<hr>
<p>

<table border=0 cellpadding=20>
<tr valign=top><td width=50%>
<h2>Think about Greenpeace and what images come to mind?</h2>
...tiny inflatable dinghies, struggling with gigantic waves, trying to stop the dumping of radioactive waste off Russia or prevent the slaughter of whales in Antartica? Or people swathed in protective clothing and masks blocking pipes to stop gallons of poison polluting our seas? Or climbers unfurling a banner on a toxic waste incinerator in Cork to draw attention to another abuse of the environment?<p>
<h3>Environmental crimes are commited simply because nothing is done to stop them. That's why Greenpeace believes in non-violent direct action. When the safety of the planet is in the balance...</h3><br></td>
<td width=50%>
<h2>...ACTIONS SPEAK LOUDER</h2><br>
Since 1971 Greenpeace has been at the cutting edge, getting it's hands dirty, taking risks and taking on governments and big business.<br>
As well as peaceful direct action, Greenpeace lobbies governments and industrialists and gathers evidence to build legal cases to take through the courts. Greenpeace enables it's supports to voice their dissent, as tens of thousands did to protest against THORP, the nuclear reprocessing plant at Sellafield.<p>
<h2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Whatever it takes, Greenpeace will continue to defend the earth through non-violent direct action.</FONT></h2></td></tr></table>
<h2>Who's behind Greenpeace?</h2>
<h3>PEOPLE LIKE YOU</h3>
4,500,000 supporters worldwide make Greenpeace what it is. 4,500,000 ordinary people playing their part in the fight for clean air, fresh water, the protection of wildlife and a safe and nuclear free planet.<br>
It is Greenpeace policy not to accept money from corporations nor from governments. Greenpeace is not affiliated to any political organisation. We refuse to compromise our independence so that whenever the environment is threatened, we are free to target our campaigns at whoever is responsible.<br>
To have a chance, Greenpeace needs everyone who is worried by what is happening to get behind us. Whether we succeed or fail depends on the commitment of people like you. Every time one more person joins our supporters, Greenpeace gets bigger and stronger.<br>


