<html>
<head>
<title>Millennium Clean Water Campaign</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<h1>Millennium Clean Water Campaign</h1>
<h3><a href="../liffey/index.html">The Anna Liffey Campaign</a>
<br>
<a href="../shannon/index.html">The Brad&aacute;n Feasa Shannon Celebration Tour</a></h3>

<img src="images/millennium.gif" height=315 width=296 alt="Millennium Clean Water Campaign"></center><p>
The Greenpeace Ireland Clean Water Campaign, launched on the River Shannon this year flagged the
need to ensure that the Irish people have clean water coming into the new millennium and beyond.<p>

The greatest legacy we can leave to future generations is clean, fresh water. Our delicate inland water-ways are suffering under the onslaught of a concoction of polluting discharges. Sewage, slurry, industrial wastes, dump leachate, fertilisers, forestry and peat bog runoff, all make their way into our waterways.<p>

Nutrient levels in the water are increasing. Public health is at risk. Water sports enthusiasts have seen events cancelled. The past months have seen a number of major fish kills in the Shannon alone. We can't ignore the warning signals.<p>

Its time we shouted STOP. Everyone needs to take responsibility for protecting the water. Our very survival depends on it.<p>

Greenpeace have called, and will continue to call, on the government to take an integrated, catchment based approach to policies aimed at protecting our rivers. Greenpeace have shown that the solutions are available, reed bed technology for the treatment of slurry and sewage, dry or low flush toilets, phosphate-free detergents. Let's use them.<p>

Greenpeace are urging individuals, communities, everyone, to take ownership of their rivers once again. Celebrate what they were and what they can be once again. Over the next four years
Greenpeace will be celebrating many more of Ireland's river systems. Through "Living Downstream", our school education project, River-watch groups and our water quality database, we are strengthening our role as an independent watchdog for the environment.<p>

Join with us by beginning to celebrate your river now.<p>
<hr>

The Millennium Clean Water Campaign was launched in March 1996 on board the Brad&aacute;n Feasa.
Over a two week period Greenpeace travelled up the length of the Shannon - celebrating the river, listening to the people and offering solutions.<p>

Over 500,000 people reside in the Shannon catchment. Over one fifth of this population receive their drinking water directly from the rivers. A vital point. Greenpeace strongly support those who are willing to take the initiative and begin protecting the health of our water. Viable solutions have been demonstrated.<p>

The excess input of plant nutrients, nitrogen, potassium and, especially phosphorus, through sewage, slurry and fertiliser discharges, has resulted in many of the problems the waterways are facing this summer. The growth of toxic algae has resulted in the deaths of animals and the cancellation of water sports events. Delicate ecosystems within rivers and lakes are at breaking point, and the stress is beginning to show.<p>

The solutions presented by Greenpeace are not new, in fact other European countries have been using some of them for years. The promotion of constructed wetlands, or reed beds, as a clean and efficient alternative to conventional sewage treatment plants is one possibility.<p>

There are already a number of constructed wetlands in operation in Ireland. The first one was constructed for the Curragh Camp during the 1800's.<p>

A constructed wetland, is an artificially created ecosystem. Reeds, lilies and other wetland plants are planted over' layers of clay and gravel beds. The waste water' from both slurry and sewage can be passed through the head of the reed bed. As it filters through the underlying layers, the plants take nutrients up out of the water. Bacteria in the water attach on to the clay particles, leaving a discharge equal to that coming out of a conventional tertiary sewage treatment facility. At 20% of the cost of conventional treatment systems, constructed wetlands are a viable alternative.<p>

<b>A nation-wide ban on phosphate-based detergents.</b><p>

Up to one sixth of the phosphorus, (the plant nutrient causing many of the problems in Irish water-ways), in waste water comes from fabric washing processes.<p>

Many European countries including Belgium and Germany, have reduced the market for phosphate-based detergents through legislation, voluntary agreements and public pressure on detergent manufacturers.<p>

Phosphate-free detergents are available. Public pressure on supermarkets can make these alternatives more readily available. This is one solution that everyone can be involved in implementing! Buy phosphate-free detergents, and get everyone you know to buy them.<p>

How can you tell if they are phosphate-based or not?<p>

Look at the ingredients box found on the side of any detergent pack. It will list a number of different ingredients like surfactants and bleaching agents. The bulk of most powders is made up of a substance known as a 'builder', which assists in removing dirt from fabrics. Phosphate is used as a builder. If it is contained in your pack it will be listed. Often up to 30% of the pack will be phosphate. Look for packs containing an alternative builder, called zeolite.<p>

<b>A reduction in agricultural wastes through a move to sustainable agriculture</b><p>

Up to two thirds of phosphorus entering our water ways can be attributed to agricultural sources. Severe pollution events in the past have resulted from bad management practices involving slurry disposal. There are guidelines for good practice now available through Teagasc aimed at improving the way farms are managed to reduce pollutant sources.<p>

By integrating solutions into a catchment-based management policy for all waterways, we can go a long way towards ensuring clean water for the next generation.<p>

</body>

