<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace Ships Released</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#0068B5"><basefont size=3>
<CENTER>
<img align=left src="images/25yearssmall.gif" width=150 height=131>
<IMG SRC="images/25yearst.gif" ALT="25 Years of Greenpeace" WIDTH=475 HEIGHT=42>
<br>
<br>
<img src="images/endnukeage.gif" width=437 height=56></CENTER><br clear=all>

Since the first Greenpeace ship, the Phyllis Cormack, sailed 
into the US atomic test site at Amchitka, Alaska in 1971, the 
campaign to rid the world of nuclear weapons has been a mainstay 
of Greenpeace's work. Combined with international work to end 
nuclear energy generation and to stop nuclear waste dumping and 
reprocessing, Greenpeace is determined to END THE NUCLEAR AGE.<hr>
<p>
<img align=right width=402 height=41 src="images/journeys.gif">
<br clear=all>
<FONT COLOR="#FB8D10">In 1972, David McTaggart, now Honorary Chair of Greenpeace 
International, began what would become a series of voyages to 
the French Test Site at Moruroa Atoll in the South Pacific. 
Sailing his yacht "Vega", McTaggart and his crew spent 20 days 
at the test site before finally being detained by the French 
authorities.<p>

The next year McTaggart returned to Moruroa. This time Vega was 
boarded by French commandos and McTaggart was badly beaten. 
Photos of the beatings smuggled to the worlds press brought 
international outrage to bear on France.<p>

Greenpeace ships have returned to Moruroa consistently to try to 
bring an end to France's testing programme. But it was in 1985 
that the issue really came to international attention. While 
preparing to set sail to Moruroa the Greenpeace flagship, 
Rainbow Warrior, was blown up by French secret service agents in 
Auckland, New Zealand resulting in the death of photographer, 
Fernando Pereira.<p>

This did not deter Greenpeace who immediately sent the MV 
Greenpeace in its place. Right up to 1995 when the replacement 
Rainbow Warrior and MV Greenpeace were brutally seized by French 
commandos at Moruroa, Greenpeace crews have borne witness to the 
plight of the South Pacific.<p>


But it is not only French testing which has been the focus of 
Greenpeace campaigns. Actions at the US test site in Nevada, at 
the Soviet Union's Test Site in Novaya Zemlya and in 1995, the 
first ever Greenpeace action in China, have been central to the 
Greenpeace aim of achieving a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.</FONT> 
<hr>
<p>
<img width=460 height=36 src="images/react.gif"><br>

Closer to home the Greenpeace Nuclear Campaign has focused on 
the dangers presented by nuclear reprocessing at Sellafield in 
England and LaHague in France. <p>

Greenpeace has blocked shipments of nuclear waste to and from 
the plants, it has consistently fought legal battles against 
reprocessing, it has lobbied around the world for an end to this 
nightmare and most dramatically, in 1987 two Greenpeace members 
were jailed in Britain for blocking the Sellafield discharge 
pipeline.<hr><p>

<img align=right width=444 height=34 src="images/herecomesun.gif"><br clear=all>
<FONT COLOR="#FB8D10">
Now Greenpeace is working to make nuclear power obsolete. 
Intensive research and lobbying around the world to promote the 
solar alternative is central to the Greenpeace Campaign. Ten 
years on from the world's worst nuclear disaster at Chernobyl it 
is time to start the Solar Revolution. </font><hr>

<FONT COLOR="#0000A0"><CENTER><h2>RAINBOW WARRIOR FREE</h2></CENTER></FONT>

The Greenpeace flagship Rainbow Warrior sailed from Hao atoll into 
international waters on 19th March, five months after being seized 
by the French at Moruroa.
The Rainbow Warrior and the MV Greenpeace were both detained at the 
Hao military base, while the Vega, La Ribaude and Manutea were 
released from captivity at Moruroa a week before.


The captains of both the Rainbow Warrior and the  MV Greenpeace 
were under pressure from the French authorities to leave Hao as 
soon as possible.  The skipper of the Rainbow Warrior, Andy Troia, 
would not leave until the MV Greenpeace was released, so the two 
ships could sail together for safety reasons.
"Our ships are in bad disrepair and we have not had adequate 
time to check all the systems on board," he said.  "Both ships 
will require extensive repairs before returning to campaign 
work, and Greenpeace will be able to decide their destinations 
only after seeing how they handle at sea." 
<hr>
