<html>
<head><title>Peaceful Nuclear Co-Operation Agreement ?</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#E1E8E6" link="#00a000" vlink="#00a000">
<CENTER><h1>Peaceful Nuclear Co-operation Agreement?</h1>
<hr width=70%>
<table border=0  width=70% cellpadding=10><tr><td align=center>
<font size=+1>You can let the Government know that you support Greenpeace and oppose the opening of negotiations on this new nuclear deal between Japan and the EU by filling out <a href="form.html">this form</a>.<br></font>
</td></tr></table>
<hr width=70%>
<h2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Negotiations between Japan and the EU<br>
 to begin during the Irish EU Presidency</FONT></h2>
</CENTER>

<center><table bgcolor="#f0f0f0" border=1 width=80% cellpadding=10><tr><td align=center>
<i><font size=+1>Talks to agree a 'Peaceful Nuclear Co-operation Agreement' between
the European Union and Japan could soon begin. Such an Agreement
would enable nuclear trade between Europe and Japan to expand more
easily.<p>

Greenpeace sees this proposal as a further threat to the
environment and to nuclear non-proliferation, in that it will assist the
expansion of the global trade in nuclear weapons materials. This cannot
be in the interest of Ireland or the EU as a whole.</font></i></td></tr></table>
</center>
<br>

<font size=+1>
The European Commission and Japan have begun informal talks with the
objective of securing a 'Peaceful Nuclear Co-operation Agreement' between
Japan and the European Union.<p>

If, and once, official negotiations are embarked upon, the talks will be based
on the <a href="http://www.cec.lu/en/comm/euratom/euratom.html">EURATOM</a> Treaty. This Treaty, the European Atomic Energy
Treaty, is one of the original three Treaties of the Common Market.<p>

Before the Commission can begin formal negotiations with Japan, however,
they must first get the approval of the EU Council of Ministers. This matter
may be on the Council's agenda as early as October. If Council approves,
then the Commission will most likely open negotiations with Japan before
the end of the year, i.e. during the Irish Presidency.<p>

BNFL (operators of the Sellafield site) are desperate to secure new large
contracts to supply plutonium-fuel to Japan. If this Aggreement proceeds then
Japan will take it as a signal that the EU, including Ireland, supports
plutonium reprocessing and nuclear fuel fabrication.<p>

Aside from the day-to-day environmental risks posed by Sellafield, this
agreement is inherently linked to the transportation of plutonium fuel from
Europe to Japan. This is most likely to be by sea, but may be by air.<p>

Ireland must stop this happening. The decision at Council will most likely
need to be by qualified majority in line with Article 101 of Euratom which
states:</font><p>

<CITE>&quot;The Community may, within the limits of its powers and jurisdiction, enter into
obligations by concluding agreements or contracts with a third State, an
international organization or a national of a third State.<p>

Such agreements or contracts shall be negotiated by the Commission in
accordance with the directives of the Council: they shall be concluded by the
Commission with the approval of the Council, which shall act by a <B>qualified
majority</B>&quot;.
</CITE><p>

<font size=+1>Qualified Majority means 62 out of 87 votes in favour of the Mandate for
the Commission. Therefore, Ireland will have to enlist the support of other
Member States to stop this.</font><p>

<CENTER><table bgcolor="#f0f0f0" border=1 cellpadding=10><tr><td align=center><b>Voting in the Council of Ministers</b><br><br>
Member States' votes are weighted on the basis of population size as follows:<br><br>

10 votes to Germany, France, Italy, UK<br>
8 votes to Spain<br>
5 votes to Belgium, Netherlands, Portugal, Greece<br>
4 votes to Austria, Sweden<br>
3 votes to Finland, Denmark, <b>Ireland</b><br>
2 votes to Luxembourg<br><br>

making 87 votes in total. Adoption of a proposal from the Commission by qualified<br>

majority requires 62 votes out of the 87.<br>
</td></tr></table></CENTER>

<p><font size=+1>
These negotiations, if given the go ahead, will be conducted on behalf of all
EU member states, not just the nuclear states. Ireland must seek support to
oppose the Mandate. To do anything else would be hypocritical. Ireland's
endorsement of a so-called 'Peaceful Nuclear Co-operation Agreement' with
Japan would be rightly interpreted as contrary to its historical role in
promoting effective nuclear non-proliferation and in calling for an end to
reprocessing at Sellafield/THORP.</font><p>

<center>
<b><font size=+2>Greenpeace demands that the Irish EU Presidency does all within its
power to ensure that no such deal is negotiated.</font></b><br>


<hr width=70%>
<table border=0  width=70% cellpadding=10><tr><td align=center>
<font size=+1>You can let the Government know that you support Greenpeace and oppose the opening of negotiations on this new nuclear deal between Japan and the EU by filling out <a href="form.html">this form</a>.<br></font>
</td></tr></table>
<hr width=70%></center>

Greenpeace Ireland, 44 Upper Mount Street, Dublin 2<br>
Tel: 01 6619836; Fax: 01-6605258<br>
e-mail: <a href="mailto:greenpeace@iol.ie">greenpeace@iol.ie</a><p>
