<html>
<head>
<title>Chernobyl - TEN Years On</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFDECE" text="#000020">
<center>
<table>
<tr>
<td><img src="images/chernobyl.jpg"></td>
<td><img src="images/ten.gif"></td>
<td><img src="images/yearson.jpg"></td>
</table>

Please visit the <font size=+1><a href=http://www.greenpeace.org/~comms/nukes/ctbt/index.html>Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty</a></font> page.<p>
</center>
<table cellspacing=4>
<tr valign=top><td>
At a Press Conference to mark the 10th anniversary of the Chernobyl 
accident Greenpeace said that unless governments world-wide 
begin a rapid programme to shut down all nuclear reactors another  
accident, another Chernobyl,  will  occur. The statement was by 
two  Ukrainians  -- Natalia Proebrazhenska, a scientist and 
Volodymyr Usatenko, an engineer and politician -- who travelled to 
Ireland as part of the Greenpeace  Chernobyl 10th Anniversary 
Testimonies Tour.<p>

Both  Ms  Proebrazhenska and Mr Usatenko spoke of the  devastation  -
-  the deaths, the human health problems, the contamination of 
agricultural land and  drinking water,  and  the  widespread  fear of 
having  children  --  caused  by  the Chernobyl accident 10 years 
ago.<p>

Ms Proebrazhenska is concerned about the fate of the children and has  
been involved since May 1986 when she assisted in the evacuation  of  
children from Kiev. Over the past ten years she has devoted her life 
to helping with medical  research, getting medical equipment and 
supplies, and  to  working closely with sick and dying children.
"Chernobyl continues to cause much agony and suffering. It is only 
now that we are beginning to see its real effects," she said. "I now 
work for an end to  nuclear power globally. I do not wish to see this 
horror happen  again, anywhere.<p>

Volodymyr  Usatenko,  a  Deputy of the Ukrainian  Parliament  and  a  
power engineer  by training, became involved in the Chernobyl issue 
in 1987  when he spent 60 days at the plant with the military 
reserves assisting with the clean up of the accident site.</td>
<td>"The present post-Chernobyl plight of Ukraine is an example to the 
world of the  consequences of nuclear power. The question is not 
whether  French  or American or UK reactors are of a better design 
than those of Chernobyl, but whether  we  are  willing to live and 
die with a  dangerous  technology,  a technology out of control," he 
said.<p>

John Bowler, Campaigns Director of Greenpeace Ireland, drew  the  
links between  Chernobyl  and the threat posed to Ireland  by  
Britain's  nuclear stations.<p>

"Everyone  in  Ireland  knows of Sellafield and  its  associated  
risks  to Ireland,  but we must remember that there are many nuclear 
power plants  on Britain's  west  coast, bordering the Irish Sea. A 
serious accident at any of these would be disastrous for Ireland. 
According to the Radiological Protection Institute the Chernobyl 
accident could cause up to 25 fatal cancers here over a 70-year 
period. Imagine the consequences to  Ireland in the event of an 
accident at a British plant. Wylfa in  North Wales for instance is 
less than one hundred miles away," he said.<p>


Ten  years  after  the Chernobyl accident, is now more apparent than 
ever that nuclear power is an ultimate problem, rather than the 
ultimate solution.<p>

In its Testimonies Report Greenpeace  offers  first  hand  accounts  
by  those  who experienced  the Chernobyl disaster and now live with 
the  consequences. Testimonies  is a stark reminder of the real price 
humanity has to pay  for nuclear technology.<p></td></tr></table>
<hr>

<table border=1><tr width=75%><td>
<font size=7> >       </font><b><i><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#004080">New Energy Deal</FONT></b></i>
</td></tr></table>
Greenpeace  believes  that  now  is the time to build  a  future  
based  on realistic,  safe  and  sustainable energy sources  that  do  
not  carry  the environmental,  health and financial costs associated 
with nuclear  energy. The operational  Chernobyl  reactors  generate  
about  5%  of   Ukraine's electricity.  A new energy study released 
by Greenpeace earlier  this  week shows  that increased energy 
conservation, wind power and the  transfer  of surplus energy from 
western Europe could remove the country's dependency on Chernobyl. 
Greenpeace has estimated that wind-based energy production alone 
could eventually produce between 10 and 15% of the Ukraine's 
electricity needs.
<p>
Now is the time to start to implement a New Energy  Deal. Nuclear 
power is not  safe and  it is certainly not sustainable. A world-wide 
nuclear phase-out is  the only way forward.
<hr>
</center>
</body>
</DOC>
