<html>
<head>
<title>Greenpeace USA Fisheries Campaign: Dolphin-Safe Tuna?</title>
<META Name="description" Content="Greenpeace Fisheries Campaign information updates.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="tuna dolphins Greenpeace USA environment NGO clean earth water air action protest">
<link rev="made" href:"mailto: jay.townsend@wdc.greenpeace.org">
</head>
<body bgcolor="FF FF FF" text="#00 00 80" link="#00 80 00" 
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/bio_upd.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a></center>
<h1>A Dolphin-Safe Label That Really Means It</h1>
<img align="right" vspace="10" hspace="10" width="324" height="215" src="pix/tunadolp.gif"
ALT="photo of dolphins surrounded by tuna net"></img>
<p>
Over the past few months, there have been many questions raised
regarding Greenpeace's support for U.S. legislation and
international agreements which address the killing of dolphins in
tuna fisheries.  To set the record straight, there is a definite
number of dolphins Greenpeace believes is acceptable to kill
during tuna fishing: <i>ZERO</i>.  This has been our position for 25
years and remains our position today.
<p> 
We believe that this goal of reducing dolphin deaths related to
tuna fishing to zero can only be achieved through international
cooperation.  One country acting alone cannot save the world's
dolphins, oceans, atmosphere, or forests.  Yet, in the case of
the "tuna-dolphin" issue, as it is known, this is exactly what
the United States has tried to do.  The <b>"Marine Mammal Protection
Act (MMPA) of 1972"</b> was passed by Congress to address the problem
of dolphin kills in the tuna fishery of the Eastern Tropical
Pacific Ocean (ETP).  While tremendous progress has been made,
Greenpeace believes that the only way to eliminate dolphin kills 
is through a strong international commitment by all the countries
fishing for tuna in the region.  
<p> 
In the ETP, Greenpeace supports a new international strategy for
saving dolphins from tuna nets, while ensuring a healthy and
viable tuna fishery for generations to come.  Greenpeace believes
the current U.S. "dolphin-safe" law falls far short of
accomplishing these goals.  Moreover, Greenpeace is concerned
that the public is being lead to believe that all tuna bearing
the "dolphin-safe" label is caught without killing
dolphins, that "dolphin-safe" tuna is environmentally-friendly,
and that the problem of dolphin kills in tuna fisheries has been
solved.  These things are simply not true.  
<p>

<h3>Background</h3>
<p>  
In the 1950s, a new fishing technology emerged, the purse-seine
net, that enabled ships to fish more intensively and travel
farther out to sea to catch tuna for a growing market. This net 
is deployed around a school of fish and then pulled tight like a 
drawstring on a bag, capturing thousands of pounds of fish at
a time.  Today, more than ninety percent of the world's canned
tuna is caught with this technology.  
<p> 
In 1959, in the ETP, the U.S. tuna fleet found that the largest, 
most valuable tuna swam beneath dolphins.  The U.S. fleet began
the practice of encirclement of dolphins to catch the tuna. By
the early 1960s, U.S. purse-seiners fishing for tuna in the ETP
were killing hundreds of thousands of dolphins annually.        
For decades, Greenpeace has campaigned aggressively on the 
"tuna-dolphin" issue.  Working with other concerned organizations throughout
the 1980s and 1990s, our efforts finally paid off, thrusting the
issue to the forefront of the international environmental agenda.
The U.S. public, the largest consumers of tuna in the world,
began to take notice.  Through citizen action, consumer boycotts,
and other political activities, laws were passed in the United
States to help put a stop to this unnecessary killing.  
<p> 
In 1988, Congress first used economic pressure for dolphin
conservation by adding a new provision to the <b>MMPA</b>, requiring
other fleets in the ETP to kill dolphins at a rate no higher than
the U.S. fleet in order to import tuna into the United States. 
This measure was a complete failure.  Within two years, all other
fishing nations had been embargoed, and dolphin deaths and the
practice of encirclement of dolphins to catch tuna continued.  
<p> 
Criteria for use of the "dolphin-safe" label was enacted by 
Congress as an amendment to the <b>MMPA</b> in 1990.  This legislation
prohibited the practice of encirclement of dolphins in the ETP in
order for that tuna to be labeled as "dolphin-safe."  
<p> 
Another amendment to the <b>MMPA</b> was added in 1992 directing the
United States to negotiate a five-year moratorium on the practice
of encirclement of dolphins with the other countries active in
the ETP.  If the moratorium was not agreed by June 1994, the
United States would ban the sale of non-"dolphin-safe" tuna
within its borders.  
<p> 
But the threat of a closed U.S. market proved unsuccessful, and no 
moratorium was agreed upon.  However, the fishing countries in the
ETP did come together <i>VOLUNTARILY</i> and agree to reduce dolphin
kills on a seven-year schedule.  Under this cooperative 
agreement, dolphin deaths have decreased dramatically, numbering
only 3300 in 1995.    
<p> 
<h3>Is It Really "Dolphin-Safe"?</h3> 
<p> 
The "dolphin-safe" label, by definition, was intended to end the practice of 
encirclement of dolphins to catch tuna.  It has failed to do so.  While the <b>La Jolla 
Agreement</b> has reduced dolphin deaths by more 90 percent since 1990, the "dolphin-safe" 
law has only reduced encirclement by just over 25 percent.  Moreover, this reduction 
in encirclement is attributed to the mass exodus of the U.S. tuna fleet who left the 
ETP to avoid the "dolphin-safe" laws. Unfortunately, other fishing fleets continue 
to encircle dolphins with impunity. 
<p> 
The "dolphin-safe" label we have come to trust has been
manipulated by the Starkist, Bumblebee and Chicken of the Sea
companies into a mere marketing tool to sell more tuna.  The
canners have used the label to imply that all catches are
verified as "dolphin-safe" through an airtight enforcement and
monitoring scheme.  This is far from the truth.  
<p> 
In the ETP, where less than 20 percent of the world's canned tuna is caught,
verification is the tightest, with independent observers on every
boat complemented by dockside observers at the cannery.  For the
rest of the world's canned tuna, the burden of verification rests
solely with dockside monitors who are forced to accept the word
of the skipper as to whether the tuna is "dolphin-safe." 
<p> 
Many of the transnational corporations involved in tuna fishing 
have moved their tuna boats and processing facilities to areas
where there is less regulation than in the ETP.  Most U.S. tuna
boats have been sold to other countries or moved to other regions
to avoid the restrictions of the "dolphin-safe" law and U.S.
legal jurisdiction.  As a result, most of the tuna canning
production has moved from U.S. territories in the South Pacific
to Southeast Asia where monitoring and enforcement of these U.S.-
based policies is almost impossible.   
<p> 
Some vessels fishing for tuna outside of the ETP evade observer
requirements by fishing in another part of the Pacific for most
of their trip, and "topping off" their catch in the ETP on their
way home.  Tuna from that entire trip would then be considered
"dolphin-safe." 
<p> 
In other regions, large tuna transport ships complicate efforts
to track "dolphin-safe" tuna by taking to port the tuna from
several boats from different ocean regions.  Once on land,
determining which tuna is "dolphin-safe" gets even more
complicated as "dolphin-safe" tuna are mixed with loads from
other transport boats. By the time it reaches your grocery store, 
there is little surety that it is actually "dolphin-safe."       
<p>
Finally, it is also important to note that in the ETP and
elsewhere, dolphins have never been the only creatures killed by
vessels purse-seining for mature tuna.  Millions of juvenile
tuna, shark, sea turtles and billfish are taken, with no effort
made to reduce the take or assess the full impact of this bycatch
on the marine environment.  It is clear that even so-called
"dolphin-safe" tuna still causes environmental damage.   
<p> 
<h3>Greenpeace's Solution</h3>
<p>
The "dolphin-safe" label did what was necessary at the time of
its passage:  it brought much needed attention to this issue. But
the current law has gone as far as it can.  However easy or
appealing it may sound to simply shut down the ETP tuna fishery,
this is not a viable option.  Doing so would raise questions of
survival for fishing communities and the need to feed a growing
world population.  Tuna is the leading seafood consumed in the
United States, and a renewable protein source for poor and low-
income persons the world over.
<p> 
There needs to be an international agreement, binding on all
fishing countries through national laws, that will protect not
only dolphins, but other marine species as well as the long-term
sustainability of the tuna stocks.  Resolving these problems in
the ETP would set an important precedent that could lead to
similar agreements for all regions where tuna are caught.    
Therefore, Greenpeace believes the time has come for replacing
unilateral embargoes and the single-country approach with strong
international regulations.  With the leadership of our sister
Greenpeace offices in Latin America -- Mexico, Chile, Brazil,
Guatemala and Argentina --  Greenpeace participated in
discussions with those countries fishing in the ETP, the result
of which was the <a href="#panama"><b>Panama Declaration</b></a>.  
<p> 
The declaration brought all of the countries fishing for tuna in
the ETP to the table, and is a critical first step toward
creating a legally-enforceable international agreement to address
the environmental problems in the ETP tuna fishery.  The 
consensus support for the <a href="#panama"><b>Panama Declaration</b></a> indicated a
strong willingness among the fishing countries to negotiate and adopt an
agreement that would:
<ul> 
<li>Commit all countries fishing for tuna to reduce dolphin deaths 
towards zero;</li>
<li>Be legally binding, and supported by national laws;</li>   
<li>Ensure stronger compliance and enforcement measures rather    
than the current voluntary compliance scheme;</li>
<li>Require mandatory reporting and enforcement measures to be    
shared with all fishing nations;</li>
<li>Protect already depleted dolphin populations;</li>
<li>Ensure healthier marine ecosystems by protecting dolphins as   
well as juvenile tuna and other marine species caught in the   
course of fishing operations;</li>
<li>Provide incentives for fishers who do not kill dolphins; and</li> 
<li>allow the U.S. to impose future trade sanctions on nations failing to 
live up to their commitment to protect dolphins.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<h3>Greenpeace's Position On Current Legislation</h3>
<p>
During its final days in October, the 104th Congress failed to take 
final action on <b>H.R.2823/S.1420</b>, <b>"The International Dolphin 
Conservation Act,"</b> legislation that would have fulfilled U.S. 
commitments under the <a href="#panama"><b>Panama Declaration</b></a>. While the House of
Representatives had voted to approve the legislation by a 316-107 margin 
in July, the U.S. Senate was unable to bring it up for a vote prior to
its adjournment.  while it's too early to tell what the prospects are for 
passage in the 105th Congress, Greenpeace will urge the new Congress to
support the legislation  and pass a reintroduced version in early 1997.   
<p>
To accomplish all of this is no small feat.  But, we already have
taken several steps toward what continues to be the only
acceptable number of dolphins which can be killed during tuna
fishing: <i>ZERO</i>.  If we succeed in getting governments and fishing
people around the world to agree to that goal and to keep making
clear progress in that direction, then we will have a package of
environmental protection for dolphins that they can live with, 
regardless of the label.
<p>
<a name="panama"></a>
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="panama.html">Text of <b>Panama Declaration</b></a></li>
<li><a href="tunatest.html">Testimony of Clifton Curtis</a> on behalf of Greenpeace 
before the Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife and Oceans of the U.S. House of 
Representatives Committee On Resources On Tuna/Dolphin-Related Issues as Addressed in
<b>H.R. 2823</b> and <b>H.R. 2856</b></li>
</ul>
<p> 
<center><h4>Also see our <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/publist.html">Public Information pages</a> 
for available <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/biodiversity.html">Biodiversity/Fisheries Campaign
Reports</a>.</h4>
</center>
