<html>
<head>
<title>Greenpeace USA Daily News/Campaign Updates</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FF FF FF" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00" vlink="#80 00 00" 
alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center>
<a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/news_rel.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0 ALT="Campaign News Releases"></a>
<hr width=100%>
<tt>
<font size=+3><b>GREENPEACE RELEASES CONFIDENTIAL FRENCH GOVERNMENT DOCUMENT ON
RADIOACTIVE SHIPMENT ROUTE</b><p></font></center>
<b>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico, December 18, 1996</b> -- According to a confidential document
obtained by Greenpeace, the second controversial plutonium waste shipment from Europe to
Japan will leave France on January 16, 1997, on board the U.K.-registered ship <i>Pacific Teal</i>. The
document, released today by Greenpeace, says the ship will travel around the Cape of Good Hope in
South Africa, the east of Australia, and through the South Pacific. The document, the
authenticity of which has not yet been confirmed, also states that en-route governments are to be informed on
December 23 of the intended route of the waste shipment.
<p> 
The same document appears to have been sent by the French Foreign Ministry in
Paris to its embassies in Tokyo, London and Washington, as well as to senior officials in the French
nuclear industry.
<p> 
"If the information in this document is correct, then it highlights the desperation of the governments of
France, Japan and the UK to avoid the strong public and political opposition to nuclear shipments in
the Caribbean, Central and South America," said Tom Clements from on board the vessel <i>M/V
Greenpeace</i>, docked today in San Juan. 
<p> 
Since the beginning of December, Greenpeace has been campaigning in the
Caribbean and Panama Canal to oppose the shipment from using that route. Today the <i>M/V Greenpeace</i>
leaves Puerto Rico for Frederiksted, St. Croix, U.S. Virgin Islands. The Greenpeace ship <i>Rainbow
Warrior</i> arrived December 16 in the Argentine port of Ushuaia near Cape Horn to protest the
waste shipment.
<p> 
The route given in the French document is the same as the 1992 plutonium
shipment on board the <i>Akatsuki-Maru</i>, which generated widespread opposition among nations along the route.
In 1995, the <i>Pacific Pintail</i>, carrying plutonium waste to Japan, sailed around South America amid
strong condemnation by the governments of Brazil, Argentina and Chile.
<p> 
"All routes for this shipment are unacceptable from an environmental and
security perspective," Clements said.  "Greenpeace will remain in the Caribbean until, and beyond, the
time this deadly shipment sets sail, and we will continue to work with the citizens and
governments of the region to expose and oppose such shipments."
<p>
<font size=+1> 
NOTE: The <a href="/~comms/no.nukes/transhn.html"><b>French Government document</b></a> is available 
on the Greenpeace International <a href="/~comms/no.nukes"><b>no.nukes</b></a> campaign page.                                  
<p>
For more background information, please read our on-line Campaign Bulletin, 
<a href="/~usa/reports/nuclear/stop_plutonium"><b>"Stop Plutonium"</b></a>.
<p></font>
REPORTERS MAY CONTACT:<br>
Shaun Burnie, Greenpeace International, Amsterdam, <b>011 31 20 52 36 257</b><br>
Deborah Rephan, Greenpeace News Desk, Washington, DC   <b>(202) 319-2492</b>
<p>
</tt>
<p>
