<CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif">
<H2>...Because our kids deserve a future</H2>
<IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"></CENTER>
<pre>


</pre>
</BODY>
</HTML>


</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B24-108</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA082-000568-B044-536</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://greenpeace.org:80/~usa/reports/nuclear/stop_plutonium/index.html 193.67.176.1 19970103170846 text/html 9357
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 03 Jan 1997 17:11:25 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 9186
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Dec 1996 22:40:32 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>"Greenpeace Bulletin - Stop Plutonium"</title>
<META Name="description" Content="Greenpeace bulletin documenting the lethal radioactive threat from tranportation of plutonium waste around the world.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="plutonium nuclear transport shipments radioactivity secret IAEA Akatsuki Maru Pacific Sandpiper Greenpeace USA environment">
<body background="pix/amchbck.gif" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00"
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<table width=575 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td colspan=2>
<img src="pix/nuke-hr2.gif" width=553 height=6><center>
<img src="pix/stopluto.gif" width=504 height=100 ALT="Stop Plutonium"></center>
<img src="pix/nuke-hr2.gif" width=553 height=6></td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/plutorad.gif" width=121 height=121 ALT="radiation symbol"><br>
<img src="pix/plutoqt1.gif" width=121 height=336 ALT="The secret transport is the latest chapter in Japan's program to obtain tens of tonnes of weapons-usable plutonium.">
</td>
<td valign=top>
In late 1996 or early 1997, a British ship containing highly radioactive nuclear waste is expected to leave the French port of Cherbourg bound for Japan. The secretive transport is the latest chapter in Japan's program to procure tens of tonnes of weapons-usable plutonium. This shipment of glassified, highly radioactive plutonium waste involves tremendous risks to the environment and public health.
<p>
In 1992, after the transport of 1.7 metric tonnes of plutonium onboard the ship <I>Akatsuki Maru</I> caused international condemnation around the globe, Japanese authorities said that they would reconsider the role of plutonium in their energy program. Instead, with the release of a new long-term plan in June of 1994, they rededicated themselves to an ambitious program of plutonium procurement and stockpiling; thereby assuring their status as a world leader in the international trade in weapons-usable plutonium. As part of this misguided and economically unjustifiable nuclear program, Japan, supported by France and Britain, is quietly preparing to make tens of transoceanic transports of irradiated nuclear fuel, nuclear waste and plutonium before the year 2000 alone.
<p>
<img align=right src="pix/plutop1.gif" width=200 height=400 ALT="GP protest of rad waste trasport ship">
The transport of highly radioactive plutonium waste is part of a program to ship more than 3,000 cylindrical glass blocks of some of the most radioactive waste ever produced. In fact, the waste is so deadly that a person within one meter of a single unshielded glass block would receive a fatal dose of radiation in less than one minute.
<p>
The imminent shipment is only the second attempt at moving such deadly material.  The first such transport was made from France to Japan in 1995.  In a desperate effort to evade international attention, that shipment, onboard the British-flagged <I>Pacific Pintail</I>, avoided the Caribbean and Panama Canal and was routed along the South American coast and around Cape Horn.  During its dangerous voyage, the transport was condemned by many nations around the world, and numerous countries put military aircraft in the sky and naval vessels at sea in response to the threat posed by the ship's passage.
<p>
The upcoming shipment will involve the carriage of forty glass blocks which belong to the Tokyo, Kansai, Kyushu and Shikoku electric power companies of Japan.  This cargo will contain some 20,500,000 curies of radioactivity. As British, French and Japanese authorities are keeping the shipment secret, it is not known which ship or route will be chosen.  
<p>
Despite the immense risks involved in moving such dangerous material, there are serious shortcomings in the transport and safety arrangements being made by relevant authorities. These dangers are intensified by apparent cost-cutting measures that have further eroded already inadequate safety provisions. In addition, rather than notifying and involving countries situated along the transports' routes, the Japanese, French and British authorities involved have chosen to act secretively and in arrogant disregard of public will and the authority of other sovereign states.  Altogether, the planned transports are a recipe for disaster which will only be stopped by public opposition and political and legal action.
</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>
<img src="pix/plutorad.gif" width=121 height=121 ALT="radiation symbol"><br>
<img src="pix/plutoqt3.gif" width=121 height=303 ALT="These glass blocks of "plutonium waste" are among the most radioactive materials ever produced.">
</td>
<td>
<img align=left src="pix/plutoqt2.gif" width=121 height=89 ALT="Why Produce and Transport Nuclear Waste?">
The nuclear waste  shipments are the outcome of Japan's ambitious program of plutonium procurement. In order to acquire plutonium, Japan has sent irradiated nuclear fuel from its nuclear power reactors to "reprocessing" plants in France and Britain.  At COGEMA's la Hague (France) and BNFL's Sellafield/THORP (U.K.) reprocessing plants, this irradiated nuclear fuel is chemically dissolved, and plutonium and uranium are removed from the other radioactive waste products formerly contained in the fuel.
<p>
In addition to the separated plutonium and uranium, reprocessing generates a tremendous volume of nuclear waste. A small proportion of this waste from reprocessing is mixed with glass and turned into blocks of highly concentrated radioactive waste. These glass blocks of "plutonium waste" are among the most radioactive materials ever produced. It should be noted that while an estimated 1,280,000 kg of glassified plutonium waste will be transported to Japan in this fashion, this represents only a very small proportion of the overall volume of nuclear waste generated by reprocessing. According to a document leaked to Greenpeace in July 1994, current reprocessing contract negotiations may require only between 3 and 7 percent of the nuclear waste arising from reprocessing to return to the clients. If all the generated nuclear wastes were to be returned to the clients, thousands of additional nuclear transports would be required; for example, British authorities have estimated that the return of clients' waste from the THORP/Sellafield reprocessing site would require more than 19,000 transports.
<p>
A large proportion of the nuclear waste generated by plutonium separation in France and Britain is discharged into the air, ground and sea, creating direct short- and long-term risks to the environment and public health. At the same time, all of the chemicals, equipment and other materials involved in the reprocessing activities themselves become contaminated by the radioactivity released from the reprocessed fuel.  In the end, reprocessing generates a volume of waste as much as 189 times greater than that of the irradiated fuel.
<p>
This nuclear waste generation is a sensitive subject for the plutonium industry and its governmental sponsors.  The terms of the contracts between the reprocessors (Britain and France) and their clients (Japan and others) are kept secret from politicians and the public alike. It is clear that if the public were fully aware of how much waste is dumped or stored in France and Britain, and the quantities which will be returned to Japan and the other client nations throughout Europe, there would be widespread resentment and opposition. By and large, the nuclear industry in Japan and the European client states have been able to dump their nuclear waste in France and Britain, while the plutonium industry in those two countries has aggressively promoted reprocessing as a clean, high-tech enterprise that makes money rather than nuclear waste.
<p>
Nonetheless, resentment and protest in France and Britain have grown, and government and industry have been forced to try and address public concern.  Accordingly, COGEMA and BNFL (the governmentally owned and controlled reprocessing companies in France and Britain respectively) are now planning to return some of the generated nuclear waste to Japan and the European clients. While the material returned may account for as little as 3 percent of the volume of nuclear waste ultimately generated for each client, the planned transboundary movement and return of waste have caused additional protests in the client nations, as well as those along the transport route.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/amspace.gif" width=121 height=10 ALT="(blank space)">						
</td>
<td valign=top>
<font size=+1><b><a href="part2.html">Ahead to Part 2</a> : How Will the Plutonium Waste Be Transported?</b></font>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>
Please see our <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/publist.html">Public Information page</a> for 
other Greenpeace Reports.<p>
