</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace: Say NO to Genetically Engineered Soybeans!</TITLE>
<META Name="description" Content="Greenpeace report documenting the faults of genetically engineered foods.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="genetic engineering soy beans Monsanto farming pesticides Roundup Greenpeace USA environment">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pix/gex.gif" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00"
VLINK="#80 00 00" ALINK="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/get_inv.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a></center>
<p>
<table width=560 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0>
<tr><td>
<center>
<img src="pix/out_up.gif" vspace=5 width=560 height=23 ALT="Outreach Update">
</center>
<font size=+3>Genetically Altered Soybeans Threaten U.S. Food Supply</font>
<p>
This fall, U.S. farmers will harvest the first crop of genetically engineered
soybeans. This represents a crucial step in a massive genetic experiment in
which human beings and the environment are guinea pigs.  These soybeans,
developed by Monsanto and known as "Roundup Ready Soybeans" (RRS), may be mixed
with traditional soybeans and sold to both domestic and foreign markets, making
it the first genetically engineered food to be distributed widely.  There is
one -- and only one -- benefit of RRS: it can survive exposure to the herbicide
glyphosate (trade name "Roundup"), allowing farmers to apply it even after the
soybean has started to grow.  This one benefit, however, is outnumbered by
several risks:  to our health, our environment, and our farm economy.
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>Genetically Altered Soybeans</b><p></font>
<p>
Soy is a major staple of the world food supply.  Soybean oil, mulch, and
derivatives (such as lecithin) are used in up to 60 percent of the food products found
on supermarket shelves, as well as being a major component of animal feed.
Roundup Ready is a genetically altered strain of soybean, combining genes from
a virus, a bacteria and a petunia to create a species which is resistant to the
herbicide Roundup.  Monsanto, a St. Louis-based company who also created Agent
Orange and PCBs, holds the patent on RRS, and is the producer of Roundup.  The
patent is in turn licensed to seed companies, such as Pioneer and Asgrow, who
produce and sell the RRS seeds to farmers.
<p> 
Soybeans are America's second largest agricultural crop, accounting for $14
billion in sales each year.  In 1996, 1-2 percent of the U.S. soybean crop was planted
with RRS.  Monsanto projects that 30 percent or more of the U.S. crop will be RRS in
1997.  Monsanto also intends to introduce RRS to farmers in Brazil and
Argentina.
<p> 
The impact of RRS on our health and the environment is not known.  Genetically
engineered plants are living and can breed and even cross-breed, possibly
endangering whole ecosystems.  The hazard of genetic pollution exists
everywhere RRS is grown because of the potential of weeds incorporating the
gene, but the most severe potential impact is in Asia and Australia, where weedy
varieties of soybeans exist.  These strains are the most likely plants to adopt
the Roundup genes, and would do so faster than other plants.  Other vegetation
can also develop a resistance to the herbicide, requiring additional
applications that has potential repercussions on our soil and water.
<p> 
RRS is also a genetic experiment with our bodies.  The potential for allergic
reactions to the virus, bacteria, and/or petunia added to soybeans to make RRS
is unknown because they are all foreign to the human diet.  Since soya is
contained as a sub-component in such a wide variety of foods, it would be very
difficult to trace soya as an allergen.  And, certainly, without labeling of
products containing genetically engineered soybeans, determining food allergies
would be impossible.
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>European Consumer Concern</b><p></font>
Public awareness and concern about genetically engineered food is high in
several European countries.  EuroCommerce, which represents about one third of
European retailers, has already sent a letter to the regional head of the
American Soybean Association in Brussels, demanding segregation of genetically
engineered (GE) and traditional soybeans so that products containing the
experimental beans can be labelled.  Switzerland and Austria are planning
national referenda concerning the growing and use of genetically engineered
crops and food, and on October 8 the Norwegian grocery trade stated that it
would not accept genetically engineered soybeans.  These precautions against
Monsanto's reckless behavior will affect America's soybean exports, and
subsequently American farmers.  
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>American Farmers and Monsanto</b><p></font>
Approximately half of the annual U.S. soybean crop is exported, with more than
one-third of our total crop sent to Europe alone.  In light of the existing
European consumer concern about genetically engineered foods and the growing
reluctance of food companies and retailers to sell RRS, Monsanto is gambling
with the livelihoods of thousands of American farmers in this giant genetic
experiment. 
<p> 
Since RRS is designed to be resistant to Monsanto's own herbicide, the planting
of RRS will guarantee higher profits for Monsanto as farmers who plant the
Monsanto bean will use the Monsanto herbicide.  Due to this experiment with
genetically engineered foods, American farmers stand not only to suffer severe
losses on the European market, but to have Monsanto claim greater control over
their farms. This will make farmers dependent on a single
corporation -- Monsanto -- thus reducing their ability to care for their land and
control their seeds.
<p> 
American farmers have been victimized by Monsanto before. In 1996 another
Monsanto product, genetically engineered cotton, went wrong. The cotton was
supposed to protect itself against caterpillar attack by producing its own
pesticide, but it failed and approximately 20,000 acres of cotton was lost.
There is even a danger that the caterpillars will become resistant to the
pesticide. 
<p> 
Recently, Monsanto genetically engineered "rBGH," a controversial growth hormone
for cows. This is designed to make them produce more milk but can harm the cows
themselves. Farmers and consumer groups in the U.S. have protested against its
use, and the European Union has banned it at least until the year 2000.
<p>
<table cellspacing=10 border=0>
<tr><td valign=top width=50%>
<table cellpadding=15 border=1>
<tr><td valign=top>
<font size=+1>
Genetically engineered foodstuffs should not be grown, produced or marketed
because of:
<ul><li>the risk of alien species invading, multiplying and displacing native flora
and fauna;</li>
<li>the near impossibility of cleaning up mistakes;</li>
<li>the unnecessary gamble with human -- and animal -- health.</li></ul></font>
</td></tr></table>
</td><td valign=top width=50%>
<font size=+3>Greenpeace Recommends:</font>
<ul><font size=+2>
<li>Consumers, food retailers, soybean brokers and processors demand soy 
products free from genetically engineered manipulations.</li>
<li>Farmers avoid the Roundup Ready Soybean and plant only non-genetically 
engineered soybeans and other crops.</li>
</font>
</ul>
</td></tr></table>
<img src="pix/can_do.gif" vspace=5 width=560 height=23 ALT="What you can do:"> 
<p>
<font size=+1>
Monsanto is engaging in a gigantic genetic experiment with our environment,
health, and economy.  Consumers have the right to know of possible dangers in
our food supply; this includes genetically engineered foodstuffs.  In the case
of RRS, Monsanto is trying to eliminate this right to know by forcing it on the
consumers and contaminating sources of traditional soybeans.
<p> 
<a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/roundup/index.html"><img align=left src="/~usa/pix/biobean.gif" width=90 height=90 ALT="Genetically Engineered Soybean" border=0></a>
<b>Contact your local food retailer</b> and tell them you don't want
genetically-engineered contaminated food.<p>
</font>
<b>For more information, please see our on-line report, <a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/roundup/index.html">"Not 
Ready for Roundup"</a>.
</b>
</td></tr>
</table>
<pre>

</pre>
</body>
