<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean - Latest Update!</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<IMG SRC="pics/newsupd.gif" ALT="[Latest Update!]" ALIGN="bottom" BORDER="none">  
<P>

<A HREF="#Issue1"><IMG SRC="pics/smlincin.gif" ALT="[Issue 1: Incineration]" ALIGN="absmiddle" BORDER="none"></A>
<A HREF="#Issue2"><IMG SRC="pics/smlfishw.jpg" ALT="[Issue 2: Waste Trade & Fisheries]" ALIGN="absmiddle" BORDER="none"></A>
<P>

<PRE>
<A NAME="Issue2.1">
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Issue #2 UPDATE!</B><FONT SIZE=3>
<B> The Waste Ban Treaty.</B>
</A>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>
Update On The Waste Trade
Campaign In Lebanon
</B><FONT SIZE=3>
 
Lebanon was shaken last October by two waste trade
scandals. Greenpeace has helped uncover the case of 36
containers full of plastic wastes from Germany.  Shortly
afterwards, the authorities on Beirut port confiscated 2
containers full of plastic waste from Belgium.
 
<B>1. WASTE FROM GERMANY:</B>
 
The Greenpeace Mediterranean Office has been pressing
Germany to take back from Lebanon all the 36 containers
filled  with a mixture of plastic wastes.  No distinction
should be made between contaminated and not contaminated
waste.
 
Last November, three German experts inspected the
containers at Beirut Port.  Lebanese officials and
Greenpeace were present at the site and documented the
inspection. The experts will write a report and then the
German authorities are expected to say next January that
they will return all the waste.
 
Until today, German officials have refused to clearly
state that they would return all the waste and insinuated
that they might return only the contaminated wastes. This
is unacceptable and outrageous.  Germany has no excuse.
It cannot hide behind anything because German and
European Union (EU) laws were broken when the 36
containers were sent to Lebanon last July. Germany has a
legal and moral obligation to agree to take back this
waste just like it did last month with 380 tons of
industrial chemical German waste in Hungary.
 
A Greenpeace expertise, published recently, proved that
the export from Germany to Lebanon of 36 containers with
plastic wastes is an illegal operation under German and
EU laws. Treatment of waste inside Germany is the first
option of waste disposal under Article 3 of the German
law on shipments of waste. The second priority is
treatment in another EU country.  Disposal outside the EU
can only be the last option when treatment inside Germany
or the EU is impossible. 21 containers are clearly
hazardous waste under the German legislation. This means
that their export to Lebanon is illegal under article
1.1b of the Basel Convention," the expertise said.
 
Due to strong indications that the German waste was
shipped to Lebanon for final disposal, "this waste export
is prohibited by the EU Council regulation on the
supervision and control of shipments of waste (EEC Nr.
259/93, Article 14).   Even if the wastes shipped to
Beirut would be considered as wastes for recovery, they
would by no means fall into the Green List of Wastes
(Annex II to EEC 259/93) because of their contamination,"
the expertise added.
 
Greenpeace has provided copies of the expertise to the
Lebanese judicial authorities and to the Environment
Ministry to support them in their work to return the
wastes to Germany. We also gave copies to the German
authorities in Bonn and Baden-Wuerttemberg and to the
German embassy in Beirut.  Greenpeace has been in regular
contact with the authorities in Bonn and in Stuttgart,

the capital of the state of Baden-Wuerttemberg from which
the waste originated.
 
<B>2. BACKGROUND WASTE FROM GERMANY:</B>
 
A Lebanese Environment Ministry report and a French
expertise proved that the 36 containers are full of
unsorted plastic waste, including PVC plastics, that
cannot be recycled in Lebanon. There are no facilities in
Lebanon to deal with such wastes because some of it is
contaminated with chemicals like pesticides and
fertilisers, said the Lebanese and French report. Some
waste is from hospitals and biologically contaminated.
The shipment was sent to Lebanon via Rotterdam last July.
It was declared as plastic raw material for the
industrial production. The Lebanese company "George
Freiha and Sons" was to buy it but on 8th August the
company rejected the material when it realised that it
was useless waste.
 
Greenpeace has learnt that Bernd Bretzing, the director
of RC-GMBH Reifenrecycling, was in 1993 the director of
the German company Asian Trade Import Export. This
company was responsible for dumping in the Baltic state
Estonia 6,000 tons of used tires from Germany in the
early 1990s. They were burnt illegally and emitted
poisonous smoke.  Bretzing was jailed on remand in
Germany last August under suspicion of illegally storing
hazardous waste.
 
<B>3. WASTE FROM BELGIUM:</B>
 
Lebanese authorities demanded last November that Belgium
returns 2 containers full of mixed plastic wastes, some
of it contaminated with chemicals. The 2 containers
arrived in Beirut Port on 24 October and were confiscated
shortly afterwards.
 
A Lebanese factory called Saltex imported the 2
containers. It is owned  by a man called Jean Salakhian.
He got the waste through a Lebanese businessman in
France, Nabil Kassir. Salakhian paid for the 2 containers
20,000 French Francs. When the shipment arrived at Beirut
Port, the importer claimed that he refused it because of
the horrible smells. The shipment was declared as plastic
bags and used plastic bags.
 
Lebanese authorities, already alarmed at that time by the
issue of German plastic waste, confiscated the 2
containers. The environment ministry sent experts to
inspect the waste. They wrote 2 reports saying that the
waste from Belgium is contaminated with pharmaceutical
chemical substances like "Eugenol", "Phnyliques" and
"Amidiques". They concluded: "These wastes were meant for
final disposal and
cannot be recycled in Lebanon." The numbers of the 2
containers are: TRIU539192/9  and TRIU525857/8.
Authorities in Lebanon have arrested Jean Salakhian.
 
<B>4. EVALUATION OF THE TOXIC TRADE CAMPAIGN:</B>
 
In a preliminary evaluation of the toxic trade campaign
in Lebanon one can say that two years of work on this
issue led to a strong awareness among Lebanese officials
and the people. Deputies and the new Environment Minister
Akram Shuhayeb took our ideas about a new legislation to
ban the import of all wastes even under the disguise of
recycling.
 
I gave the head of the Parliamentary Committee on the
Environment, Elie Skaff, and Mr. Shuhayeb documents to
help them draft a law banning the import of all sorts of
wastes - even under the disguise of recovery or
recycling. Lebanon may become
next year the first Arab state to pass a stiff anti-waste
trade law.
 
Greenpeace supports the position of the Lebanese
government and the judiciary who asked Germany to return
all the waste and make no exceptions.  Greenpeace
reiterates its call to the Beirut government to sign the
Waste Trade Protocol of the Barcelona Convention, that
was signed in Izmir last October, and the 1995 Basel Ban
amendment to protect itself from toxic and nuclear waste
attacks.
 
The export of all sorts of wastes from industrialised
nations to developing ones - even for so-called recovery
or recycling - should be banned. Waste is waste and
should stay where it was produced. As a matter of
principle, clean production methods should be introduced
in all industrial processes so that no hazardous or toxic
waste is produced in the first place.
 
Fouad Hamdan
Greenpeace Mediterranean Office
Lebanon Campaign
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:gp.med@cyberia.net.lb">gp.med@cyberia.net.lb</A>
</PRE>

<P>
<HR>
<P>
<BR>

<PRE>
<A NAME="Issue2">
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Issue #2: EU NEWS</B><FONT SIZE=3>
<B>   Fisheries Management,
   The Waste Ban Treaty.</B>
</A>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>
Report From The Second Diplomatic
Conference On Fisheries Management
In The Mediterranean
</B><FONT SIZE=3>
Venice, 27-29 November 1996.
 
This second EU sponsored conference has shown an
improvement from the previous one which was held in Crete
two years ago.  Almost all the countries which made
interventions recognised the need to take measures
towards the conservation and sustainable exploitation on
marine resources in the Mediterranean.
 
The Commission's position (Emma Bonino) was clear and
strong: it is necessary to reduce fleets in the Mediterranean
and change the current path of lack of action. She openly 
referred to the need to implement the UN Treaty and the FAO
Code as well as that the EU must become a GFCM Member Party
as soon as possible.
 
The main concrete conclusion of the conference is the
creation of a working party of legal and technical experts to
develop a system of conservation and management harmonised at
Mediterranean level.  This working party will be mandated
to provide the States'contribution to the 22 Session of
the GFCM.  It will prepare practical proposals and submit
them in time for the next session of the GFCM to be held
in Morocco in October 1997.
 
On the specific driftnet issue, the Italian Minister
defended a total driftnet ban in the Mediterranean, giving
assurances that his country will implement the reconversion 
plan in order to eliminate the Italian Drift-net fleet.

<HR>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>
European Union Bans Hazardous Waste Trade
</B><FONT SIZE=3> 
Brussels, December 10.

European Union (EU) followed through its commitments with the 
United Nations Basel Convention to prohibit hazardous wastes 
exports to non-OECD countries.

At yesterday's Council meeting, EU environment ministers
from all 15 member states reached political agreement to 
amend EU legislation so that shipments of hazardous waste for 
recycling and recovery to all non-OECD countries have to end 
by December 31, 1997 (1).
 
This will close the recycling loophole through which most
hazardous waste exports are currently flowing. While EU-
exports of waste for final disposal are prohibited since 
1993, shipments of wastes for recovery, no matter how
hazardous, are still allowed.  Following yesterday's decision
for the legal amendment, and beginning in 1998, hazardous 
waste traders in the EU will no longer be able to justify 
their dirty business with sham or dirty recycling operations 
in non-OECD countries.
 
"The transposition of the Basel Ban into EU law is a
great step forward to the detoxification of our planet", 
said Axel Singhofen, Greenpeace International EU Toxics 
Advisor.  "The hazardous waste export ban will force the 
rich EU countries to minimize hazardous waste generation at 
the source and spare the less industrialized world from 
their toxic effluent," added Singhofen.
 
The ministerial decision made it very clear that the EU
ban is a no-exception ban, since no kind of circumventing
trade agreement will be possible after 31 December 1997, and
all existing trade agreements will end by that date (2).
 
As one of the biggest steps towards clean production
since Rio, the European Community has now taken the global
lead in establishing that all hazardous waste exports to 
non-OECD countries, due to the immanent threat to health and
environment, are criminal.  Following the example of the
EU, it is now up to the rest of the world, in particular to 
the remaining OECD-countries, to transpose into legislation
their commitment under the Basel Convention to ban all OECD -
non-OECD hazardous waste trade.
                            ---
 
<B>CONTACT:</B>
Axel Singhofen, Greenpeace EU Unit, +32-2-280-1987.
 
<B>NOTES FOR THE EDITOR:</B>
(1) The EU is a contracting party to the Basel Convention
on the Control of Transboundary Movements of Hazardous
Wastes and their Disposal.  In March 1994, the contracting 
parties to the Basel Convention decided (Decision II/12) to 
immediately ban all hazardous waste exports from OECD to 
non-OECD countries for final disposal, and as of January 1, 
1998, all hazardous wastes destined for recovery. In April 
1995, Environment Commissioner Bjerregaard took the 
initiative to amend the existing EC Regulation on waste 
shipments (EEC/259/93) accordingly.
 
(2) see amended text of Regulation EEC/259/93, Article 16
(1): "All exports for recovery of waste listed in Annex V
shall be prohibited except those to: (a) countries to which
the OECD Decision applies; (b) other countries: [..] Any 
such exports shall however be prohibited from 1 January 
1998 onwards."
</PRE>

<P>
<HR>
<P>
<BR>

<PRE>
<A NAME="Issue1">
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Issue #1: INCINERATION</B><FONT SIZE=3>
</A>
<IMG SRC="pics/img0051.jpg" ALT="[Incinerator]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

On July 10th 1996, the Greenpeace Mediterranean Office held 
a press conference on incineration in Malta during which it 
presented a report entitled "The Burning Truth".  The 
conference was held jointly with Moviment Ghall-Ambjent, 
Friends of the Earth (Malta).  This report said that 
incinerators and landfills are being proposed in Malta, 
Lebanon, Turkey, Israel and other states as the 
environmentally acceptable solution to the current waste 
crisis.  But Greenpeace explained that  this is nothing but 
a myth.  Waste incineration is actually a seriously 
polluting technology.

The embedding of waste incineration and landfilling in 
southern Mediterranean states would ensure a waste-
generating industrial infrastructure, encourage waste trade 
and divert capital from waste prevention and recycling 
activities.  This would also postpone the introduction of 
Clean Production policies in industrial processes and hinder 
a sustainable future.  Under the guise of "transfer of 
environmentally sound technology for sustainable 
development", the West`s hazardous  and unwanted 
technologies are now being exported to Malta, Lebanon, 
Turkey, and other southern Mediterranean states.

Source reduction, reuse, recycling and composting of 
household waste is the only way to solve the growth waste 
crisis in the southern and eastern Mediterranean.  
Therefore, Greenpeace calls for:

1.  An immediate ban on burning waste containing chlorinated 
compounds and heavy metals.
2.  Plans to phaseout existing incinerators.
3.  A halt in construction of new incinerators and in the 
expansion of existing ones.
4.  A ban on dumping all sorts of hazardous waste in 
landfillls.
5.  Formulating and implementing programs for waste 
prevention, reuse, recycling and composting of household 
waste.  Financial incentives for communities to institute 
programs for source reduction, reuse, recycling and 
composting of solid household and urban waste.
6.  Formulating and implementing large-scale Clean 
Production programs in the industry.  Financial incentives 
to promote the introduction of clean production and not end-
of-pipe technologies.

<A HREF="pet_malta01.html"><IMG SRC="pics/arrow.gif" ALT="[->]" ALIGN="absmiddle" BORDER="none"><IMG SRC="pics/spacer.gif"  ALT=" " ALIGN="absmiddle" BORDER="none">Save Malta from Incineration! Sign the petition <B><I>Now!</I></B></A>


<A HREF="israel.html"><IMG SRC="pics/israelst.gif" ALT="[Israel]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A><P>

In Israel, authorities want to incinerate waste from  Ramat 
Hovav, Israel’s hazardous waste disposal site.  Some 45,000 
tons of  waste are stored on the site.  The planned 
incinerator is to burn toxic as well as sewage sludge, used 
oils, solvents, pesticides, waste rich with heavy metals, 
PVC and polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs).  The toxic ash is 
to be landfilled in the Negev.

Authorities are planning to build the country`s first 
household waste incinerator in Hadera, south of Haifa.  
Plans exist for a landfill for municipal waste in the Negev.


<A HREF="lebanon.html"><IMG SRC="pics/lebanst.gif" ALT="[Lebanon]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A><P>

The Lebanese Environment Ministry and the Council for the 
Development and Reconstruction (CDR) have formulated waste 
management plans relying solely on incinerators and 
landfills.  On December 5, 1996, the Lebanese Parliamentary 
Committee on Agriculture and Environment made a tragic 
mistake when it allowed the government to seek 110 million 
dollars of foreign loans to set up several incinerators and 
waste landfills in the country.

The agreement between the Lebanese government and the 
International Bank for Development and Reconstruction 
envisages getting a loan of 55 million dollars.  The 
remaining 55 million dollars are to come from Japan.  The 
money is to be used to set up 15 landfills, modernise and 
rehabilitate the existing landfills, set up two new 
composting plants in the cities of Saida and Zahle, 
modernise the incinerator in Amrusieh south of Beirut and 
set up there a composting plant, and construct a new 
incinerator for hospital waste.  The agreement does not even 
mention the ideas of "waste prevention and reduction" or 
"Clean Production".  Greenpeace has learnt that the toxic 
ash of the Amrusieh incinerator in southern Beirut is being 
dumped in the Borj-Hammud landfill.  They were part of 
15,800 barrels of toxic waste were dumped in 1987/88.  They 
were part of 15,800 barrels and 20 containers of toxic waste 
imported illegally from Italy in 1987.


<A HREF="turkey.html"><IMG SRC="pics/turkeyst.gif" ALT="[Turkey]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A><P>

In Turkey, a hospital and hazardous  waste incinerator is 
being constructed in Izmit, and  is expected to  be 
operational next September.  The  city is a centre of the 
country`s  heavy industry.  The city is a centre of the 
country`s heavy industry.  The incinerator is expected to 
burn 2600kg of solid waste per hour and 1.400 kg of waste 
water per hour.  There is also an industrial and household 
landfill in Izmit with a surface of 800.000 m2.  Authorities 
constructed an incinerator for hospital waste in Istanbul.  
Recently, after a short period of operation, the plant was 
closed for "technical modifications".  Its furnace has a 
capacity of 1000 kg per hour.


<A HREF="malta.html"><IMG SRC="pics/host2.gif" ALT="[Head Office (Malta)]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A><P>

In Malta, a 1992 official report estimated the waste 
problems to be:

*domestic solid waste: 97.200 tonnes per year in 1992 
increasing to 126,400 tonnes by the year 2010
*industrial solid waste: 90,000 tonnes per year in 1992 
increasing to 100,000 tonnes by the year 20110

Malta`s Environment Secretariat  is reported to be seriously 
considering the Incinerator option. This would be a tragic 
decision.  Authorities are looking for a short term, quick 
solution to the waste problem, when they should rather 
formulate and implement long-term Clean Production, waste 
reduction and recycling policies, a process requiring 
dedication and patience.

</PRE><HR><PRE> 
<FONT SIZE=4>
<A HREF="israel.html"><IMG SRC="pics/israelst.gif" ALT="[Israel]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
<B>HAIFA CHEMICALS</B>
<FONT SIZE=3>

<IMG SRC="pics/img0032.jpg" ALT="[Stop Haifa Chemicals!]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

The Israeli environment ministry and Haifa Chemicals 
recently agreed to solve the company`s waste problem on 
land.  This was possible after Greenpeace torpedoed plans of 
Haifa Chemicals to build a pipe to discharge toxic effluents 
directly into the sea.  The company is now discharging its 
toxic sludge into the Kishon River, and its ship the 
"Aribel" regularly dumps highly toxic sludge into the 
Mediterranean.  The accord has loopholes: It allows the 
factory discharge into the Kishon for the coming 4.5 to 6 
years.  Haifa Chemicals then celebrated the "year of 
environment" to greenwash its image.

<IMG SRC="pics/img0028.jpg" ALT="[Aribel]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

</PRE><HR><PRE> 
<FONT SIZE=4>
<A HREF="turkey.html"><IMG SRC="pics/turkeyst.gif" ALT="[Turkey]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

<B>SHELL</B>  <IMG SRC="pics/img0022a.jpg" ALT="[Shell]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="absmiddle"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3>
Shell has been systematically polluting an aquifer in 
southeast Turkey.  To escape possible liabilities, it sold 
the oil to Perenco that is continuing the criminal practice.

Pumping polluted water into the aquifer must stop at once.  
This practice will effect the lives of future generations in 
and around Diyarbakir.  Shell must accept permanent 
responsibility for the legacy it left.  The double standards 
and non-existent ethics of Shell are now clear to everybody.  
Shell and Perenco are just keen to make money at the expense 
of the environment and the people of Turkey.  The 
Dutch/British company Shell would have never injected 
polluted water into the aquifers in Britain or the 
Netherlands.  

<IMG SRC="pics/img0023.jpg" ALT="[Midyat/Diyarbakir Aquifer]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

In a related development, Turkey narrowly escaped from a 
disaster when one of Perenco`s oil pipelines transporting 
crude oil to nearby tanks exploded north of Diryarbakir last 
July.  The blast ignited a fire that Perenco could not 
extinguish.  It called the army that was able to stop the 
fire from reaching huge oil tanks.  Greenpeace contacted 
Perenco, but it refused to give any information.  Perenco`s 
main business strategy has been to buy unprofitable oil 
fields and drilling assests from at a profit after cutting 
staff and operating costs to a minimum.

The pipelines of Perenco are falling apart and maintenance 
work is almost non-existent to save costs.  Greenpeace 
demands that Turkish authorities force Perenco to repair and 
maintain its facilities to achieve the best possible safety 
standards.  The company must stop injecting production water 
polluted with chemicals and oils into the Midyat aquifer. 

<FONT SIZE=4>
<A HREF="turkey.html"><IMG SRC="pics/turkeyst.gif" ALT="[Turkey]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
<B>CHERNOBYL</B>

<IMG SRC="pics/ch02.jpg" ALT="[Chernobyl]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

<B>OFFICIALS LIED OVER IMPACT OF CHERNOBYL
IN TURKEY</B>
<FONT SIZE=3>
When the Chernobyl nuclear plant exploded in 1986, Turkish 
politicians claimed that the impact on their country was 
null. The Reality is different: People consumed contaminated 
food. Ten years after the disaster, the same officials are 
now promoting plans for a nuclear power plant in Turkey.
 

Turkish authorities have lied to their people about the 
impact of the Chernobyl disaster. The disinformation policy 
has been going on since the nuclear power plant exploded in 
the Ukraine on April 26, 1986.  This resulted in tons of 
contaminated food being consumed by millions of people. Last 
April Greenpeace published a report on this issue and on the 
tenth anniversary of the nuclear disaster.  The report 
included confidential memos from Turkish officials and the 
few credible Turkish scientific studies on the impact of 
Chernobyl in Turkey.
 
Turkish ministers and other officials forbade scientists to 
carry out independent studies, allowed only a handful of 
politicians to make public statements on the issue and 
allowed contaminated food to be sold. In Turkey, the sale 
and export of contaminated tea and hazelnuts, and not public 
health, was the main concern of authorities. This means that 
radiated food will effect people for many years to come.

<IMG SRC="pics/ch06.jpg" ALT="[Child]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
 
The Turkish Atomic Energy Agency (TAEK) knew about the 
contamination in regions like the Black Sea. But it neither 
warned farmers growing tea in this region nor factories 
processing it. Contaminated tea was sold on the Turkish 
market.  Best quality tea was sold most likely in Germany 
and consumed by Turkish workers living there. Results of 
measurements in Germany of tea bought in
Turkey in June 1987 varied from dangerous levels of 6,000 to 
30,000 Bq/kg.
 
Cahit Aral, Turkish Minister of Industry and Trade, bluntly 
said in June 1986:  "All meat, milk, water, fish, vegetables 
from all over our country are totally clean. There is no 
radioactive contamination harming human health." But he 
confessed in 1992: "The government has indeed hidden the 
facts and figures on the impact of Chernobyl in Turkey." He 
justified this policy with the following argument: "We did 
take our revenge on the Soviet Union for the nightmare of 
Chernobyl by exporting contaminated hazelnuts to Russia." 
Mr. Aral confirmed that the same hazelnuts were given  for 
free to Turkish soldiers. Hazelnuts were also distributed in 
primary schools. 
 
Mr. Ozemre, former head of TAEK, Mr. Aral and other 
officials had tried to suppress information about the 
consequences of the Chernobyl disaster.  Today thay are 
promotin nuclear power  with the support of the current 
coalition government.  Officials recently said that the 
tender for the construction of a nuclear power plant in 
Akkuyu near Mersin would start soon.
 
Greenpeace demands that Turkish authorities allow intensive 
and independent scientific research on the impact of 
Chernobyl in Turkey.  The full consequences on people`s  
health and on the environment must be assessed.  All 
information on this issue should be made public.  And all 
nuclear plans should be scrapped once and forever. 

<IMG SRC="pics/ch1.gif" ALT="[Gas Mask]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

<FONT SIZE=4>
<A HREF="turkey.html"><IMG SRC="pics/turkeyst.gif" ALT="[Turkey]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
  <B>COAL MINES</B>

<IMG SRC="pics/miner.jpg" ALT="[Coal Miner]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

<B>THE MUGLA TRIANGLE WILL STOP DESTROYING LIVES
AND THE ENVIRONMENT</B>
<FONT SIZE=3>
On June 20th, 1996 the Aydin Administrative Court, accepted 
the demand to stop the Gokova, Yenikoy and Yatagan Coal 
Power Plants due to the damage they inflict on human health 
and the environment.  The cases for Gokova and Yatagan was 
started in 1993 and Yenikoy in 1994 by The Izmir 
Environmental Movement Lawyers.

The lawyers first applied to the Prime Ministry, and the 
Ministry of Energy for the closure of these power plants 
stating that their operation violate the laws and cause 
environmental damage.  Then they sued The Ministries of 
Energy and Health, Mugla Governor’s Office and the Turkish 
utility TEK at the Aydin Administrative court.

Turkey is an extremely energy wasteful country and therefore 
has a great potential in energy efficiency.  Unfortunately, 
energy efficiency is not taken seriously by the Ministry of 
Energy which is busy with dangerous nuclear investments.  
Also, the power lost in transmission and distribution in 
Turkey amounts to a huge 25 percentage.  Turkey could easily 
keep Yatagan, Yenikoy and Gokova closed and forget its 
nuclear plans if it invested in energy efficiency and its 
clean, inexpensive and safe renewable energy sources now.  
Renewables not only contribute to a cleaner environment, but 
also help with creating more jobs than the polluting thermal 
and nuclear power plants.

Greenpeace demands that the decision of The Aydin 
Administrative Court is implemented immediately and the 
nuclear tender to be cancelled.  This is the only way to a 
safe and secure energy future where efficiency and 
renewables are the true solution.

</PRE><HR><PRE> 
<FONT SIZE=4>
<A HREF="cyprus.html"><IMG SRC="pics/cyprst.gif" ALT="[Cyprus]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
<B>AKAMAS PENINSULA</B>
<FONT SIZE=3>

<IMG SRC="pics/img0013.gif" ALT="[Turtle]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>

A company owned by Cypriot Foreign Minister Alecos 
Michaelides is breaking the law.  "Thanos Hotels" is 
building a hotel in the Akamas Peninsula, a protected area 
where endangered turtles nest.  The scandal began when the 
government relaxed last January normal building restrictions 
on the reserve in Akamas to allow the development by "Thanos 
Hotels".  This company is owned by Mr. Michaelides.

To raise the pressure against Mr. Michaelides,  Greenpeace 
protested last May in front of the Cypriot Foreign Ministry.  
The demonstrators carried sandwich boards with a caricature 
showing Mr. Michaelides greedily grabbing Akamas to build a 
hotel there.  A banner read: "Minister Michaelides, hands 
off Akamas!"

</PRE><HR><PRE>

<FONT SIZE=4>
<A HREF="malta.html"><IMG SRC="pics/host2.gif" ALT="[Head Office (Malta)]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
<B>ARCTIC SUNRISE</B>
<FONT SIZE=3>
<IMG SRC="pics/arcticsr.gif" ALT="[Arctic Sunrise]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
<!--<IMG SRC="pics/img0018.jpg" ALT="[Arctic Sunrise]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>-->

Malta - the Greenpeace ship "Arctic Sunrise" began in July a 
four-month tour in the Mediterranean.  Its crew will hunt 
boats using banned driftnets.  The activists will also 
campaign on toxic waste trade, incineration and nuclear 
power.  The boat will visit Italy, Spain, France, Greece, 
Malta, Turkey, Lebanon, Israel, Cyprus and Tunisia.

</PRE>

<BR><BR><BR>
<HR>

<FONT SIZE=3>

The following snippets are taken from our forthcoming 3rd 
issue of <B>Greenpeace Mediterranean <I>In Action!</I></B><P>

<PRE>
<FONT SIZE=4>
<B>FRANCE WANTS TO EXPORT NUCLEAR WASTE</B>
<FONT SIZE=3>
France has been blocking and agreement on a protocol banning 
the export of toxic and nuclear waste from northern to 
southern Mediterranean countries.  Dring recent negotiation 
rounds, France has filed a "reserve" on the inclusion of 
radioactive waste in the export ban to non-European Union 
countries in the basin.  France agreed to ban nuclear waste 
exports to 66 developing countries in Asia, the Pacific and 
Latin America, but it refuses to apply the same policy in 
the Mediterranean.  Greenpeace demands that France signs the 
protocol during a meeting in Turkey this September.


<FONT SIZE=4>
<B>SOLAR ENERGY IS MARKETABLE</B><IMG SRC="pics/fluorblb.gif" ALT="[Fluorescent Bulb]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="absmiddle"></A>
<FONT SIZE=3>
Athens - Greenpeace exchanged last April normal lamps in the 
Greek Ministry of Energy with energy-efficient ones.  The 
"high-tech" bulbs consume only a fifth of the energy and 
last ten times longer than the normal ones.  The action 
meant that the ministry would save about 20,000 kilowatt-
hours, or $2,500, per year.  Greenpeace wants authorities in 
the Mediterranean to subsidise energy-efficient technologies 
and provide incentives to alternative energies like solar 
and wind.

In Germany, Greenpeace proved last spring that rooftop 
photovoltaic units are now 40 percent cheaper than before.  
Five firms submitted to us bids saying they can offer 2-
kilowatt rooftop solar facilities fulfilling specific 
technical and cost criteria.  Greenpeace then collected from 
4,000 people intents of purchase for such a facility.  If 
all these people install a solar rooftop unit, this would 
double present solar power use in Germany.

<IMG SRC="pics/roofcell.jpg" ALT="[Roof-mounted Solar Cells]" BORDER="none" ALIGN="bottom"></A>
</PRE>

<BR><BR><BR>

