<HTML>
<HEAD>
<LINK REV="MADE" HREF="duncanc@xs4all.nl">
<TITLE>Options for Extension of the Non-Proliferation Treaty</TITLE>
<P>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<A HREF = "index.html"><img src="back.gif" alt="Back to Index Page"></A> </H2>
<p>
<B>December 1994</B><P>
<H1>Options for Extension of the Non-
Proliferation Treaty<br>A Legal Analysis</H1>
<A Name = textf1> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef1">  [1]</A> <P>
By Duncan Currie, Greenpeace International Legal Department
<p><h3>
<A HREF = "#Table_of_Contents">Table of Contents</A> </H3>
<P>
<H1><A NAME=h_1_introduction> </A> </H1>
<H1>1.    Introduction</H1>
The Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons<A NAME= h_textf2> </A> 
<A Name = textf2> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef2">  [2]</A>  ('NPT') was concluded in 1968 
and is aimed at the promotion of nuclear disarmament and the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and 
attempts to freeze the transfer of nuclear weapons technology from nuclear to non-nuclear states. The 
NPT was concluded for an initial 25 years after its entry into force in 1970.<A NAME= h_textf3> </A> 
<A Name = textf3> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef3">  [3]</A> <P>


Article X(2) of the NPT reads as follows:<P><ul>
Twenty-five years after the entry into force of the Treaty, a conference shall be 
convened to decide whether the Treaty shall continue in force indefinitely, or shall be 
extended for an additional fixed period or periods. This decision shall be taken by a 
majority of the Parties to the Treaty.<P>
</UL>
Thus a conference is due to be held on 17 April to 12 May 1995 in New York to decide the extension of the 
NPT and review its implementation.<A NAME= h_textf4> </A> 
<A Name = textf4> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef4">  [4]</A>  <P>
Three options are expressed in Article X(2): the Treaty shall continue in force indefinitely, the Treaty shall 
be extended for an additional fixed period, or the Treaty shall be extended for additional fixed periods. <P>
Discussion about extension of the NPT should be viewed in the political context of the debate. Questions 
of interpretation of Article X cannot be resolved in a political vacuum. As was noted in a general 
context,<P>
Many disputes which appear to be disputes about the correct interpretation of a treaty 
or customary law have hidden motivation. Judicial resolution in terms of legal issues 
presented would not touch the real source of the difficulties, the real problems and 
policies that are involved.<A NAME= h_textf5> </A> 
<A Name = textf5> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef5">  [5]</A> <P>
Shabtai Rosenne likewise noted that <P><UL>
[T]he harsh fact is that the elements of the law of treaties and indeed the treaties 
themselves are completely overshadowed by the graver clashes of interests, even 
vital interests, not merely of the States immediately and directly concerned, but of 
others as well. It is a tendentious and misleading oversimplification to treat them as 
disputes of an exclusively legal character, as 'legal disputes' or as 'legal questions'.<A NAME= h_textf6> </A> 
<A Name = textf6> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef6">  [6]</A> <P></UL>
That nuclear interests affected by the NPT affect the vital interests of both nuclear and non-nuclear states 
Party is clear.<A NAME= h_textf7> </A> 
<A Name = textf7> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef7">  [7]</A>  Thus it is vitally important that 
Article X be seen as clearly and dispassionately as possible in order that the pending Extension 
Conference in 1995 can take place in a broad and realistic political context. This political dimension is 
been seen in the varying interpretations of Article X in the literature to date.<A NAME= h_textf8> </A> 
<A Name = textf8> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef8">  [8]</A> <P>
The essential argument is between those that favour an indefinite extension, consisting primarily of nuclear 
weapons states, and those that favour renewal for single or multiple periods, often predicated upon 
progress in achieving a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty ("CTBT"), security assurances and wider 
adherence to the NPT.<P>
This paper concludes that there is considerable latitude given to the Parties, that if the Parties do not 
reach an agreement then the Treaty will expire, and that a rolling set of fixed periods of extension with a 
decision-making mechanism between them about continuing on into the next period is compatible with the 
provisions of the NPT.<P>
<H1><A NAME=h_2_background_on_the_npt> </A> </H1>
<H1>2.    Background on the NPT</H1>
The two-tiered nature of the NPT was agreed to by the non-nuclear weapons states predicated<A NAME= h_textf9> </A> 
<A Name = textf9> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef9">  [9]</A>  upon undertakings towards 
concrete steps towards disarmament, including a mandatory initial 5 year review and optional subsequent 
reviews every five years with a view to assuring that the purposes of the Preamble and the provisions of 
the Treaty are being realised,<A NAME= h_textf10> </A> 
<A Name = textf10> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef10">  [10]</A>  together with five tangible 
steps to halt the nuclear arms race and limit, reduce and eliminate the stocks of nuclear weapons and 
delivery systems.<A NAME= h_textf11> </A> 
<A Name = textf11> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef11">  [11]</A>  The five yearly review 
Conferences have shown that none of the five steps have been reached and therefore some non-nuclear 
powers argue that the nuclear powers have breached their obligations, including in particular Article VI.<A NAME= h_textf12> </A> 
<A Name = textf12> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef12">  [12]</A>  Negotiations towards a 
comprehensive nuclear test ban, nearly twenty-five years after entry into force of the Convention, have 
only recently commenced in Geneva. The ABM Treaty,<A NAME= h_textf13> </A> 
<A Name = textf13> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef13">  [13]</A>  Intermediate-range Nuclear 
Forces Treaty<A NAME= h_textf14> </A> 
<A Name = textf14> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef14">  [14]</A>  and STARTs I and II  
represent only halting progress towards ceasing the nuclear arms race. Many non-nuclear weapons states 
would argue the world is not even close to nuclear or general disarmament and the review conferences 
have revealed that the purposes of the Preamble and the provisions of the Treaty, Article VI in particular, 
are far from being realised.<A NAME= h_textf15> </A> 
<A Name = textf15> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef15">  [15]</A> <P>
<H1><A NAME=h_3_aspects_of_treaty_interpretation> </A> </H1>
<H1>3.    Aspects of Treaty Interpretation 
</H1>
<H2><A NAME=h_3_1_traveaux_préparatoires> </A> </H2>
<H2>3.1    Traveaux Préparatoires</H2>
Article 32 of the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties<A NAME= h_textf16> </A> 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_32_supplementary_means_of_i"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
<A Name = textf16> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef16">  [16]</A>  permits recourse to 
supplementary means of interpretation, including the preparatory work<A NAME= h_textf17> </A> 

<A Name = textf17> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef17">  [17]</A>  of the treaty (<I>traveaux 
préparatoires</I>) and the circumstances of its conclusion, in order to confirm the meaning or to determine 
the meaning when the interpretation leaves the meaning ambiguous or obscure or  leads to a result which 
is manifestly absurd or unreasonable. The extension provisions of Article X (2) are both ambiguous and 
obscure, thus recourse to <I>traveaux préparatoires</I> appears amply justified.<P>
The intention of the non-nuclear states in insisting on the five yearly review provisions was that this would 
provide the framework for the momentum towards achieving the five tangible steps towards disarmament. 
The extension provisions of Article X can then be seen in context of being intended to facilitate the 
finalization of remaining steps.<P>
George Bunn has noted that instead of the indefinite term advocated by the Soviet Union and the United 
States, Italy and other non-nuclear states proposed that the NPT should be of fixed term but automatically 
renewable for additional fixed terms, but allow parties to withdraw at the end of any term.<A NAME=h_textf18> </A> 
<A Name = textf18> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef18">  [18]</A>  This proposal gave rise to 
the 'additional fixed periods' concept, but the right of individual withdrawal was rejected in favour of the 
provision to end the treaty for all parties either by a short extension in 1995 or by non-renewal at the end 
of an additional fixed period.<P>
<H2><A NAME=h_3_2_subsequent_practice> </A> </H2>
<H2>3.2    Subsequent Practice</H2>
The Vienna Convention mandates in Article 31 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_31_general_rule_of_interpre"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
that a treaty shall be interpreted in good faith in accordance 
with the ordinary meaning to be given to the terms of the treaty in their context and in the light of its object 
and purpose. Any subsequent agreement between the parties regarding the interpretation of the treaty or 
the application of its provisions is taken into account, as is any subsequent practice in the application of 
the treaty which establishes the agreement of the parties regarding its interpretation. A special meaning 
shall be given to a term if it is established that the parties so intended. Most notably, a practice has 
evolved whereby an abstention by a permament member of the Security Council is not considered a veto, 
contrary to the language of Article 27(3) of the United Nations Charter.<A NAME= h_textf19> </A> 

<A Name = textf19> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef19">  [19]</A> <P>
Thus any interpretation of Article X should be viewed not only in the wider context of the NPT but in light of 
practice by the NPT Parties and any agreement between the Parties. Such an interpretation would 
strongly militate against a restrictive interpretation of Article X relating to such matters as conditions on 
renewals. <P>
During the 1990 Fourth Review Conference, a number of non-nuclear states called for a comprehensive 
nuclear test ban treaty which would facilitate the extension of the NPT for a significant period beyond 
1995.<A NAME= h_textf20> </A> 
<A Name = textf20> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef20">  [20]</A>  Other working papers 
explicitly drew the connection between Article VI and Article X.<A NAME= h_textf21> </A> 
<A Name = textf21> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef21">  [21]</A>  Working Group I at the 
1994 Pugwash Conference concluded that:<P>
This Group is wholly convinced of the necessity of extending the Non-Proliferation 
Treaty beyond 1995, for one or more fixed periods, and is opposed to an indefinite 
extension. The extension(s) must be of a finite duration to prevent the permanent 
categorization of some nations as 'nuclear weapon states' and the implicit legalization 
and acceptance of nuclear weapons. One or more periods of extension should be 
envisaged; a majority urged that they be linked to the completion of explicit 
disarmament measures. A 25 year period, to reach a nuclear-weapon-free world, was 
urged.<A NAME= h_textf22> </A> 
<A Name = textf22> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef22">  [22]</A> <P>
<H2><A NAME=h_3_3_canons_of_construction> </A> </H2>
<H2>3.3    Canons of Construction</H2>
The central question at all times is the agreement of the Parties,<A NAME= h_textf23> </A> 
<A Name = textf23> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef23">  [23]</A>  while the primary rule of 
treaty interpretation<A NAME= h_textf24> </A> 
<A Name = textf24> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef24">  [24]</A>  in the Vienna Convention 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>is 
that of good faith: a treaty shall be interpreted in good faith in accordance with the ordinary meaning to be 
given to the terms of the treaty in their context and in the light of its object and purpose.<A NAME=h_textf25> </A> 
<A Name = textf25> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef25">  [25]</A>  An interpretation consistent 
with the practice of the treaty and consistent with the preamble and its expressed object and purpose is 
thus not only permitted but mandated by the Vienna Convention. The United States acting Deputy Director 
of the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency has suggested that a narrow construction must be 
placed upon Article X as an important new legal obligation may be imposed, thus Parties must choose one 
of the three options and the extension conference is not authorized to take any other extension option.<A NAME= h_textf26> </A> 
<A Name = textf26> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef26">  [26]</A> Yet since United States 
officials have argued for an indefinite extension, this argument is apparently intended to result in placing 
the most onerous legal obligation possible.<P>
<H2><A NAME=h_3_4_other_authentic_languages> 
</A> </H2>
<H2>3.4    Other Authentic Languages</H2>
Article XI of the NPT provides that English, Russian, French, Spanish and Chinese language versions are 
equally authentic. Article 33 of the Vienna Convention 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_33_interpretation_of_treati"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
provides that the terms of the treaty are presumed 
to have the same meaning in each authentic text<A NAME= h_textf27> </A> 
<A Name = textf27> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef27">  [27]</A>  and that, except where a 
particular text prevails in accordance, when a comparison of the authentic texts discloses a difference of 
meaning which the application of Articles 31<A NAME= h_textf28> </A> 
<A Name = textf28> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef28">  [28]</A>  and 32<A NAME=h_textf29> </A> 
<A Name = textf29> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef29">  [29]</A>  does not remove, the 
meaning which best reconciles the texts, having regard to the object and purpose of the treaty, shall be 
adopted. It is thus useful to refer to the French and Spanish versions.<A NAME= h_textf30> </A> 

<A Name = textf30> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef30">  [30]</A> <P>
The French version of the Article X(2) <A NAME= h_textf31> </A> 
<A Name = textf31> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef31">  [31]</A>  uses the phrases 
'demeurera en vigueur pour une durée indéfinie', which does not materially differ from 'continue in force 
indefinitely', and the phrase 'ou sera prorogé pour une ou plusieurs périodes' which does not differ 
materially from 'shall be extended for an additional fixed period or periods'. Thus the French version 
incorporates the same concepts as the English and the same ambiguities, and does speak in terms of 
prorogé or extension of the Treaty, thus suggesting there has been a deadline that may be extended.<P>
The Spanish Article X(2) <A NAME= h_textf32> </A> 
<A Name = textf32> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef32">  [32]</A>  is phrased as follows: 
"decidir si el Tratado permanecerá en vigor indefinidamente o si se prorogará por uno o más períodos 
suplementarios de duración determinada," thus using the term 'prorogará', and again making the extension 
contingent on a decision by the Parties.<P>
<H2><A NAME=h_3_5_other_possibilities_for_termina> </A> </H2>
<H2>3.5   Other Possibilities for Termination of the NPT</H2><A NAME= h_textf33> </A> 
<H2><A NAME = textf33> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef33">  [33]</A> </H2>
There are no specific provisions in the NPT with respect to termination. However termination of the 
treaty<A NAME= h_textf34> </A> 
<A Name = textf34> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef34">  [34]</A>  could be effected by 
consent of the Parties after consultation with any other contracting States<A NAME= h_textf35> </A> 
<A Name = textf35> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef35">  [35]</A>  following Article 54 of the 
Vienna Convention.
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_54_termination_of_or_withdr"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
<A NAME= h_textf36> </A> 
<A Name = textf36> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef36">  [36]</A>  Consent by the Parties to 
such a termination of the treaty may be implied. In particular, a treaty may be considered  as terminated if 
all parties conclude a later treaty relating to the same subject matter which is intended to supplant the 
earlier treaty or if the later treaty is incompatible with its provisions.<A NAME= h_textf37> </A> 

<A Name = textf37> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef37">  [37]</A> <P>
Likewise, the Vienna Convention 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>contains principles governing termination following breach, which 
principles have been described by the International Court of Justice as a codification of customary 
international law.<A NAME= h_textf38> </A> 
<A Name = textf38> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef38">  [38]</A> A material breach of a 
multilateral treaty by one of the parties entitles the other parties by unanimous agreement to suspend the 
operation of the treaty in whole or in part or to terminate it either in the relations between themselves and 
the defaulting State or as between all the parties.<A NAME= h_textf39> </A> 
<A Name = textf39> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef39">  [39]</A>  A party specially affected 
by the breach may invoke it as a ground for suspending the operation of the treaty in whole or in part in the 
relations between itself and the defaulting State. Any party other than the defaulting State may invoke the 
breach as a ground for suspending the operation of the treaty in whole or in part with respect to itself if the 
treaty is of such a character that a material breach of its provisions by one party radically changes the 
position of every party with respect to the further performance of its obligations under the treaty.  A 
material breach of a treaty consists in a repudiation of the treaty not sanctioned by the Vienna Convention <br><A HREF="vien-tr.html"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
or the violation of a provision essential to the accomplishment of the object or purpose of the treaty.<A NAME= h_textf40> </A> 
<A Name = textf40> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef40">  [40]</A> <P>
Article VI of the NPT requires that each of the Parties to the Treaty undertakes to pursue negotiations in 
good faith on effective measures relating to cessation of the nuclear arms race at an early date and to 
nuclear disarmament, and on a treaty on general and complete disarmament under strict and effective 
international control. It is arguable that Article VI has been consistently breached by the nuclear 
States.<P>
<H2><A NAME=h_3_6_withdrawal_from_the_npt> </A> </H2>
<H2>3.6    Withdrawal from the NPT</H2>
Article X (1) provides that<P><UL>
Each Party shall in exercising its national sovereignty have the right to withdraw from 
the Treaty if it decides that extraordinary events, related to the subject matter of this 
Treaty, have jeopardized the supreme interests of its country. It shall give notice of 
such withdrawal to all other Parties to the Treaty and to the United Nations Security 
Council three months in advance. Such notice shall include a statement of the 
extraordinary events it regards as having jeopardized its supreme interests.<P>
</UL>
This must be taken in addition to the more restrictive general right of termination following breach.<A NAME= h_textf41> </A> 
<A Name = textf41> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef41">  [41]</A>  It may be argued that an 
'event' is required. This may be more than a material breach of Article VI, for instance, but may be related 
to such a breach, and in any case would most likely amount to a violation of a provision essential to the 
accomplishment of the object or purpose of the treaty within Article 60 of the Vienna Convention.
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_60_termination_or_suspensio"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
 North 
Korea purported to invoke the withdrawal clause in 1993.<A NAME= h_textf42> </A> 
<A Name = textf42> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef42">  [42]</A>  The Security Council later 
called upon North Korea to reconsider its intention to withdraw<A NAME= h_textf43> </A> 
<A Name = textf43> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef43">  [43]</A>  and North Korea 
suspended its withdrawal notice. This course of events could be seen to reinforce the strength of the 
requirements for withdrawal.<P>
In some circumstances, termination or withdrawal from a treaty may be justified under the doctrine of 
<I>rebus sic stantibus</I>,<A NAME= h_textf44> </A> <A NAME = textf44> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef44">  [44]</A> which is 
codified in Article 61 of the Vienna Convention. 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_61_supervening_impossibilit"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
A fundamental change of circumstances which has 
occurred with regard to those existing at the time of the conclusion of a treaty, and which was not foreseen 
by the parties, may be invoked as a ground for terminating or withdrawing from the treaty  where the 
existence of those circumstances constituted an essential basis of the consent of the parties to be bound 
by the treaty; and  the effect of the change is radically to transform the extent of obligations still to be 
performed under the treaty.<A NAME= h_textf45> </A> 
<A Name = textf45> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef45">  [45]</A>  A fundamental change of 
circumstances may not be invoked as a ground for terminating or withdrawing from a treaty if the 
fundamental change is the result of a breach by the party invoking it either of an obligation under the treaty 
or of any other international obligation owed to any other party to the treaty.<A NAME= h_textf46> </A> 
<A Name = textf46> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef46">  [46]</A> <P>
<H1><A NAME=h_4_extension_options> </A> 
</H1>
<H1>4.    Extension Options</H1>
<H2><A NAME=h_4_1_general_procedural_consideratio
> </A> </H2>
<H2>4.1    General Procedural Considerations 
and Failure to Reach a Decision</H2>
Any decision must be taken by a majority of the Parties to the Treaty, not simply a majority of Parties 
attending the Extension Conference. If the Conference fails to achieve a majority in favour of one of the 
extension options, then there seems to be no reason that the Parties could not agree, by majority, not to 
extend the Treaty. In this way, Article X could be read as permitting Parties to agree to extend the NPT in 
one of the three suggested ways - or not. It is by no means certain that this interpretation, particularly if it 
were adopted by a majority of the Parties to the NPT, would be <I>ultra vires</I> Article X.<A NAME=h_textf47> </A> 
<A Name = textf47> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef47">  [47]</A>  It has been argued that 
failure to reach any decision could not result in termination since this would in effect amount to a right of 
termination which is not provided for in the Treaty.<A NAME= h_textf48> </A> 
<A Name = textf48> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef48">  [48]</A>  However conversely this 
could be seen as an expiration of the natural duration of the treaty, absent a decision to extend the treaty. 
An interpretation of Article X which restricted any possible decision to the three listed options, but 
permitted, for instance, an extension of one day<A NAME= h_textf49> </A> 
<A Name = textf49> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef49">  [49]</A>  would be unduly narrow. 
Other authors have suggested that failure to reach agreement would mean that once the extension 
conference is convened it should continue "until it reaches one of the alternatives open to it"<A NAME=h_textf50> </A> 
<A Name = textf50> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef50">  [50]</A>  and that the conference 
must continue in being so that it can reconvene, and that should it be unable to reach a decision within 
some reasonable time, "the parties could consider that the Treaty had lapsed and declare that judgement 
to the depositaries without reference to the provisions for withdrawal in article X(1)".<A NAME=h_textf51> </A> 
<A Name = textf51> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef51">  [51]</A>  <P>
However, while this may be a course open to the parties, a more straightforward conclusion may be that 
failure to reach agreement could lead to automatic termination at the conclusion of the conference. Epstein 
and Szasz suggested that such a step, even if it did not formally require notification to the Security Council 
under Article X(1), may  nonetheless prompt the Security Council to resolve that any withdrawal from the 
NPT constitutes a threat to peace under Article 39 of the United Nations Charter and is therefore not 
permissible.<A NAME= h_textf52> </A> 
<A Name = textf52> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef52">  [52]</A>  However, apart from a 
query whether such a step would in fact constitute a 'withdrawal', it is speculative that the Security Council 
would pass such a resolution, even if such a resolution, concerning as it would the necessary 
consequence of the failure of Parties to reach a decision, would be soundly based.<A NAME=h_textf53> </A> 
<A Name = textf53> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef53">  [53]</A> <P>
Hoinkes<A NAME= h_textf54> </A> 
<A Name = textf54> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef54">  [54]</A> considers the 
Epstein/Szasz suggestion of declaring the Treaty to have lapsed 'gratuitous' and suggests that a 
"straightforward reading of the text comes the conclusion that the Treaty cannot be terminated other than 
by exhaustion of either a single period of extension or the last in a series of periods of extension". 
However, it is not easy to extract such a meaning from the text of the Treaty. The Parties certainly may 
choose one of the three stated options, following which the Treaty may expire. However if the Parties do 
not choose one of the options, the Parties could thereby  have chosen not to extend the treaty at all. By 
necessary inference, a Treaty which is not extended has surely expired: otherwise there is no need for 
extension. <P>
Another interpretation is that the Parties may choose 'whether the Treaty shall continue in force 
indefinitely', on the one hand, or whether it 'shall be extended for an additional fixed period or periods' on 
the other. Either choice requires a decision. It must be noted that the Parties could not agree on indefinite 
duration when the Treaty was concluded, thus even if Article X could be said to be the <I>quid pro quo</I> 
for an otherwise indefinite treaty, that compromise resulted in the need for a choice. In other words, a 
second opportunity is presented for the parties to agree on an indefinite duration. It appears difficult to 
conclude that the non-nuclear states may be said to have consented to an indefinite agreement if parties 
cannot reach any agreement at all in 1995, as well as if parties agree to such an agreement, particularly in 
view of the use of the term 'extended': as noted, an indefinite agreement is surely not capable of 
'extension'. The better view is thus that the NPT would expire if no extension agreement is reached. A 
paper presented by Germany on behalf of the European Union similarly concludes that "while the NPT 
would be deemed to be terminated if the Conference failed to take a decision on extension, the 
Conference cannot be closed without a decision on extension pursuant to article X.2." <A NAME=h_textf55> </A> 
<A Name = textf55> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef55">  [55]</A> <P>
Looking at the matter from a different angle, Epstein and Szasz suggest that the Article X(2) option for 
indefinite extension would be otiose if the Treaty was already of indefinite duration.<A NAME=h_textf56> </A> 
<A Name = textf56> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef56">  [56]</A>  The two authors note that if 
the Parties fail to agree on any of the Article X(2) options, an interpretation which would not permit the 
Treaty to expire until one of the Article X(2) conditions are fulfilled is to create an indefinite treaty by 
inaction:<A NAME= h_textf57> </A> 
<A Name = textf57> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef57">  [57]</A>  a result which would 
replace an explicit method of extending the treaty indefinitely by majority agreement with one which would 
extend the treaty indefinitely because majority agreement could not be obtained. This rather attractive view 
is, however, rather difficult to reconcile with Epstein and Szasz's later suggestion that the NPT should be 
considered as staying in effect for up to another five year period, while the parties endeavour to reach 
decision.<A NAME= h_textf58> </A> 
<A Name = textf58> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef58">  [58]</A> Attractive and sensible as 
this suggestion is, it is difficult to extract from the text of Article X. A solution more consistent with Article X 
and more certain would be for the Parties to agree to further additional extension periods subject to 
conditional reviews, the first period being for five years.<P>
Epstein and Szasz suggest an additional option: that if no CTBT is concluded prior to the Extension 
Conference, the Parties may decide to recess the conference and reconvene when a CTBT is concluded 
or some other treaty such as a treaty covering fissionable material for weapons, nuclear disarmament or a 
non-first-use agreement is signed.<A NAME= h_textf59> </A> 
<A Name = textf59> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef59">  [59]</A> However, such a course 
would be controversial and perhaps hazardous, in light of the ambiguous wording of Article X, and may 
open the way for parties to declare their belief that the NPT is at an end, thus giving rise to uncertainty at 
best and further controversy and instability at worst. <P>
It is usefel to refer to the current draft Rules of Procedure in this respect.<P>
<H3><A NAME=h_4_1_1_rules_of_procedure> </A> </H3>
<H3>4.1.1    Rules of Procedure</H3>
Rule 28(3) of the draft Rules of Procedure for the 1995 NPT Review and Extension Conference<A NAME= h_textf60> </A> 
<A Name = textf60> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef60">  [60]</A>  provides that:<P>
(a)  The requirements of paragraph 2 of article X of the Treaty shall be considered met 
when there is a consensus in support of a proposal made in accordance with that 
paragraph,  provided that the Conference is quorate as defined in Rule 13.<A NAME= h_textf61> </A> 
<A Name = textf61> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef61">  [61]</A> <P>
(b)  If, notwithstanding the best efforts of delegates to achieve a consensus decision 
on extension, a proposal or proposals come up for voting, the President shall defer the  
vote for 48 hours and during this period of deferment shall make every effort, with the 
assistance of the General Committee, to facilitate the achievement of general 
agreement and shall report to the Conference prior to the end of the period.<P>
(c)  If by the end of the period of deferment the Conference has not reached a 
consensus decision on the extension, voting shall take place and the decision shall be 
taken by a  majority of the Parties to the Treaty, in accordance with paragraph 2 of 
article X.<P>
(d)  The Conference may be closed only when the decision required by paragraph 2 of 
article X of the Treaty has been reached.<P>
Thus the draft Rules contemplate that the Conference remains open until a majority decision has been 
reached. Under draft Rule 20,  a representative may at any time move the suspension or the adjournment 
of the meeting. No discussion on such motions shall be permitted and such motions shall, subject to rule 
23,<A NAME= h_textf62> </A> 
<A Name = textf62> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef62">  [62]</A>  be immediately put to the 
vote.<P>
Paragraph 16 of the German paper<A NAME= h_textf63> </A> 
<A Name = textf63> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef63">  [63]</A>  claims that it is implicit that 
the Treaty must continue in force while the Conference is in session and that therefore while the 
Conference is suspended or adjourned the Treaty continues in force. To avoid this possibility, however, 
would appear to require a mechanism for restricting the duration of a suspension or adjournment. As 
neither the Treaty nor the draft Rules of Procedure for the Conference give guidance on the possible 
duration of such a suspension or adjournment it would seem necessary to specify the suspension and 
adjournment options possible in the Rules of Procedure or by a Resolution of the Conference as part of 
any suspension or adjournment decision. If this was the means chosen, it would seem desirable for the 
Parties to have the possibility of restricting this in terms of limits on the duration of any suspension or 
adjournment. However it should be emphasized that in view of the difficulties of interpretation surrounding 
Article X and the termination of the Treaty, any suspension or adjournment of the NPT beyond the current 
meeting may give rise to claims by Parties that the Treaty has terminated. Thus use of suspension or 
adjournment as a device for <I>de facto</I> unlimited extension would be controversial at best and at 
would be likely to give rise to instability and uncertainty as to the status of the Treaty. In particular, 
suspension may be viewed as such a device, as may be any adjournment of excessive length or without a 
specific timetable attached.<P>
If the draft Rule of Procedure 28(3)(d) is adopted by the 1995 Conference as drafted, the Conference will 
not be able to be terminated without taking a decision pursuant to Article X.2, and thus the possibility of an 
automatic termination of the NPT by a failure to reach a majority decision on an extension option would 
thus be averted provided that an attempt at indefinite or long term suspension or adjournment is not made 
so as to give rise to uncertainty as to the continued viability of the Treaty. This would then appear to 
strengthen the importance of the conditions which need to be attached to any suspension or adjournment 
decision of the 1995 Conference to ensure that the Treaty remains in force during the suspension or 
adjournment period.<P>
In conclusion, Article X is far from clear and there is a difficult question of interpretation which will be 
resolved by standard rules of interpretation including reference to the context of Article X and the 
subsequent practice of the parties at the extension conference and possibly beyond.<P>
<H2><A NAME=h_4_2_timing_of_the_decision> </A> </H2>
<H2>4.2    Timing of the Decision</H2>
One tactical issue is the timing of the extension of the decision. John Simpson of Southampton University 
has noted<A NAME= h_textf64> </A> 
<A Name = textf64> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef64">  [64]</A>  that Foreign Ministers may 
be present during the early part of the conference, and any decision made at this time could strengthen 
the legitimacy of the vote and avoid the necessity of reference of delegates to capitals for decisionmaking. 
However, there are far stronger arguments for the decision to be made at the end of the conference, when 
the review process would have been completed. The latter would with respect appear to be the more 
logical solution, as the conclusions of the review would be available to crucial in assisting any extension 
decision. This approach would also allow more time for consultation and negotiation.<P>
Preparatory Committee meetings have been held throughout 1993 and 1994<A NAME= h_textf65> </A> 
<A Name = textf65> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef65">  [65]</A>  to settle procedural issues. 
At present, the conference is due to consist of a plenary session of 5-10 days in which heads of delegation 
will make formal opening statements, a following period of 5-10 days in which committees will examine the 
implementation of the NPT and a final period of 5-7 days when a drafting committee and other groups will 
attempt to finalize the Final Document.<P>
<H2><A NAME=h_4_3_indefinite_extension> </A> 
</H2>
<H2>4.3     Indefinite Extension</H2>
In the absence of  a comprehensive test ban treaty and treaty towards nuclear and general disarmament, 
it seems unlikely that the requisite majority of the Parties would agree on indefinite extension, although the 
United States strongly favors this option,<A NAME= h_textf66> </A> 
<A Name = textf66> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef66">  [66]</A>  as apparently do the Group 
of Seven,<A NAME= h_textf67> </A> 
<A Name = textf67> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef67">  [67]</A> and officials from a 
considerable number of countries including, to name a few, Argentina,<A NAME= h_textf68> </A> 

<A Name = textf68> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef68">  [68]</A>  Australia,<A NAME=h_textf69> </A> 
<A Name = textf69> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef69">  [69]</A>  Germany,<A NAME=h_textf70> </A> 
<A Name = textf70> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef70">  [70]</A>  Russia<A NAME=h_textf71> </A> 
<A Name = textf71> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef71">  [71]</A>  and Japan<A NAME=h_textf72> </A> 
<A Name = textf72> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef72">  [72]</A>  have at some time 
expressed a preference for an indefinite extension. On the other hand, an Indonesian official<A NAME=h_textf73> </A> 
<A Name = textf73> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef73">  [73]</A>  favours a CTBT prior to the 
extension conference and a comprehensive review prior to any extension decision and an Iranian 
Ambassador<A NAME= h_textf74> </A> 
<A Name = textf74> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef74">  [74]</A>  has called for agreements 
on the peaceful use of nuclear energy, a CTBT, security assurances, agreements on an attack on nuclear 
facilities, disarmament and a nuclear-weapon-free zone in the Middle East. The Mauritius Minister of 
External Relations<A NAME= h_textf75> </A> 
<A Name = textf75> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef75">  [75]</A>  has called for an extension 
of ten to fifteen years allowing linkage to progress on nuclear disarmament and a CBTB and negotiations 
surrounding the discriminatory nature of the Treaty.<P>
Hoinkes, arguing for an indefinite extension<A NAME= h_textf76> </A> 
<A Name = textf76> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef76">  [76]</A>  argues that Article X 
provides only one shot at unlimited duration. <A NAME= h_textf77> </A> 
<A Name = textf77> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef77">  [77]</A>  She accepts that unlimited 
duration was unachievable by consensus at the time the Treaty was concluded and argues that "if a 
majority of the parties does not opt for unlimited duration after twenty-five years, the opportunity is lost, 
unless the Treaty is amended, and if a majority of the parties opts for extension for a single fixed period or 
a series of fixed periods, the Treaty will expire at the end of the period or periods unless it is amended."<A NAME= h_textf78> </A> 
<A Name = textf78> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef78">  [78]</A> It would appear correct that 
the option of indefinite duration as such is only available at the extension conference. However as a 
suitably large number of fixed periods - such as one hundred five year periods, for the sake of argument - 
subject to conditions, which are not excluded by Article X, may for all practical purposes approximate an 
extension of indefinite duration, the point seems academic. In fact the main substantive difference 
between the two results would be that multiple fixed term renewal would provide an opportunity for regular 
review to ensure the Treaty is achieving its objectives in a way that indefinite extension would not, and 
thus may be more consistent with the objects and principles of the Treaty, with the expressed wishes of 
many non-nuclear states to link extension with progress towards the Article VI objects and particularly a 
CTBT<A NAME= h_textf79> </A> 
<A Name = textf79> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef79">  [79]</A>  and with the existing review 
provisions in Article VIII.<P>
In that light the argument that the extension conference provides the only opportunity for indefinite 
extension appears more a procedural or political tactic than a substantive choice. <P>
<H2><A NAME=h_4_4_extension_for_an_additional_fix
> </A> </H2>
<H2>4.4    Extension for an Additional Fixed 
Period</H2>
If one fixed period is chosen, the treaty would terminate at the expiration of that period, which could be of 
any duration. No further extension would be possible without further agreement of the parties and 
amendment of the NPT. While it has been argued that only one extension conference is authorized by 
Article X and that an amendment of the Treaty  would be necessary to permit such a conference,<A NAME= h_textf80> </A> 
<A Name = textf80> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef80">  [80]</A>  it would be unduly 
restrictive to argue that a further conference is not permitted by Article X: Article X is silent on the matter. 
Parties, or non-Parties, for that matter, could still agree outside the NPT to hold a further conference to 
discuss possible extension by amendment, for instance. No breach of the NPT would be thereby incurred 
by the conference alone. Likewise, while obviously further extension of the treaty under the majority 
provisions of Article X(2) would not be possible,<A NAME= h_textf81> </A> 
<A Name = textf81> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef81">  [81]</A>  there is no reason parties 
cannot otherwise agree prior to or at subsequent termination to renew the treaty by amendment.<A NAME= h_textf82> </A> 
<A Name = textf82> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef82">  [82]</A>  Clearly such an agreement 
would need to comply with the special majority requirements of Article VIII(2).<A NAME= h_textf83> 
</A> 
<A Name = textf83> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef83">  [83]</A> <P>
Epstein and Szasz have suggested that a majority of the Parties could provide for a single extension, at 
the end of which the parties would again be able to select one of the Article X(2) options.<A NAME=h_textf84> </A> 
<A Name = textf84> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef84">  [84]</A>  While such a view has the 
advantage of flexibility, Article X(2) merely provides for the three options as being applicable after twenty-
five years after entry into force of the Treaty. It would be a lengthy extension to apply the same options 
after some further review period. The better view is that if Parties resolved to renew for one single fixed 
period, then that is the binding decision under Article X(2) and any further extension would have to take 
place under the more formal amendment provisions of Article VIII.<P>
It has been suggested that the extension conference is not authorized to choose a single fixed period to be 
followed by another extension conference.<A NAME= h_textf85> </A> 
<A Name = textf85> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef85">  [85]</A>  This observation is 
misleading at best. It is true that a single fixed period means just that, but there is no prohibition on a 
further conference, if the parties so choose. However any further extension would require a treaty 
amendment. This restriction does not apply to multiple extension periods, with intervening 
conferences.<P>
<H2><A NAME=h_4_5_extension_for_additional_fixed_
> </A> </H2>
<H2>4.5    Extension for Additional Fixed 
Periods</H2>
There can be any number of additional fixed periods, which can themselves be for any duration, including 
a number of fixed periods of different duration. <P>
The conclusion of a comprehensive test ban treaty may have an impact on the duration of the NPT insofar 
as such developments are of a fundamental or vital character.<A NAME= h_textf86> </A> 
<A Name = textf86> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef86">  [86]</A>  Insofar as such a treaty 
would render Article V not only obsolete but effectively repealed as between parties to both instruments,  
although <I>rebus sic stantibus</I> may not strictly speaking apply as a CTBT was in fact foreseen by the 
parties in the preamble,<A NAME= h_textf87> </A> 
<A Name = textf87> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef87">  [87]</A> the possibility significantly 
strengthens the argument for tying any fixed extension periods to developments such as a CTBT.<P>
George Bunn  has suggested multiple twenty-five year renewal periods, automatically renewed unless a 
majority of the Parties decide to terminate the Treaty at the end of any period.<A NAME= h_textf88> 
</A> 
<A Name = textf88> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef88">  [88]</A>  This has the advantage 
that the renewals are explicitly authorized by Article X. Bunn argues that any subsequent review 
conference would simply decide to halt further automatic renewals, and thus would not qualify as an 
extension conference.<A NAME= h_textf89> </A> 
<A Name = textf89> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef89">  [89]</A>  However at first sight this 
may only solve part of the problem. A contrary argument would be that periods fixed by the 1995 extension 
conference are just that, and no subsequent conference may purport to terminate the period. However 
termination by agreement of all the Parties is always permissible under Article 54 of the Vienna 
Convention, 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_54_termination_of_or_withdr"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
upon consultation with contracting States. <P>
Obviously an extension mechanism is equally valid irrespective of the duration of the extension period and 
therefore, for example, extensions of 5 years in duration could offer additional advantages by linking closer 
the review of the operation of the Treaty with decisions to proceed from one extension period to 
another.<P>
Moreover, if Parties to the NPT evince a clear intention in the extension conference and thereafter to 
agree to multiple renewals of the Treaty conditional upon a subsequent event, such as the signing of a 
treaty, or Conference, then such intention should be taken as subsequent agreement between the parties 
regarding the interpretation of the treaty or the application of its provisions under Article 31 of the Vienna 
Convention, 
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_31_general_rule_of_interpre"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>
together with any subsequent practice in the application of the treaty which establishes the 
agreement of the parties regarding its interpretation, and as such would guide the interpretation of Article 
X. This is particularly so as it is difficult to otherwise ascribe a sensible meaning to the words 'or periods', 
as multiple automatic periods are in reality no different than one period if there is no intervening event 
which may render a later period less than inevitable.<P>
In a suggestion perhaps giving rise to a little more difficulty, one or more twenty five year periods with 
review conferences every five years and extension conferences at the end of each period has been 
suggested.<A NAME= h_textf90> </A> 
<A Name = textf90> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef90">  [90]</A>  There certainly seems to 
be no reason that Article VIII.3 should not continue in force so further <I>review</I> conferences are 
permitted. This suggestion may meet with an objection that <I>extension</I> conferences are not, 
however permitted. However, agreement and subsequent practice of the parties can not be excluded as a 
sufficient basis for further conferences, as there are no clear prohibitions of such conferences in the text of 
the Treaty.<P>
<H3><A NAME=h_4_5_1_conditions_for_renewal> </A> </H3>
<H3>4.5.1    Conditions for Renewal</H3>
Different periods could be automatic or predicated upon conditions, as Article X is silent on the matter. 
However the periods must be 'fixed'. This would appear to mean fixed in duration, although perhaps 
another means of fixation through mechanism of the parties or an external mechanism may not be 
excluded. A decision setting a certain number of fixed periods, each contingent upon the satisfaction of 
certain criteria, would appear to satisfy Article X. It has been argued that conditions are required for a 
number of fixed periods, as something must take place before the end of each successive period in order 
to give meaning to the plural 'periods'.<A NAME= h_textf91> </A> 
<A Name = textf91> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef91">  [91]</A> Whether conditions are 
required, they certainly appear consistent with Article X, particularly in light of the existing review 
provisions of Article VIII.<A NAME= h_textf92> </A> 
<A Name = textf92> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef92">  [92]</A> <P>
There are clearly risks associated with setting absolute time-limits to steps to be achieved within each 
extension period. However, the value of being able to specify goals for the performance of the Treaty's 
operation in a given period as a factor relating to its renewal at the end of that period, can also be seen to 
be a valuable mechanism for enhancing the performance of the Treaty. In particular, goals such as a 
CBTB, negotiations and progress towards realization of the Article VI goals would be both tangible and 
directly relevant to the Treaty.<P>
It has been suggested that the treaty does not authorize the Conference to condition the extension 
decision on a CTBT.<A NAME= h_textf93> </A> 
<A Name = textf93> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef93">  [93]</A>  With respect, no restriction 
is nowhere supported by either the text of the NPT nor the <I>traveaux préparatoires, </I>wherein the 
negotiators clearly considered a CBT and other disarmament goals relevant considerations to the duration 
question,<A NAME= h_textf94> </A> 
<A Name = textf94> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef94">  [94]</A>  or by the discussions of the 
Parties to date.<A NAME= h_textf95> </A> 
<A Name = textf95> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef95">  [95]</A>  Notably, Mr Graham does 
not dispute the legality of the attachment of conditions to an extension decision, noting only 'obvious 
dangers' to such an approach and the precedent it would set.<A NAME= h_textf96> </A> 
<A Name = textf96> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef96">  [96]</A>  It would be peculiar, to say 
the least, to permit the attachment of conditions to an extension decision yet not to deny the relevance of 
conditions to the extension decision itself. Mr Graham does agree that a decision for multiple fixed 
extension periods, with a transition mechanism between periods, would be permissible.<A NAME= h_textf97> </A> 
<A Name = textf97> </A>  <A HREF = "#notef97">  [97]</A> <P>
<A NAME=h_4_5_2_the_number_of_multiple_fixed_> </A> </H1>
<H3>4.5.2    The Number of Multiple Fixed Periods</H3>
The question may arise whether the Parties could agree to an open-ended number of fixed periods, each 
being followed by a conference, or whether the number as well as duration of the periods should be fixed. 
It would not seem inconsistent with the Treaty if the Parties agreed to an open-ended number of periods. 
Article X, in providing the option that the Treaty "shall be extended for an additional fixed period or periods" 
would not seem to prohibit what would effectively be an automatic renewal system, or, put another way, an 
indefinite treaty with the possibility of termination at the end of any given fixed period. If the Parties so 
decided, then that decision should colour any interpretation according to Article 31 of the Vienna 
Convention. <P>
<br><A HREF="vien-tr.html#h_article_31_general_rule_of_interpre"> Goto Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</A><br>

<H1><A NAME=h_5_conclusions_and_a_suggested_exten> </A> </H1>

<H1>5.    Conclusions and A Suggested Extension Option</H1>
There is considerable latitude available to the Parties in deciding on whether and how to extend  the 
Treaty under Article X.2. A rolling set of fixed periods of extension with a decision-making mechanism 
linked to conditions between each period addressing the continued extension of the Treaty into the next 
period of extension is fully compatible with the provisions of the NPT.<P>
A failure by a majority of the Parties to reach agreement on an extension option at the 1995 Review and 
Extension Conference could lead to automatic termination at the conclusion of the conference. <P>
Rule 28(3)(d) of the provisional draft Rules of Procedure attempts to prevent this by only permitting the 
Conference to be closed when the decision required by Article X.2 has been reached. It has been 
suggested that it is implicit that the Treaty must continue in force while the Conference is in session and, 
therefore, if the Conference is suspended or adjourned the Treaty continues in force. However to avoid the 
uncertainty as to the Treaty's continued efficacy which would accompany an open-ended suspension or 
adjournment a mechanism would be required for carefully restricting and defining the duration and 
conditions of any suspension or adjournment. As neither the Treaty nor the draft Rules of Procedure for 
the Conference give guidance on the possible duration of such a suspension or adjournment it would seem 
necessary to specify the suspension and adjournment options possible in the Rules of Procedure or by a 
Resolution of the Conference as part of such a decision.<P>
The following components of an NPT extension option are suggested for the consideration of the 
Parties:<P>
1.     extension for an open-ended series of fixed extensions of five years duration;<P>
2.     a Conference between each period to decide whether or not to continue further renewals. A decision 
to proceed with each period of renewal would be taken following a review of the operation of the 
Treaty at a Conference to take place at the end of each 5 year period;<P>
3.     at each such Conference, objectives for the operation of the Treaty in the subsequent 5 yearly 
period or periods shall be specified by the Parties to the Treaty.  <P>These could include:<P>
<uL>
(a)     conclusion of a comprehensive test ban treaty;<P>
(b)     satisfactory ratification and observance of such a treaty;<P>
(c)     good faith negotiations and concrete progress on effective measures moving towards to 
cessation of the nuclear arms race at an early date and to nuclear disarmament; and<P>
(d)     good faith negotiations towards a treaty on general and complete disarmament under strict 
and effective international control.<P>
<P>
</UL>
<P>
<H1><B>Options for Extension of the Non-Proliferation 
Treaty</B><P><B></H1>
