</A> Joint Statement by President Yeltsin and President Clinton, in Paul Ingram  (ed.),  <I>Political 
Aspects</I>, <I>supra</I> note 4, 71.

<p> <A HREF = "#textf72">  [72]<A NAME= notef72> </A> 
 
</A> Statement by Yoshimoto Tanaka, Ambassador of Japan to the Conference on Disarmament,  in 
Paul Ingram  (ed.),  <I>Political Aspects</I>, <I>supra</I> note 4, 67.

<p><A HREF = "#textf73">  [73]<A NAME= notef73> </A> 
 
</A> Letter from Soemadi D.M. Brotodiningrat, Ambassador to the Conference on Disarmament, in 
Paul Ingram  (ed.),  <I>Political Aspects</I>, <I>supra</I> note 4, 64-66.

<p><A HREF = "#textf74">  [74]<A NAME= notef74> </A> 
 
</A> Letter from Kia Tabatabaee, Ambassador and Deputy Permanent Representative to the 
Conference on Disarmament,  in Paul Ingram  (ed.),  <I>Political Aspects</I>, <I>supra</I> note 4, 66-
67.

<p> <A HREF = "#textf75">  [75]<A NAME= notef75> </A> 
 
</A> Speech by Ahmud Swalay Kasenally, Minister of External Relations, in Paul Ingram  (ed.),  
<I>Political Aspects</I>, <I>supra</I> note 4, 68.

<p> <A HREF = "#textf76">  [76]<A NAME= notef76> </A> 
 
</A> Mary Elizabeth Hoinkes, <I>supra</I> note 4, 254, arguing that "[t]o make the NPT the most 
effective instrument it can be, the Treaty needs to have the 'job security' that unlimited duration provides." 
Ms Hoinkes was at the time Acting General Counsel, U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.

<p><A HREF = "#textf77">  [77]<A NAME= notef77> </A> 
 
</A> Mary Elizabeth Hoinkes, <I>supra</I> note 4,252-253.

<p> <A HREF = "#textf78">  [78]<A NAME= notef78> </A> 
 
</A> Mary Elizabeth Hoinkes, <I>supra</I> note 4,252-253.

<p>  <A HREF = "#textf79">  [79]<A NAME= notef79> </A> 
 
</A> See discussion on page 8.

<p>  <A HREF = "#textf80">  [80]<A NAME= notef80> </A> 
 
</A> Hoffmann letter, <I>supra</I> note 47, 3, 4.

<p>  <A HREF = "#textf81">  [81]<A NAME= notef81> </A> 
 
</A> Hoffmann letter, supra note 47, 3.

<p> <A HREF = "#textf82">  [82]<A NAME= notef82> </A> 
 
</A> Vienna Convention, Article 70 reads as follows: 
1. Unless the treaty otherwise provides or the parties otherwise agree, the termination of a treaty under its 
provisions or in accordance with the present Convention: 
(a) releases the parties from any obligation further to perform the treaty;  
(b) does not affect any right, obligation or legal situation of the parties created through the execution of the 
treaty prior to its termination. 
2. If a State denounces or withdraws from a multilateral treaty, paragraph 1 applies in the relations 
between that State and each of the other parties to the treaty from the date when such denunciation or 
withdrawal takes effect.

<p><A HREF = "#textf83">  [83]<A NAME= notef83> </A> 
 
</A> NPT Article VIII.2: "Any amendment to this Treaty must be approved by a majority of the votes of 
all the Parties to the Treaty, including the votes of all nuclear-weapon States Party to the Treaty and all 
other Parties which, on the date the amendment is circulated, are members of the Board of Governors of 
the International Atomic Energy Agency."

<p></A>  <A HREF = "#textf84">  [84]<A NAME= notef84> </A> 
 
</A> 1993 Epstein and Szasz, <I>supra</I> note 4, 756.

<p> </A>  <A HREF = "#textf85">  [85]<A NAME= notef85> </A> 
 
</A> Graham June 18 Statement, <I>supra</I> note 26, 4 and Graham June 10 Statement, 
<I>supra</I> note 26, 2.

<p>  <A HREF = "#textf86">  [86]<A NAME= notef86> </A> 
 
</A> See Elias, <I>supra</I> note 35, 122, noting the observation of the ICJ court in <I>Fisheries 
Jurisdiction (United Kingdom v. Iceland), Jurisdiction of the Court, Judgment</I>, I.C.J. Rep. (1973), 18 
that "changes in the law may under certain conditions constitute valid grounds for invoking a change of 
circumstances affecting the duration of a treaty" where the changes are of a fundamental or vital 
character.

<p> <A HREF = "#textf87">  [87]<A NAME= notef87> </A> 
 
</A> Contrary to the requirement in Article 62(1) of the Vienna Convention.

