<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bcurrent.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>

<P><KBD><a href="#endsadd"><font color="#ff0000">ENDS</font></a> Report 251, December 1995.</KBD>

<P><H2><KBD>Study shows phthalates, APEs reduce sperm counts. </KBD></H2>

<P>Low levels of exposure to oestrogenic chemicals can cause laboratory rats to have lower sperm counts and smaller testes, a scientific study has confirmed (1).  The research gives the first strong experimental evidence to support the hypothesis that exposure to industrial chemicals - particularly phthalates, alkyl phenols and bisphenol A - is responsible for observed declines in human sperm production.  Although the effects seen are not proven to be oestrogenic, they appear to occur at exposures which are below recognised no observed effect levels (NOELs). 

<P>Recent epidemiological studies have reported that men's sperm counts are in decline, while certain male reproductive disorders, including testicular cancer, are on the increase.  Wildlife scientists have drawn parallels with the reproductive problems seen in animal populations affected by pollution and suggest that the effects in man may be the result of exposure to chemicals with hormonal properties.  A recent review of the evidence commissioned by the Department of the Environment from the Institute for Environment and Health concluded that the link was "plausible" (ENDS Report 246, pp 3-5). 

<P>The present study was carried out by Dr Richard Sharpe and colleagues at the Medical Research Council's Reproductive Biology Unit in Edinburgh.  Dr Sharpe fed female rats with chemicals which had been shown to be oestrogenic in vitro assays - butyl benzyl phthalate (BBP) and octyl phenol (OP).  BBP is a plasticiser used in PVC packaging, and OP is a breakdown product of alkyl phenol ethoxylate (APE) detergents.  Both are widespread in the environment.  Another group of rats was fed the APE detergent octyl phenol polyethoxylate (OPP), which shows little or no activity in in vitro oestrogen assays. 

<P>The dose levels were chosen to mimic possible levels of human exposure, and a positive control group of animals was also fed a powerful synthetic oestrogen, diethylstilboestrol (DES), for comparison. 

<P>The rats were mated and their male offspring allowed to grow to maturity, receiving doses of the test compound during postnatal development.  The testis weight, sperm count, and body and organ weights of the offspring were measured at maturity and the results compared with control animals which received no oestrogenic compounds. 

<P>The results showed that male rats exposed to all three test compounds had significantly smaller testes than the controls by a factor of 5-13%.  Sperm counts were also reduced in animals treated with OP and BBP by 10-21%.  DES reduced size and sperm count in exposed animals, but also had other effects on body weight and litter size. 

<P>The researchers found that the testis structure of the treated animals was identical to the controls, but believe that the crucial effect of the chemicals may have been to reduce the number of sperm-producing Sertoli cells.  These are formed only during a fixed window of development, and their number affects the total size and sperm production of the organ. 

<P>The experimental design included three different treatment regimes to test the effects of different lengths of exposure.  All offspring were exposed to oestrogenic chemicals up until weaning, but in one group treatment began after birth, in the second group mothers began treatment two weeks prior to conception, and in the third group the mothers had been exposed for seven weeks before conception. 

<P>The treatment effects were consistent across all three groups, but the animals which received the longest exposure generally showed the most pronounced effects.  The suggestion is that all of the compounds accumulate in mother and offspring and exert a cumulative effect. 

<P>The potency of OPP in the experiment compared to its very weak effects in vitro was also particularly striking.  The researchers attribute this to its metabolism to OP in the animals a reaction which does not occur readily in cell cultures. 

<P>The experimental animals received up to 370æg/kg/day of OP, OPP and BBP, but as the chemicals were administered via drinking water, exposure increased as the animals grew.  The researchers conclude that, at least as far as BBP is concerned, human exposure may approach, but is likely to be less than, the experimental levels.  They note that there appear to be no data on human exposure to OP and APEs. 

<P>Monitoring by the Ministry of Agriculture (MAFF) has shown that many packaged foods contain levels of phthalates in the tens of milligrams per kilogram range (ENDS Report 245, pp 7-8).  The researchers note that one study has shown that foil-packed butter contained close to 50mg/kg of BBP. Consumption of 50g per day of this product alone would give a 60kg person an intake of 40 microgrammes/kg body weight/day, leading them to recommend that "further studies on the oestrogenicity of phthalates should be a priority."

<P>The study does not prove that the effects of the compounds are caused by oestrogenic or other hormonal mechanisms.  However, given the current understanding of the possible developmental effects of hormone-disrupting compounds, such mechanisms do appear highly probable. 

<P>Dr Sharpe was not available for comment as the paper appeared in print.  But co-author Professor John Sumpter of Brunel University said: "I was surprised at the relatively low level at which the effects were seen."  He added: "I am pretty certain that human exposure to BBP is less than in the experiment, but that is a single chemical and what is more realistic is simultaneous exposure to several compounds at lower levels."  Experiments along these lines should be a priority for future research, he recommended. 

<P>Professor Sumpter also confirmed that Dr Sharpe has completed studies on bisphenol-A - a compound known to have oestrogenic properties which has been found to leach into food from the epoxy lining of some metal cans (ENDS Report 246, p3).  Bisphenol-A was also found to cause a reduction in rat testis size and sperm production. 

<P>Dr Sharpe's results suggest that several oestrogenic chemicals may have significant effects at levels much lower than those previously regarded as toxicologically significant.  For example, the researchers note that the established NOEL of BBP for testicular toxicity in rats is 125-150mg/kg body weight/day, a factor of 300 higher than the doses shown to be effective in the experiment. 

<P>Gwynne Lyons, scientific consultant to the Worldwide Fund for Nature, commented: "The results call into question previous NOELs for environmental chemicals.  These effects are subtle and not easily seen.  Industry needs to look more closely at its toxicity testing protocols." 

<P>Geoff Randall, who chairs a European Centre for Ecotoxicology and Toxicology Of Chemicals (ECETOC) task force on environmental oestrogens, said that the paper was "an interesting piece of work but not sufficiently thorough to test the hypothesis [that industrial chemicals affect human sperm counts] fully."  He added: "The trouble is we don't know the dose.  The materials are in the drinking water and we can't plot a dose/response curve."  More robust studies are needed to quantify the effects and explain their relationship to effects in humans, he concluded. 


<P><B>(1).</B> Sharpe, R.M. et al.  1995, Environmental Health Perspectives, Vol 103 (12), pp 1136-1143. 



