<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bcurrent.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>

<P><H3><KBD>ENDS Report 246, July 1995, pp.3-5.</KBD></H3>



<P><H3><KBD>DoE report understates evidence of oestrogen pollution </KBD></H3>


<P>There is convincing evidence of a decline in human reproductive health but no evidence of a causal link with oestrogenic chemicals, a review commissioned by the Department of the Environment (DoE) has concluded.1 

<P>However, some of the chemicals which are of most concern - notably phthalates and bisphenol-A - barely get a mention. The review is also in danger of understating the full force of the scientific argument behind current concerns because of its focus on gaps in the evidence. 

<P>The report was commissioned from the Institute of Environment and Health (IEH) in response to growing concern about the possible impacts of oestrogen-mimicking chemicals on the reproductive health of human and wildlife populations. It reviews much ofthe scientific evidence to emerge in recent years (ENDS Reports 226, pp 21-24, and 243, pp 15-19). 

<P>On human health effects, the IEH found the evidence of increases in breast and testicular cancers "particularly convincing". The incidence of hypospadias - a deformation of the penis - has also increased substantially, it says. But on the question of sperm counts, it concludes only that "the balance of evidence suggests a downward trend", while trends in undescended testes and male breast cancer are even less certain. 

<P>The report barely considers possible biological mechanisms connecting these health trends with environmental oestrogens, and finds other hypotheses explaining them to be "plausible". 

<P>Findings in wildlife - such as vitellogenic responses in fish exposed to oestrogenic effluents (see pp 5-6) and reproductive failure in alligators exposed to organo-chlorine pesticides - "increase the concern", it says. 

<P>But the report's bottom line is that "a causal relationship between exposure to environmental oestrogens and adverse effects on human reproductive health has not yet been established. Further information from epidemiological and experimental studies is still needed to allow assessments of risk to be made based on a weight of evidence approach." 

<P>The report was welcomed by Environment Secretary John Gummer as "a sound basis for taking forward our policies." It "reinforces the need for further research to clarify whether real problems exist," he said. 

<P>The report suggests many topics for future research. One key area is evolving standardised tests for oestrogenic effects. A widely used human breast cancer cell assay has been criticised by industry specialists because its oestrogen receptor is believed to be abnormal. 

<P>Assessments of human exposures to key chemicals of concern are also needed. These include phthalate plasticisers, alkylphenol ethoxylates (APEs) and the epoxy resin monomer bisphenol-A (see p 3). A dietary study of phthalates in food is due to be completed by the Ministry of Agriculture (MAFF) early next year but other sources of exposure also need to be examined. MAFF studies have already suggested that environmental and food processing sources may be significant (ENDS Report 245, pp 7-8). 

<P>The UK is also cornmitted to conducting risk assessments on alkylphenols as part of an EC programme of testing bulk industrial chemicals. Other research priorities are more long term, such as establishing a baseline of sperm counts to assess whether these are declining. 

<P>However, research most likely to push the issue forward has already been completed by Dr Richard Sharpe and colleagues at the Medical Research Council's Reproductive Biology Unit in Edinburgh. In a television interview in July, he said that he had results awaiting publication which show that low-level exposure of pregnant rats to phthalates caused a reduction in testis weight in their male offspring. The changes were induced by levels comparable to human dietary exposures. Other oestrogenic compounds, including bisphenol-A and alkylphcnols, proved to have similar effects. 

<P>Speaking at the report's launch, IEH Director Professor Lewis Smith acknowledged the importance of Dr Sharpe's findings. "If these effects are convincingly demonstrated in rats then my personal view is that there should be action," he said. "It would be a case of using the precautionary principle." 

<P>The view of the DoE, IEH and Dr Sharpe remains, however, that there is at present insufficient evidence on any compound for regulatory action. But Friends of the Earth and the Worldwide Fund for Nature (WWF) have criticised the Government for failing to act now on a precautionary basis. 

<P>For the Chemical Industries Association (CIA), Liz Surkovic suggested that the reproductive effects may have been caused by "lifestyle changes". Consumption of fat, fibre and phytoestrogens had all changed in the last fifty years, she said. But she declined to repeat to ENDS earlier CIA allegations that tight underpants were responsible. 

<P>In press statements, the CIA, the British Plastics Federation (BPF) and the Soap and Detergent Industries Association all highlighted the relatively “weak” oestrogenic activity of chemicals like APEs and phthalates. This is one poinl not covered fully by the IEH review. Although these artificial oestrogens are 1,000 times less active than natural oestrogen in cell assays, the comparison ls a false one. 

<P>As the report notes, natural oestrogens are bound to proteins in the blood stream called sex hormone binding globulins (SHBG). These lower the effectivc concentration of oestrogen in the body and mediate its effects. However, there is good reason to believe that the mechanism does not work for artificial oestrogens 

<P>In general, binding to the oestrogen receptor is non-specific. Binding to SHBG proteins is much more specific and some artificial oestrogens, such as the drug diethyl stilboestrol, are known not to bind to SHBG. The absence of this control mechanism will amplify the effects of these compounds. 

<P>Research on the effect of APEs on fish has also found that in vitro assays underestimate the oestrogenic effects of the detergents on living animals by l00 times (see pp 5-6). The effects are probably due to the length of the exposure and to bioaccumulation. 

<P>The IEH is also open to criticism for giving only a passing mention to phthalates and bisphenol-A. A BPF spokesman told ENDS that phthalates were therefore "not a chemical of concern". However, the DoE told ENDS that their omission had been purely a matter of  timing because key papers implicating them have only been published in recent weeks. "Phthalate esters are at the top of our list," the DoE says. 

<P>As reported last month, studies by MAFF have shown that phthalate plasticisers are present in some foods in the tens of milligrams per kilogram range. Migration from packaging is one of the major sources. However, the different branches of the packaging industry are all denying responsibility for the contamination. 

<P>The BPF and the European Council of Plastics and Intermediates (ECPI) told ENDS that phthalate levels in plastic packaging are negligible. The ECPI said that "printing inks, adhesives and coatings are the major applications." 

<P>Moira Macmillan of the British Coatings Federation (BCF) admitted that phthalates were present in inks but declined to give levels. She also said that "printing inks cannot be the only source", but when pressed was unable to give any figures to justify the claim. 

<P>The BCF represents ink and coating manufacturers but has not taken a stand on the phthalates issue. It says that its members are taking different views. Some are talking to their customers about substitution, while others believe the issue will affect specialist applications and are delaying action until it is forced on them. 

<P>Industry associations such as the BCF and ECPI are failing to acknowledge the severity of the situation by taking refuge in dubious statements from MAFF. A recent study of foods packaged in paper and board concluded, MAFF has said, that estimated phthalate intakes from these sources would be "well within tolerable levels", and that even the intakes of extreme consumers "would be well within the respective tolerable daily intakes (TDIs)." 

<P>The statements do not stand up to scrutiny. MAFF has not yet considered total dietary intakes of phthalates, and rough calculations from previous MAFF studies on a wide range of foods suggest that TDIs - which were in any event not intended to protect against oestrogenic effects - could easily be exceeded. 


<P>WWF's pollution consultant Gwynne Lyons commented: "The Department of Health's Committee on Toxicology said that phthalates were insufficiently tested in 1987, and repeated the warning in 1990. Industry is culpable and wanton for not testing them." 


<P><B>1</B> Environmenlal oestrogens: Consequences to human health and wildlife, from IEH, University of Leicester, PO Box 138, Lancaster Road, Leicester LE1 9HN, £15.00. 


<P>Reproduced courtesy of <a href="http://www.ends.co.uk/"><font color="#ff0000">ENDS</font></a><BR>
Finsbury Business Centre<BR>
40 Bowling Green Lane<BR>
London EC1 0NE



</td></tr>
</table>
