<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bcurrent.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>

<P><H3><KBD>"The Emasculators" by Dr Charles Tyler.</KBD></H3>

<P><H3><KBD>Originally published in BBC Wildlife Magazine.</KBD></H3>

<P>Male fish producing yolk. Female terns pairing up with each other. A lake’s 
turtles with only one sex among them. Declining sperm counts in pumas, 
belugas and humans. What’s happening to the world’s boys? Dr Charles 
Tyler looked in the water.  
Looking back, I suppose it was obvious from the start that something was 
seriously wrong. Feminised fish were turning up in British rivers, and no one 
knew why. Before long we had a major detective story on our hands – with a plot 
and a named cast of suspects worthy of any conventional whodunit.

<P>It all started with some findings on the roach, a fish whose very name conjures 
up images of lazy summer afternoons on the river. At one site, near a sewage 
outlet on a river in south-eastern Britain, biologists began to find roach with both 
male and female sex organs. Images of summer afternoons rapidly gave way to 
an altogether more disturbing picture. 

<P>When we heard about the findings, my colleague John Sumpter and I suspected 
that the sewage effluent might be harbouring some chemical that was affecting 
sexual development. We found that male fish downstream of the sewage outlet 
were producing a protein normally found only in females – something we had 
already noticed in some other fish populations. The protein in question was 
vitellogenin, a component of the nutritious yolk that females pack into their eggs. 
If males were making it, the natural order was being turned on its head. 
Disconcerting as it was, the discovery gave us an important clue. Female fish 
make yolk protein in response to oestrogen, the sex hormone in their 
bloodstream. Perhaps male fish were making the protein because of some 
chemical in the river with oestrogen-like effects.
John and I felt we had to find out whether male fish were becoming feminised 
elsewhere in the UK. From 1989 to 1991, with help from the Ministry of 
Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, we placed groups of rainbow trout in rivers at 
more than 20 sites around the country, each of which was below a discharge 
from a sewage-treatment works. When we analysed the blood samples, we 
couldn’t believe our eyes: male rainbow trout at every site had yolk protein in 
their blood - a sure sign of sexual disruption.

<P>Even more remarkable was the amount of yolk protein involved. After just three 
weeks’ exposure, the trout had up to 100,000 times more yolk protein in their 
blood than was normal in male fish – more than half of their blood protein was 
yolk. This was incredible, for these were levels typical of fully mature females. 
To check our findings, we repeated the work with a native fish, the carp. We got 
similar results. Our original discovery was not a one-off: fish populations up and 
down the country were being exposed to oestrogenic chemicals. But what were 
they and where were they coming from? 

<P>As we were piecing together this astonishing story, a similar tale was unfolding 
in the US. Researchers from the US Fish and Wildlife Service were investigating 
a dramatic decline in the alligator population in Lake Apopka, Florida, when they 
found that more than half the juvenile males had abnormally small penises, and 
many had unusual testes. Most of the males were sterile and had abnormally 
high levels of oestrogen in their blood. Turtles from the same lake were faring no 
better, for nearly all were female. Something, it seemed, was feminising the 
lake’s reptiles. 

<P>There was more. On the Pacific coast of the US, western gulls and common and 
roseate terns had also been experiencing problems. The sex ratio had tipped in 
favour of females, and so females were pairing with one another, producing 
large clutches of infertile eggs. Some of the males had developed female sex 
organs, while others had simply lost their sex drive and failed to arrive at the 
breeding colonies.

<P>The mystery deepened further when reproductive anomalies turned up in 
mammals, too. Biologists studying the last remaining Florida cougars (a 
subspecies of puma) reported that males were producing less sperm than they 
should, and what they did produce tended to be abnormal. Not only were the 
cougars having to contend with mercury contamination and a dwindling gene 
pool – there are only 30-50 of them left in the wild – they were also facing a tide 
of feminising pollutants.

<P>As I read more widely, more of these sad tales emerged. Beluga whales at the 
polluted mouth of the St Lawrence River, in Canada, were experiencing 
reproductive problems. Pallid sturgeon in the Missouri and Mississippi rivers 
hadn’t bred in 10 years. Fish in the Great Lakes were being feminised, along 
with the bald eagles. Worldwide, there were declines in populations of 
amphibians and many birds. Could these problems also stem from oestrogenic 
chemicals in the environment? Most of the evidence was circumstantial. What 
we needed was proof that some man-made chemical was responsible. 
We began to search for suspects. One of the first chemicals to come under 
suspicion in our work on fish was a component of the contraceptive pill – the 
man-made oestrogen, ethinyl oestradiol. This compound seemed a good 
candidate because millions of women take the pill in the UK, and it is a very 
powerful substance indeed. Researchers have reported finding it in British river 
water.

<P>But when we tested this theory we found that much of the ethinyl oestradiol 
excreted by women is in a modified form that is inactive in fish, and it seemed 
unlikely that this compound was the cause of the problem. Even so, more 
research will be needed before we can eliminate it from our inquiries, not least 
because of signs that bacteria at sewage works may be able to turn the inactive 
form back into the active form.

<P>Another suspect emerged - quite by chance - from work by Dr Ana Soto at Tufts 
University in the US. Dr Soto was working on breast cancer cells that need 
oestrogen to divide, when she noticed that a substance leaching from plastic 
tubing was stimulating the cells to divide, as though it were an oestrogen. The 
substance was nonylphenol.

<P>Nonylphenol is a breakdown product of a class of chemicals called 
alkylphenolethoxylates (APEOs). APEOs are used mainly in detergents of one 
kind or another, but they turn up in a huge range of other items too, including 
paints, herbicides, food packaging and personal-care products. Industry uses 
about 300,000 tonnes of APEOs every year, 60 per cent of which ends up in the 
water – drinking water included. Nonylphenol is a significant pollutant in some 
UK rivers, particularly those receiving waste from the textile industry.

<P>Sue Jobling, a new recruit to our team, decided to find out whether this 
substance acted as an artificial oestrogen in fish. It did. When male fish were 
exposed to nonylphenol - as well as a number of other breakdown products of 
APEOs - they started to produce yolk protein, and their testes grew more slowly 
than usual. Here at last was some hard evidence. It looked as if nonylphenol and 
its chemical relatives could be responsible, at least in part, for the strange 
effects we had noticed in fish.

<P>But this was only part of the story, for researchers around the world were 
studying a wide range of other chemicals that could mimic oestrogens. In 
Florida, for instance, the unhappy fate of Lake Apopka’s reptiles was attributed 
to a DDT-like insecticide, dicofol, 30,000 gallons of which were accidentally 
released into the lake in 1980. The feminisation of California’s gulls was blamed 
on releases of DDT in industrial waste between 1950 and the mid-1970s. The 
idea that DDT and its chemical relatives could cause these problems was not a 
surprise: more than 30 years ago, intersex mosquitoes started to appear after 
several generations of exposure to DDT.

<P>Other pollutants have now joined the catalogue of suspects. Polychlorinated 
biphenyls (PCBs), for example, are probably responsible for reproductive 
abnormalities in tern colonies on Bird Island, off the Massachusetts coast. PCBs 
are used in sealants, plastics and paints - and something like 20 tonnes enter 
the North Sea annually. Also under suspicion are polycyclic aromatic 
hydrocarbons (PAHs) - chemical contaminants that come from the burning of 
natural fuels and from oil spillages - and some plasticisers. Although 
governments now restrict the use of some of these compounds, huge quantities 
persist in the environment because they resist breakdown by microbes.

<P>Other candidates include oestrogen-like compounds produced by plants and 
fungi. If these substances reach watercourses in large amounts – as could 
happen if cattle slurry passes untreated into a river, say – then they, too, could 
create problems for fish. 

<P>With so many chemicals under suspicion, we realised that animals would 
probably be exposed to a number of oestrogenic compounds at once. This would 
certainly be true of fish in UK rivers. But would the effects of the different 
chemicals be additive, or not? We did some more tests. We found that when 
animals were exposed to a mixture of oestrogenic compounds, the effects of the 
different chemicals were indeed additive. Ecologists, it seems, have to consider 
the entire cocktail of chemicals if they are to understand their potential effects.

<P>To make matters worse, most chemicals that mimic oestrogens have two 
troublesome properties. They tend to build up in the tissues of an animal with 
time, particularly when it spends most of its life in polluted water. They also tend 
to accumulate at the top of food chains. As big fish eat little fish, they take on an 
extra load of oestrogenic pollutants, then pass them on to the creatures that eat 
them – and so on. Some animals end up with levels of pollution 100,000 times 
higher than levels in the environment. Under these conditions, chemicals that 
are only weakly oestrogenic build up to the point where they start having serious 
effects.

<P>Our work has focused on fish and other wildlife, but there are signs that males of 
our own species may also be reacting to oestrogens in the environment. Sperm 
counts have fallen, while reproductive disorders have all increased over the last 
few decades. The reason for these changes is unknown, but exposure to 
environmental pollution by oestrogen-like substances could be playing a part, 
according to Dr Richard Sharpe of the Medical Research Council’s Reproductive 
Biology Unit, Edinburgh, and Professor Niels Skakkebaek of the University of 
Copenhagen. It is well known that oestrogens can affect the developing embryo. 
From the late 1940s to the early 1970s, some pregnant women were treated with 
diethylstilboestrol - a man-made oestrogen - to reduce the risk of miscarriage. 
The drug caused reproductive disorders in babies of both sexes.
The detective story is far from over. There are more than 60,000 man-made 
chemicals in regular use - not to mention their breakdown products – and a 
surprisingly large number are turning out to have oestrogen-like effects. (At least 
one pollutant, tributyl tin from ‘anti-fouling’ paints, is having the opposite effect, 
causing female whelks to develop penises.) There is little doubt that more 
compounds will join the list of suspects as research continues.

<P>And then there is the biggest unknown of them all. We do not yet know whether 
we are dealing with a major global problem or a localised one, affecting specific 
places such as the Great Lakes, toxic dumps and sewage outfalls. We need to 
find out. If it is global, then it is potentially very serious indeed, with huge 
implications for wildlife and humans.



<P><B>FACT FILE 1</B>
<P>Egg-makers

<P>Animals control their physiology by deploying a wide variety of hormones and 
other chemical messengers. Oestrogens govern the development of female 
sexual characteristics and help control reproductive cycles. They belong to the 
great class of steroid hormones and are close cousins of testosterone and 
cortisol. They are produced mainly by the ovary. 

<P>In mammals, the genetic make-up of an individual decides its sex, and the sex 
hormones – testosterone in males, oestrogen in females – reinforce that 
decision. In birds, reptiles, amphibians and fish the situation is rather different. 
Regardless of genetic make-up, individuals develop as females if oestrogen is 
present and as males if it is absent. In these animals, exposure to oestrogen-like 
chemicals during a critical period of development is enough to feminise the 
embryo. Such a ‘female’ may have ovaries and produce eggs, despite being 
genetically male.

<P><B>FACT FILE 2</B>
<P>Hormone hunt

<P>One way of finding out if male fish have been exposed to oestrogen-like 
chemicals is to look for yolk protein in their blood. As part of the normal 
reproductive process, female egg-laying animals make a special yolk protein 
and pack it into their eggs as a food store for their developing young. The 
protein is produced by the liver – in response to oestrogen – then transported to 
the ovary, where it is taken up by the eggs.

<P>Males also have the biochemical machinery for making yolk protein inside the 
liver, but the machinery normally lies idle simply because there is no oestrogen 
to switch it on. But if they are exposed to oestrogens – in polluted rivers, say – 
the machinery switches on and yolk protein builds up in their blood. 

<P>Researchers have developed a second test for checking whether specific 
chemicals act as oestrogens. In some reptiles, sex determination depends on 
temperature; at a high temperature, eggs develop as females, while at a lower 
temperature, they develop as males. (Intermediate temperatures give a mixture 
of males and females.) The test makes use of the fact that eggs exposed to 
oestrogens develop as females, even at a low temperature. The test involves 
painting the eggs with the chemical on trial and then incubating them at a low 
temperature, which normally produces males. If the chemical is oestrogenic, 
then a proportion of the hatchlings will be female.

<P><B>FACT FILE 3</B>
<P>Skeleton keys

<P>Oestrogens are small molecules with large effects. They enter cells with ease, 
where they meet and cling to molecules that act as specific oestrogen 
‘receptors’. As a result of this encounter, the receptors are triggered into an 
active state, whereupon they attach to DNA and switch on certain genes. 

<P>An oestrogen molecule and its receptor are like a key and its lock: only the 
correct key will undo the mechanism. But real locks are vulnerable to anything 
from a skeleton key to a jemmy – and the same seems true of these minute 
chemical structures. Some man-made chemicals ‘unlock’ oestrogen receptors 
because they have a similar structure to oestrogen, and so fit the lock. 
Many environmental pollutants bear no structural relationship to natural 
oestrogens – the key is radically different – and yet they still manage to switch 
on genes that are normally under the control of oestrogen. How they do this is 
still unknown.<P>
<B>Author:			Dr Charles Tyler<BR>
First published in:	BBC Wildlife Magazine, June 1995</B>
</td></tr>
