<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bsources.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<H3><KBD>Where do hormone disrupting chemicals come from and how are they getting into the environment?</KBD></H3>
<P>
There are a large number of synthetic chemicals in the environment that have been identified as potential hormone disrupters, and more are being found as further research is undertaken. Many of these chemicals are very widely used, and the routes by which they get into the environment are varied.
<P>
However two known hormone disrupters that are of particular concern - dioxins and phthalates - have a common source - PVC. 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo-p-dioxin,or TCDD, is one of the most toxic chemicals known, and phthalates are the most abundant synthetic chemicals in the environment.(1)
<P>
The formation of dioxins is an inevitable result of the oxychlorination process via which 1,2-dichloroethane, and thence vinyl chloride are produced. This process provides ideal conditions for the formation of dioxins. ICI themselves admit that: "it is difficult to see how any of these conditions could be modified so as to prevent PCDD/PCDF (dioxin/furan) formation without seriously impairing the reaction for which the process is designed."(2) Most of these dioxins end up in organochlorine waste which is then buried or incinerated, and others are discharged in effluent.(3)  
<P>
Dioxins are also formed when chlorinated organic compounds, or a mixture of inorganic chloride and organic matter are burned. PVC is a major source of chlorine in municipal waste incinerators (contributing 67% according to the Danish EPA) (4)
<P>
Dioxins resist breakdown in the environment, accumulate in the fatty tissue of living organisms and concentrate in increasing levels as they pass up through the food chain.
We all now carry significant levels of dioxin in our bodies.
<P>
The second group of hormone disrupting chemicals linked to PVC is the phthalates. They are one of a plethora of additives - plasticisers, colorants, biocides, lubricants, flame retardants, impact modifiers, fillers and stabilisers - that are needed to make PVC usable, in this case they make it flexible.
<P>
Three phthalates - Di(2-ethylhexyl)phthalate (DEHP), butyl benzyl phthalate (BBP) and di-n-butyl phthalate (DBP) - have been found to be oestrogenic.(5) Others have not yet been tested. They have been shown to reduce sperm counts in rats(6) and are implicated in observed declines in human sperm counts. According to the European Council for Plasticisers and Intermediates 95% of phthalates are used in the production of flexible PVC.(7)
<P>
This link with dioxin and phthalates is one reason why Greenpeace is campaigning for an end to PVC production. 20 million tonnes of PVC is produced every year. It does not biodegrade, it cannot be effectively recycled and it cannot be safely disposed of. Many of the chemicals that are emerging as hormone disrupters are linked  to chlorine production and PVC consumes about one third of all chlorine produced.
<P> 
Alternatives already exist for virtually all uses of PVC. By using these alternatives and phasing out PVC, a major source of hormone disrupting chemicals can be eliminated.
<P>

<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>

<B>1</B> Murature DA, et al. (1987), Phthalate esters and semen quality  parameters. Biomed Environ Mass Spectrom 13:473-477. Quoted in Jobling S., et al. (1995) in Environmental Health Perspectives 103(6) : pp 582-587.<BR>
<B>2</B>  ICI (1994), Report to the Chief Inspector, HMIP authorisation AK6039.<BR>
<B>3</B>  ENDS Report 251, Dec 1995 p3.<BR>
<B>4</B>  Danish EPA (1995), Environmental Project No.313, "Environmental Aspects of  PVC", pp 88<BR>   
<B>5 </B> Jobling S., et al. (1995) in Environmental Health Perspectives 103(6) : pp 582-587<BR>
<B>6 </B> Richard M Sharpe et al. (1995), Gestational and Lactational Exposure of Rats to Xenoestrogens Results in Reduced Testicular Size and Sperm Production. in Environmental Health Perspectives 103, No.12, Dec 1995 p.1136.<BR>
<B>7</B> David Cadogan, (1996) "Phthalates: Their Effect on Man and the Environment in Perspective" European Council for Plasticisers and Intermediates, PVC96 Conference, Brighton 23-25 April 1996. P63<BR>


</td></tr>
