<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bsources.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<P><a href="#endsadd"><font color="#ff0000">ENDS</font></a> Report 219, April 1993, pp19-21

<P><H2>Spotlight on PVC in the battle over chlorine</H2>


<P><B>Greenpeace has renewed its offensive against the chlorine industry with two reports on 
PVC production. The reports present data from recent studies into releases of dioxins 
and other organochlorines from European PVC plants and warn that there are vital 
gaps in knowledge about the extent and impacts of such emissions. The group has 
already scored one success in persuading the Norwegian authorities to suspend a 
decision to authorise expansion of a PVC plant.</B> 

<P>Global PVC production capacity. the annual CMAI chemical market analysis 
conference in Houston was told recently, will rise from 21 million tonnes in 1991 to 24 
million tonnes by 1997. Almost half of the new capacity is expected to be in expanding 
markets in the Asia-Pacific region. particularly China and India. Their role will be 
particularly critical in absorbing the current surplus of production in the USA, where 
publicity about the environmental impacts of PVC has led to falling sales, particularly 
in packaging. 

<P><B>Key chlorine outlet</B>
<P>These bullish forecasts appear to offer an explanation for Greenpeace's decision to 
home in on PVC in the latest step in its campaign for a ban on all chlorine production 
(ENDS Report 213, pp 15-18). Outlets for chlorine in the manufacture of CFCs, 
chlorinated solvents and bleaching agents are diminishing as recently enacted national 
and international legislation begins to bite. PVC, though, consumes about one third of 
current chlorine production. and the proportion is clearly set to rise with present 
market trends. 

<P>Greenpeace's two reports were released at the PVC industry's  annual conference in 
Brighton at the end of April. They were intended in part as a response to the partial 
life-cycle analysis on PVC published by one of the compound's major producers Norsk 
Hydro, late last year (ENDS Report 215, pp 23-24). 

<P>One of the group's targets is the Paris Commission. Ministers from the North Sea 
countries agreed last September that releases of organohalogens which are toxic, 
persistent and liable to bioaccumulate should be reduced by 2000 to levels that are 
not harmful to man or nature with the aim of their elimination (ENDS Report 212, pp 
29-30). Proposals for action submitted by governments are now being examined by a 
technical working group and a statement of intent may emerge from the Commission's 
annual meeting in June. 

<P>One of the Greenpeace reports constitutes a partial life-cycle analysis of PVC 
summarising the environmental impacts On each stage of its manufacture. The report 
re-emphasises some well-documented problems, such as mercury pollution during 
chlorine production and the difficulties posed during recycling and disposal of PVC 
products due to the substantial quantities of additives employed, some of which are 
now recognised as toxins. On the basis of these inherent problems the group argues 
that PVC manufacture is unlikely ever to be able to fulfil the requirements of cleaner 
production. 

<P><B>Focus on production residues</B>
<P>But it also draws attention to an area of the PVC life-cycle which the group says has 
hitherto been largely overlooked in analyses by industry and government bodies - the 
emissions and residues from production of the feedstocks for PVC, ethylene dichloride 
(EDC) and vinyl chloride monomer (VCM). 

<P>Norsk Hydro's report stated that the main emissions from VCM manufacture are 
EDC, VCM, carbon dioxide, nitrogen oxides and copper catalyst residues, for which it 
gave figures for all its plants. The company concedes that there are many other by-
products and many possible emissions from the cracking and oxychlorination 
processes used to produce VCM. but did not elaborate on these. 

<P>Greenpeace says that recent studies of other firms' PVC plants have shown that some 
of these emissions include dioxins and furans. In its second report. Dioxin Factories, 
it lists nine studies around four European PVC plants for organochlorines in sediment, 
diffuse emissions and groundwater. 

<P>The report cites Norsk Hydro's own measurements at Hydro Plast's factory at 
Stenungsund. Sweden, which identified 29 short-chain organochlorines in the tars and 
the light and heavy ends or residues that are separated from EDC and VCM during 
production. 

<P>The figures, which Norsk Hydro has confirmed, reveal that for every 100,000 tonnes 
of VCM output at the factory, by-products include 897 tonnes of chloroform, 687 
tonnes of 1,1,2-trichloroethane, 511 tonnes of tetrachloroethane, 459 tonnes of EDC 
and smaller quantities of other organochlorines, including 150 tonnes of carbon 
tetrachloride. Norsk Hydro says most of these products are destroyed by incineration. 

<P>But Greenpeace argues that given the many PVC production plants operating around 
the world, the amount of data on such emissions is surprisingly small. It points out that 
many of the compounds emitted during VCM manufacture are included in phase-out 
lists in various international environmental treaties, including the 1990 Ministerial 
declaration on the North Sea. 

<P><B>Sediment contamination</B>
<P>One case study reported was carried out by Dutch scientists in 1988 to look at levels 
of polychlorinated dibenzodioxins and furans (PCDD/Fs) in the sediments of the Rhine. 
In one stretch of the river, this identified the presence of isomer patterns of PCDFs 
which were unlike those which had been linked to incinerator sources. Subsequent 
investigations revealed a similar pattern of isomers in the gas-phase and residue output 
from an EDC production process involving the oxychlorination of ethylene at an Akzo 
factory in Rotterdam 

<P>Another study of sediment contamination was carried out in 1992 at 13 points along 
the Swedish west coast, including a site outside Norsk Hydro's PVC and EDC/VCM 
facilities at Stenungsund. Conducted by several Swedish research groups the study 
found high levels of hexachlorobenzene and pentachlorobenzene at Stenungsund, both 
of which are listed in the firm's by-product inventory for the site. The site was also 
contaminated with higher levels of octachlorodibenzofurans and 
heptachlorodibenzofurans than the other sampling points. 

<P>A further case study reveals findings by the Norwegian Institute of Air and a parallel 
Swedish study of fugitive emissions from Norsk Hydro's plants at Rafnes in Norway 
and at Stenungsund. Diffuse emissions totalled 66 tonnes and 240 tonnes per year, 
respectively, compared with measured direct emissions of 5.3 and 3.67 tonnes per 
year. These were said to include emissions of ethylene chloride, VCM and EDC. The 
other case studies reported by Greenpeace highlight similar discrepancies in emission 
measurements at Norsk Hydro and Solvay facilities. 

<P><B>Permit decision suspended</B> 
<P>Norsk Hydro's response has been to criticise the assumptions of production quantities 
on which Greenpeace bases several of its calculations. A particular objection is that 
emission quantities are quoted without taking into account the amounts that are 
subsequently incinerated. A spokesman confirmed that Norway's Environment Ministry 
has deferred a decision to approve the expansion of PVC production by 200,000 
tonnes per year at Rafnes until mid August, but said this was for a variety of reasons 
and not due to Greenpeace's activity. 

<P>However. a spokeswoman for the Environment Ministry told ENDS that the decision 
had been postponed directly as a result of the evidence presented by Greenpeace. She 
said the reports have been sent to the State Pollution Control Authority, while the 
Ministry itself will be looking at national and international reports of pollution around 
PVC plants. She could not at this stage say whether Norsk Hydro would be required 
to carry out further investigations of its own production facilities. 

<P>Greenpeace accepts in its report that the case studies do not represent a conclusive 
case against PVC. But the group says it will circulate the evidence to environmental 
protection agencies in other countries with PVC industries simply to highlight the 
unknown quantities in assessing the environmental impacts of PVC. At the very least it 
wants a halt in expansions of EDC/VCM and PVC capacity until further independent 
studies of releases have been carried out. 

<P>The European trade association of chlorine manufacturers and users, EuroChlor, has 
responded to the campaign with a non specific statement reiterating the importance of 
PVC and other plastics in many everyday products. EuroChlor points to everyday 
sources of dioxins such as bonfires, cigarette smoke and vehicle exhausts in addition to 
the relatively low emissions from industrial processes. And it added that claims that 
PVC production leads to harmful levels of dioxins and organochlorines are both 
alarmist and misleading. Both the chlorine industry and the PVC industry are 
committed to modem processes and monitoring technologies which ensure that 
emissions from plants are kept within statutory limits.The whiff of chlorine, it seems, 
is prompting the participants in the debate to dig themselves into ever deeper trenches. 


<P><H3>Copyright Material reproduced by permission of Environmental Data Services Ltd, 
London - Publishers of  The Ends Report </H3>

