<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bsources.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<P>Press release from Greenpeace Sweden Nov 95

<H3>Swedish Parliament demands rapid phaseout of PVC 

</H3>
<P>STOCKHOLM, 23 November 1995 - Greenpeace has hailed the decision, of the 
Swedish Parliament to phase out the toxic, chlorinated polyvinyl chloride (PVC) as a 
momentous decision for the future of the planet and future generations: 

<P>The proposal, submitted by the Committee for Agriculture, stated that an overall 
assessment shows that PVC cannot be part of an eco-cycle society, current plasticised 
as well as rigid PVC with environmentally harmful 'additives' should therefore be 
phased out. The phaseout should begin speedily.

<P>"The Swedish Parliament has taken seriously the harmful effects to human health of 
chlorine based substances and has taken real steps, to address the problem", said Matts 
Knapp of Greenpeace Sweden, "It is now time for other countries to do the same and 
work towards the total phaseout of PVC and chlorinated substances world-wide". 

<P>At a hearing on chlorine and chlorinated compounds arranged by the Swedish Ministry 
for Environment prior to the vote, the Swedish Minister for Environment, Anna Lindh 
stated: "It is no longer a question of if PVC should be phased out but how it shall be 
phased out." 

<P>Greenpeace has been campaigning for the phaseout of chlorine based substances such 
as PVC for many years, added Knapp; "This is a tremendous step for the future of our 
planet". The Swedish Chemical Inspectorate and the Swedish EPA will now 
investigate how to phase out PVC based on the Ecocycle Commission's report of 
1993. They are due to present their findings to the Ministry for Environment in June 
1996. 

<P>The text from parliament also includes statements on the production, use, waste 
treatment etc. These are a few excerpts: 


<P>On production: 

<P>...the chlorine manufacture for PVC production puts a burden on the environment 
through emissions of organochlorines, releases of mercury and high energy 
consumption. Several of the light and heavy waste streams from the actual PVC 
manufacture is highly contaminated with dioxins and other undesirable 
organochlorines. There are also diffuse organochlorine emissions from the production 
facility. Based on this, the government and relevant authorities should take the 
opportunity to decrease the negative environmental impact from chlorine production 
and the PVC manufacture itself.


<P>On recycling: 

<P>. . .The committee does not rule out the possibility that PVC can be recycled in the 
future. Material recycling of PVC using current techniques cannot be recommended. It 
should be the responsibility of the manufacturer wanting to initiate recycling to prove 
that it will not cause unacceptable environmental consequences. It should then depend 
on the relevant authority to assess and approve a proposed material recycling scheme.  


<P>On land disposal: 

<P>... conventional disposal is an inappropriate treatment method for older PVC waste 
containing hazardous substances. Conventional disposal is neither acceptable for worn-
out, or newer PVC products with hazardous components. Plasticisers and stabilisers 
will gradually be released and may be spread in the environment. The effects of this 
have not been investigated. Neither has it been investigated which degradation 
products are created in the longer term from the PVC polymer itself. 


<P>On incineration: 

<P>...When PVC is incinerated, most of the plasticisers are destroyed while heavy metals 
from stabilisers are collected in residues. The chlorine content of the incinerated waste 
causes risks from dioxin formation. Because of the chlorine content in the waste. 
special treatment steps are required for treatment of the flue gases and corrosive 
protection equipment in the incinerators. The committee is of the opinion that 
incineration, because of the low energy content in PVC waste, should only be seen as a 
short term option and should therefore decrease. 


<P>On labelling: 

<P>...All new PVC products and other chlorinated plastics should be labelled to make 
separation for recycling of other thermoplastics and waste treatment easier. 


</td></tr>
</table>
