<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bpress.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>


<P>Summary of research paper in<H3><B>SCIENCE, Vol 272, 7 June 1996.</B></H3>
by Mark Strutt, Greenpeace UK.

<p>This issue of <i>Science</i> contains a paper by <a href="cemac01.html">Arnold <i>et al.</i></a>from Tulane University in New Orleans, which reports that mixtures of weakly oestrogenic compounds were between 160 and 1600 times  more potent than the  individual chemicals in the mixture (p.1490). 

<p>The paper inspires two further commentaries in the same issue: one by Jocelyn Kaiser (p.1418) who believes that the findings are causing scientists to take a fresh look at an already "hot topic". The second article (Perspectives p.1451) points out that "We all want to know whether substances in our environment are harmful to us and other animals. But answering this question is no easy task." The author asks "How should the risk of new chemicals be assessed?" Unfortunately the answer to this question is not pursued.

<p>Arnold et al. report that "abnormal sexual development in reptiles (1, 2) or birds (3) as well as feminised responses in male fish (4 - 6) have suggested an association with environmental chemicals functioning as estrogens." Likewise hormone disrupting chemicals have been implicated in increased risk of breast cancer (7, 8) and observed decreases in human semen quality (9,10). Whilst it has been  maintained that these compounds, because of their low potency, are unlikely to have similar effects on humans (11, 12) the combined action of hormone disrupting chemicals has been given very little attention. It is this area that Arnold et al have addressed. 

<p>The researchers used genetically engineered yeast cells to investigate the interaction of a mixture of  chemicals with human oestrogen receptor. They used four pesticides believed to be only weakly oestrogenic; dieldrin, endosulfan, toxaphene and chlordane. When tested individually they yielded little response as expected. But when paired their oestrogenic activity shot up by an a factor of 160 to 1600. A result which one of the authors, John McLachlan, described as "really quite astounding" (p. 1418). Importantly the research was repeated using PCB's and human cells. A five fold increase in oestrogenic response of human endometrial cells to combinations of PCB's was demonstrated. This is the same result they got with PCB's in the yeast system and shows that observed oestrogenic effects were not specific to yeast cells.

<p>McLaughlan is quoted (p 1418) as saying that the team worked with "levels [of environmental estrogens] actually achieved in some systems" (such as turtle eggs and the serum of women with breast cancer). 

<p>The report concludes that "....the addition of weakly estrogenic PCB congeners to developing turtle eggs resulted in sex reversal of  male-determined eggs; addition of two PCB's at sub-threshold concentrations were effective. Likewise, dieldrin, endosulfan, or toxaphene, although only marginally effective in stimulating proliferation of human breast cancer cells in culture, exhibited greater than additive effects when administered together. Apparently synergistic estrogenic effects of environmental chemicals were observed in cultures of fish hepatocytes. Our data...suggest that the estrogenic potency of some environmental chemicals, when tested singly, may be underestimated".
 

<p>(1)  L.J.Guillette Jr. <i>et al., Environmental Health Perspect</i>. <b>102</b>. 680(1994)<br>
(2)  L.J.Guillette Jr., T.S. Gross, D. Gross, A.A. Rooney, H.F. Persival <i>ibid</i> <b>102</b> (suppl 4), 31 (1995)<br>
(3)  D.M. Fry, <i>ibid</i> <b>103</b> (suppl. 7), 165 (1995)<br>
(4)  R. White, S. Jobling, A.A.Hoare, J.P.Sumpter, M.G. Parker, <i>Endocrinology</i> <b>135</b>,  175 (1994)<br>
(5)  S. Jobling and J.P. Sumpter, <i>Aquat. Toxicol</i>. <b>27</b>, 361 (1993)<br>
(6)  S. Jobling <i>et al. Environ. Health Perspect</i>. <b>103</b>, 582 (1995)<br>
(7)  F.J. Falck <i>et al Archives Environ. Health</i> <b>47</b>, 143 (1992)<br>
(8)  M.S. Wolff <i>et al J. Naltl. Cancer Inst</i>. <b>85</b>, 648 (1993)<br>
(9)  E. Carlsen <i>et al Br. Med J.</i> <b>304</b>, (609) 1992<br>
(10)J. Auger <i>et al N.Engl. J. Med</i>. <b>332</b>, 281 (1995)<br>   
(11) S.H. Safe Hum. <i>Ecol. Risk Assessment</i> <b>1</b>, 17 (1995)<br>
(12) R.J. Sherins, <i>N. Engl. J. Med.</i><b>332</b>, 327 (1995)<br> 


</td></tr>
</table>
