<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bhot.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>

<P><KBD><a href="#endsadd"><font color="#ff0000">ENDS</font></a> Report 257, June 1996.</KBD>

<P><H2><KBD>Phthalate scare drives retailers to review use of PVC </KBD></H2>

<P><B>Five major retailers have pooled resources to investigate the environmental and health effects of PVC in the wake of public concern about the health risks posed by phthalates - chemicals used as plasticisers in flexible PVC. The group intends to apply the precautionary principle, and will set strategies and timetables for phasing out PVC if necessary.</B> 

<P>The health risks posed by oestrogenic chemicals were pushed up the agenda in May following the detection of phthalates in baby formula milk by the Ministry of Agriculture (MAFF) (ENDS Report 255, pp 5-6). 

<P>Also in May, the British Retail Consortium's environment committee heard presentations on PVC from Greenpeace and the British Plastics Federation (BPF) in response to requests for more information from members. A few months earlier, Greenpeace had written to major retailers urging them to stop using PVC as part of its wider campaign against chlorine (ENDS Report 229, pp l5-l7). PVC is the single largest market for chlorine, accounting for one-third of use. 

<P>In June, five major retailers - The Body Shop, Tesco, Lloyds Chemists, IKEA and the Co-op - agreed to set up an ad hoc working group to examine the "increasing public concern over PVC and the impact of dioxins and phthalates on human health and the environment." 

<P>The firms say that they will "adopt a precautionary/riskbased approach." They will initially concentrate on packaging, and then move on to applications such as building materials and cables which are of less concern to the consumer. "Timetables and strategies for phasing out PVC from retail applications with significant risk will be considered" if necessary. 

<P>The Body Shop - which, along with IKEA, has already removed PVC from items for retail sale - has led the group to date. Dr David Wheeler, Environmental Affairs Manager for Body Shop International, says that the company will invite other retailers which "recognise the problem" to join the group and "stick by its solutions". 

<P>Although the baby milk furore brought phthalates to the attention of consumers, the product is not packaged in PVC and it is not known how the samples analysed by MAFF became contaminated. The BPF says that phthalates are not used in any PVC food packaging or wrapping manufactured in the UK. It is unclear whether the chemicals are present in imported food packaging or non-food packaging. 

<P>Concern is growing among retailers about oestrogenic chemicals in products. Sainsbury's, for example, intends to investigate whether packaging for it's own brands contains phthalates or other hormone-disrupting chemicals, and will also identify PVC uses outside food packaging.

<P>Boots set up a working party on oestrogenic chemicals earlier this year, but is not convinced that flexible PVC is a major contributor to the problem. "There is a wealth of scientific evidence showing that there is a whole range of oestrogenic chemicals out there. We have to be absolutely sure that any action we take is the most effective way to reduce these effects,"  said Environmental Manager Belinda Howell. 


<P>Text courtesy of <A NAME=endsadd <a href="http://www.ends.co.uk/"><font color="#ff0000">ENDS</font></a></A><BR>
Finsbury Business Centre<BR>
40 Bowling Green Lane<BR>
London EC1 0NE 


</td></tr>
</table>
