<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bhot.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>

<P><KBD><a href="#endsadd"><font color="#ff0000">ENDS</font></a> Report 257, June 1996.</KBD>

<P><H2><KBD>Phthalates scare subsides amidst Euro-confusion </KBD></H2>

<P><B>The public concern which erupted in May over phthalates in baby formula milk was calmed after the European Commission supported an assessment by the Ministry of Agriculture (MAFF) that they pose no risk to health. However, the opinion from Brussels was not based on any scientific assessment - but an EC committee which reviewed the data in June came to less reassuring conclusions about the safety of phthalates in food and the environment.</B> 

<P>The scare began several weeks after MAFF published data on phthalates in baby milk and other foods (ENDS Report 255, pp 5-6). ENDS concluded that babies' intake of all phthalates would be above a precautionary limit set by the EC's Scientific Committee on Food (SCF). The doses of one compound, butyl benzyl phthalate (BBP), were within a factor of ten of doses shown to reduce the testis size and sperm counts of developing rats in a study carried out by Dr Richard Sharpe (ENDS Report 251, pp 8-9). 

<P>The story was picked up by the press in May and dominated the media for a week. The scare prompted the European Commission's Industry Directorate, DGIII, to ask MAFF for the data for circulation to other Member States. 

<P>However, after considering the data for only a day, DGIII announced that it agreed with MAFF's findings that there was no risk to babies' health. A Reuters article on 31 May quoted spokesman Jochen Kubosch as saying: "[Commission researchers] see no reason to say that there is any risk," and "after checking what [MAFF] found in the study, we agree with them." A document in French obtained ,by ENDS from the Commission's London office also claimed that the MAFF data had been "analysed by its experts." 

<P>However, when contacted by ENDS, Mr Kubosch denied that there had been any statement. He  said that all DGIII had done was to circulate the information to Member  States. "It was just an information procedure, not a decision procedure," he said.  Nonetheless, the messages coming from DGIII were widely interpreted by the media as an all-clear and coverage quickly subsided. However, when told that his statements had suggested there had been an independent scientific assessment,
 Mr Kubosch said: "It seems there is  some misunderstanding here. I don't  want to comment on that."  Scientific scrutiny of the MAFF  report was not undertaken until the  SCF met on 7 June. In a statement  after the meeting, the SCF said that it
 was "inappropriate" to compare the total phthalate levels found by MAFF
with the SCF's precautionary limit for all phthalates. The SCF said that 
there are uncertainties over which phthalates might be measured by MAFF's
methods and what the toxicological properties of such mixtures might be.

<P>The SCF added that it was important for Dr Sharpe's work, which showed that low doses of BBP can harm developing rats, to be followed up. His findings "suggest that reproduction could be affected...by exposure during prenatal and early postnatal life, but require confirmation," it concluded. In the meantime, it expressed the view that BBP levels in baby milk were "unlikely" to pose a risk to health. 


<P>The SCF concluded by calling for more data on phthalates in food and improved analytical methods. It also asked "appropriate bodies" to consider the ubiquitous contamination of the environment by phthalates. 

<P>Public reaction to phthalates in baby milk appears to have been as strong in Denmark and the Netherlands as in the UK. 

<P>The Danish Ministry of Health told ENDS that a debate on oestrogenic chemicals has bee,n under way in the press for some time. The Ministry is planning to repeat the phthalate analyses with products on the Danish market. 

<P>The Dutch Ministry of Health also said that there had been much media reaction and it had plans to do its own research into infant phthalate intakes. The levels of BBP found by MAFF gave cause for concern, according to the Ministry, and Dr Sharpe's experiments should be repeated to establish a dose-response relationship for the compound.



<P>Text courtesy of <A NAME=endsadd <a href="http://www.ends.co.uk/"><font color="#ff0000">ENDS</font></a></A><BR>
Finsbury Business Centre<BR>
40 Bowling Green Lane<BR>
London EC1 0NE 


</td></tr>
</table>
</center></body></HTML>
