d width=72><a href="index.html#debate"><img src="../icons/neb223.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td><td width=72><a href="index.html#press"><img src="../icons/ipress.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td><td width=72><a href="index.html#links"><img src="../icons/neb13.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td></tr><tr><!--ROW THREE - CELL ONE--><td><a href="index.html#science home"><img src="../icons/neb11.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td><!--TWO--><td><img src="../icons/neo214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></td><!--THREE--><td><a href="index.html#current evidence"><img src="../icons/neb214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td><td  ><img src="../icons/neo214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></td><td  ><a href="index.html#hot news"><img src="../icons/ner214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td><td  ><img src="../icons/neo214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></td><td  ><a href="index.html#e-mail list"><img src="../icons/neb214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td><td  ><img src="../icons/neo214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></td><td  ><a href="index.html#press"><img src="../icons/neb214.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td><td  ><img src="../icons/neo14.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></td></tr></table><br clear=left><!--END OF NAVIGATOR BAR--><P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0><!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bhot.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr><tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd><!--INSERT TEXT HERE><P><KBD>THE DAILY TELEGRAPH, WEDNESDAY 5th JUNE 1996</KBD><P><H2><KBD>How my work triggered the milk fiasco</KBD></H2><P>DR. RICHARD SHARPE<BR><P><B>‘There should be more accuracy in public utterances on health-scare issues, but in the present climate this would be a disaster’.</B><P>In the past few weeks, I have struggled to find superlatives which adequately describe my incredulity over the media and public reaction to, first BSE, and last week to phthalates in baby milk. <P>Has the rest of Britain gone mad, or is it me? Although I'm sure that scientists in many disciplines will share my reactions, I have the additional burden that it is some of my work that has been used to fuel the public panic on the phthalates. <P>The fact that I see no great problem with the phthalates in baby milk means that somebody is seriously out of line - but is it me or is it the media? To answer this question, without arrogant presumption, takes us into the poorly explored realms of the different perspectives of the scientist and layman about risks and "the truth". <P>To the public, science is about facts. Facts = certainty = "the truth". To a scientist, "facts" are more flexible; they are pieces of data which can often be interpreted in more than one way. <P>So most "facts" are not 100 per cent certain. This is because a scientist knows that. with time, a "fact" will prove to be only part of the truth, not the whole truth. <P>As a result, we scientists speak always in qualified terms, for example describing something as being "more likely" or "highly probable" or "highly unlikely". For a scientist to be more definite would be dishonest, because we know that certainty is a rare commodity. <P>This does not mean that we spend our lives sitting on the fence. We take the available "facts", put them together and construct a possible explanation (a hypothesis) which we then test - usually to destruction - and then repeat the process ad infinitum. So "the facts" and our understanding are forever changing, but improving. <P>The gulf between scientific reality and public perception is even wider regarding risk. I can illustrate this by showing how I, as a scientist, would go about assessing the risk from phthalates in baby milk. <P>I look at my data showing which level of intake of one phthalate in laboratory rats can result in a 10 per cent decrease in sperm production, and I see that this level is l0 - 100 times higher than the levels of this phthalate in baby milk powder reported by the Ministry of Agriculture. <P>At face value, this suggests already that the risk to infants is very low, but I also have to take into account many other factors which I, as an expert know about, not least of which are the inadequacies of my own data (assessment of risk is usually based on much more data). <P>Based on all this and my overall understanding, I can then estimate risk and I conclude that the "risk is minimal". Unfortunately, phrases such as this present a goldmine to journalists looking for a story. They reinterpret this as meaning that there really is some risk. But remember, to a scientist there is no such thing as "no risk", only levels of risk. Driving a car carries a moderate risk of injury, but we all accept it and drive; smoking carries an enormous risk to health, but millions choose to take it.<P>Compared with these, the risk from phthalates in milk powder, or of BSE from eating beef, are infinitesimal based on the available data. Unfortunately, the latter phrase, though scientifically accurate, can be reworked by any journalist to mean almost anything. <P>So who is right? The scientist or the journalist? And remember that public perception of science is based mainly on how non-expert journalists present it. I have little doubt on this issue. <P>The scientist tells the truth as he or she sees it, which amounts to his informed judgment based on the known facts, which he can expertly weigh and assess. In contrast, the non-scientist journalist is interpreting what the scientist says or, worst of all, is trying to please his editor. <P>Time, and new data, may show that the scientist got it wrong, but he told the truth as it was at the time. So believe the scientist before you believe the journalist - and, of course, before you believe the politician. <P>If an independent scientist says that he thinks a risk is minimal, this is what he really believes based on "facts". If a journalist or a politician makes such a pronouncement, then you should be sceptical, as they may not be basing what they say on facts but on the need to fill the front page, protect some sector of industry or to score political points. <P>So how can the general public tell whether a public pronouncement which they hear or read is accurate? An easy guide - if phrases such as "no doubt" and "absolutely certain" are used, then it will be departing from the scientific facts; the first pronouncement on BSE, "absolutely no risk of transmission to man", is a classic example. <P>I feel strongly that there should be more accuracy (that is, more uncertainty) in public utterances on health-scare issues. Unfortunately, in the present climate this would be a colossal disaster for two reasons. <P>First because the public has been desensitised by the gross exaggeration and misrepresentation of scientific data in the form of scares about salmonella and eggs, thrombosis and the new contraceptive pills, and the recent BSE and phthalate fiascos. <P>Second, because the public has not been informed how to judge relative risk. There are no quick solutions to the latter problem, but I think that responsible, informed journalism is the only way to reach the public. <P>This means putting the scary skeletons back in the cupboard and trying to help educate and inform the public on health issues in an honest rather than alarmist way. <P>To carry on as at present is to insult the common sense of the general public, who know that things cannot be as bad as the media are making out. It also means that scientists will stop talking to the media - I now decline eight out of 10 such invitations because I no longer trust the motives of most journalists: And yet, if we scientists stop talking to the media, how can we keep the public informed, which is surely our duty? <P>So the challenge for the media is: Do you really want to inform the public accurately, or do you only want to scare them? <P>The choice can be only yours, but if you want to continue to talk to me and to other scientists freely and openly, then you have got to put your house in order. I want no part of this misinformation fiasco. The public deserves "the truth" with all its shades of grey. <P>And a different challenge for politicians: when scientists express concern, such as over BSE several years ago, don't just presume that their sole motive is to get more research money. Their concern is based on "facts", which may or may not turn out to be the truth. <P>Whichever this should be, to ignore it is to be unwise and, as BSE has illustrated, can result in enormous cost to the country. All for the want of a small shrewd investment, not in industry, but in some half-decent “fact”-finding research. <P>As with everything in life, what you get out is directly proportional to what you put in, and the same is true of scientific research. There are plenty of health-scare storms out there brewing and only "facts", even with all their uncertainty, will quell those which are imagined and prepare us to respond to the infrequent real storm. <P><B>Dr Richard Sharpe has been a leading figure in studies of male infertility and the decline in sperm counts. He conducts research with the MRC Reproductive Biology Unit, Edinburgh. </B></td></tr></table></center></body></HTML>
