<!--INSERT TEXT HERE><P><H3><KBD>SUNDAY EXPRESS, SUNDAY 2ND JUNE 1996</KBD></H3>

<P><H3><KBD>Now breast milk faces tests in poison alert</KBD></H3>


<P><B>By Ian Burrell and Alistair Law<BR>
</B>


<P>Scientists have begun urgent tests of human breast milk amid fears it contains the same 
potentially harmful chemicals discovered last week in powdered baby milk. 

<P>The probe was ordered following the scare over phthalates, a range of organic 
chemicals which can impair fertility. 

<P>European health officials who had demanded details of the brands of British powdered 
milk involved said later that their was no risk to babies.

But 200 mothers around Britain have now been asked by scientists from the Ministry 
of Agriculture Fisheries and Food (MAFF) to submit samples of their breast milk for 
analysis.

<P>The study is being conducted in conjunction with the Medical Research Council at a 
Laboratory in leicester and will take at least nine months to complete.

<P>No previous testing of human milk for phthalates has been conducted and government 
officials want to be sure that levels of the chemicals are within recognised safety limits.

<P><B>Chemicals</B>
<P>Mothers may have absorbed phthalates into their milk through food and water. The 
high fat content of breast milk is likely to be a factor in increasing the prevelance of the 
chemicals.

<P>MAFF was severely criticised for not publishing the names of nine powdered babyfood 
brands found to contain phthalates. One minister claimed the public did not need to 
know about the risks.

<P>"There is no need to talke any action - if there was I would tell you" said Agriculture 
Minister Tim boswell.

<P>But, as details of the breast milk tests emerged, scientists attacked the Governments 
handling of the issue. Gwynne Lyons, a scientific adviser on the 'round table'
committee investigating environmental contaminants - including phthalates - said 
politicians must face up to the perils these chemicals posed. 

<P>"This issue must not be covered over the way the government has done this week," she 
said. "We must do more research and build in much greater safety margins. We cannot 
afford to be complacent."
                                
<B>
                         
<P>    LEVELS OF PHTHALTES FOUND PER kg</B>
    
                             <BR> 31.4 mg     Gravy granules and parmesan cheese
                                       <BR>  4.95 mg   Fats
                                       <BR>  2.9 mg     Confectionary  
                                      <BR>   2.2 mg     Meat and Fish products
                                       <BR>  0.46 mg   Bakery products
                                      <BR>  0.26 mg   Pasta and cerials
                                       <BR>  0.2   mg   Poultry
                                       <BR>  0.18 mg   Baby milk formula
                                       <BR>  0.1   mg   Eggs
                                       <BR>  0.09 mg   Carcass meat
                                       <BR>  0.02 mg   Dried fruits
                                       <BR>  0.003mg  Milk

<P>The safety level for a baby of 4 kilograms (9 pounds) would be 0.2 milligrams of       
phthalte per day (more than a kilogram of baby milk). For an adult weighing 64   
kilograms (10 stones) the safe level is 3.2 milligrams of the chemical per day.
                                                                 Source: MAFF Food Safety Directorate      

<P>Concern over contaminants in human milk is now threatening to eclipse the fears for 
the safety of manufactured milk.

<P>The breast milk tests coincide with government findings that mothers' milk contains 
alarming levels of dioxin, a highly toxic carcinogen produced by waste incineration and 
motor vehicles.

<P>A report completed last week by the MAFF Food Safety Directorate in more than 100 
mothers from Birmingham, Glasgow and Cambridge were nearly 70 times above the 
safety limit.

<P>The potential dangers of phthalates, used to make plastics more flexible, emerged in 
1972 when scientists speculated on their risk to the reproductive system.  In 1985 the 
National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences in America conducted tests on 
powdered baby milk. 

<P>Levels of phthalates were similar to those found in Britsh baby milk last week. But in 
contrast to Britain, the results were made public and millions of dollars spent 
identifying the source of the contamination and removing plastics used in packaging.

<P>Dr Michael Bolger, chief of the FDA's contaminants branch, said: "The (phthalate) 
levels in infant formulae in the U.S. are now below detectable level.


<BR><BR>



</td></tr>
