<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bpress.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE><P><H3><KBD>CHEMISTRY AND INDUSTRY, 6th MAY 1996</KBD></H3>

<P>Copyright SCI. Reproduced by permission.
This article was originally published in Chemistry & Industry, 6 May 1996.

<P><img src="../icons/c&imag.gif">           

<P>At the <a href="http://ci.mond.org"><font color ="#FF0000"> Chemistry and Industry web site</font></a></font>  you will find daily environmental news, a jobs database, meeting
announcements, and many more articles about chemically-related environmental issues.


<P><BR><H3><KBD><P>Another chemical balls-up? </KBD></H3>


<P><I>There is no conclusive evidence that synthetic hormone mimics are harmful. But industry should curb their use now anyway, before customers and governments do so.</I> 


<P>Like a genitally deficient alligator lurking in Lake  Apopka, Florida, concern about the effects of synthetic chemicals on sexual hormones in humans and wildlife is an issue about to take a painful bite out of the chemical industry's backside. Launched last week in Europe, and a month ago in the US, a book describing research on hormone mimics, Our Stolen Future, is the most visible milestone so far in what is turning into
another awkward episode in the industry's history (see page 316).


<P>Compared favourably by US vice-president Al Gore to Silent Spring, Rachel Carson's 1962 bestseller about pesticides, Our Stolen Future eloquently describes research which supports (but doesn't prove) a biologically plausible hypothesis, and leaves many questions unanswered. The research shows that a variety of synthetic chemicals (natural ones too, though it says less on those) can disrupt hormonal signals in animals. This can lead to scrambled sexual organs, sexual dysfunction and disease, bizarre behaviour and other unpleasant effects (see C&l 1995, 575). Research also shows that, in the case of humans, sperm counts are declining (see C&l 1996, 156), and testicular and breast cancers are increasing. The prevalence of undescended testes may also be, as they say, on the rise. 

<P>What is unproven and possibly unprovable, as the book's authors admit, is the hypothesis that the synthetic hormone mimics cause a multitude of environmental ills, that even vanishingly low levels of these chemicals are harmful, and that there is a serious human health and fertility hazard from those chemicals currently still in widespread use. 

<P>Nevertheless, the authors highlight studies that support the hypothesis, and give little or no mention to those that don't. From this, they conclude that exposure to synthetic hormone disrupters should be curtailed. The book is clearly one-sided, but that is its raison d 'etre: to put the case for action now. 

<P>Industry's sensible response - 'there's no evidence' and 'we're going to do some research'-is reminiscent of its forlorn defence of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs). Reasonable, yes; persuasive, no. The parallels with ozone depletion, heavily signposted in Our Stolen Future, are not lost on vice-president Gore: 'It is now clear that we waited too long to ask the right questions about the CFCs that eventually attacked the ozone layer.' 

<P>If the industry believes its own tired rhetoric on sustainable development, self-regulation and better public relations (see page 325), it will have to make more effort than it did with CFCs to respond in a credible fashion. For one thing, it is critical to avoid even inadvertently suggesting that 'no evidence of harm' some how equals 'evidence of no harm'. Equating the two, if only by implication, is just as misleading as the environmentalists' exaggerations. 

<P>There is a better way for industry: get ahead of the issue, not behind it. First, start looking now for the most cost-effective first steps to eliminate or reduce exposure to some putative hormone disrupters, and take these as soon as they are identified. This would provide encouraging evidence that companies are capable of  'responsible care' (in the generic sense), and take momentum out of calls for mandatory bans. (In any case, consumer marketing people will drive these changes even faster than the regulators: 'phthalate free' and 'hormone-friendly' labels will soon sprout in the supermarkets.) 

<P>Second, find new people to run the industry's public relations in Europe. Response to this issue is too little, too late, and too unsophisticated. CEFIC, the European chemical trade federation, has a lamentable lack of information to offer. Oestrogen mimics have been bubbling inexorably to the top of the public agenda for at least four years now (see C&l 1992, 88), plenty of time to cobble together more than some excuses about the difficulty of coordinating an industry view. 

<P>Third, put substantial funding and a sense of urgency into answering all those questions that stretch across the gaps in the data. The industry is already making slow but welcome progress here, with funding available in the US and on its way in Europe. 

<P>In the end, the outcome of this issue revolves around interpretation of the 'precautionary principle'. How much evidence do we need before we act? Companies, understandably, would like conclusive proof; consumer zealots and environmental extremists want to ban all remotely suspicious chemicals now. 

<P>The problem with hormone disrupters, as with other global environmental issues, is that conclusive evidence won't be found soon, if at all. The authors of Our Stolen Future advocate a new approach to risk assessment they call 'eco-epidemiology', in which a roomful of smoking guns mostly pointing at the dead body in the corner are sufficient for action, even if no one sees the bullets fly. Other responsible environmental and health scientists, but not all, also subscribe to a similar 'weight of evidence' philosophy. 

<P>Governments and industry should take this philosophy on board and take prudent, cost-effective, voluntary steps first. Assigning priorities for such action sensibly, of course, hinges partly on facts about these chemicals that are still unknown: for example, their relative potencies and total human exposures. But these unknowns are no excuse for lengthy delay. 


<BR><BR>
</td></tr>
</table>
