<P align=left><img src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0--><!--img width=669 height=41 src="../icons/swimmer7.gif" border=0>


<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bpress.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<P><B>Greenpeace Business.April/May 96</B>






<P>3 New Books-Environmental literary trilogy - the new silent spring?

<P>It is rare that a passionate social justice advocate, a dispassionate scientist, and a 
conservative policymaker see any aspect of the world in the same fundamental way. 
That Colborn, Durnil and Gibbs agree on so much when it comes to chlorine and 
dioxin makes this trilogy of books fascinating from several perspectives.

<P>Concern about toxic pollution in the environment began with Rachel Carson. Her 1962 
book Silent Spring warned that chlorinated pesticides and other man-made poisons 
could pollute the tissues of virtually all living things on earth: fish, birds, mammals and 
people. Carson's central message - the need to stop production and use of a broad 
range of industrial chemicals - was defamed and ignored. Today her foresight seems 
obvious.

<P>Three recently published books in the USA - by an environmental scientist, a 
housewife turned activist from Love Canal, and an arch-conservative Republican party 
leader - form a trilogy in environmental literature that surpasses even Silent Spring in 
their implications for our future. They should not be missed.

<P>Dr Theo Colborn is one of the nation's leading experts on the health effects of 
chemicals which assault the hormonal systems of humans and wildlife. Like Rachel 
Carson before her, Colborn has shaken the foundations of conventional science with 
her astute observations of the natural world, and her interdisciplinary approach to 
biology and toxicology. Her new book, Our Stolen Future: Are We Threatening Our 
Fertility, Intelligence and Survival ?, lives up to its billing as a scientific detective 
story that makes environmental science accessible to ordinary readers. 

<P>With co-authors Dr. John Peterson Myers and journalist Diane Dumanoski, Colborn 
writes engagingly about how she unravelled the 40-year mystery of alarming sexual 
abnormalities and devastating reproductive failures in wildlife - from alligators in 
Florida swamps, to bald eagles in the Great Lakes - and now, growing evidence of 
related problems developing in humans.

<P>She traced the cause to chemicals that are called 'hormone disrupters' because they 
fool the body's delicate hormone system. This system conveys the chemical messages 
that govern human development. The 'hormone disrupters' scramble the messages: 
'Muggers on the body's information superhighway...,' Colborn calls them.

<P>Many hormone disrupters are inextricably linked to industrial uses of chlorine. They 
are found in chlorinated pesticides such as DDT, and in the dioxin coming out of 
incinerator smokestacks, or production of plastics such as the ubiquitous PVC 
(polyvinylchloride). Additional hormone disrupters are commonly added to PVC and 
leach out during use. Scientists believe hormone disrupters are linked to the 50% drop 
in male sperm counts over the last 50 years, and the soaring rates of breast, prostate 
and testicular cancer. 

<P>As any adult knows, hormones rule our sexual and reproductive functions from 
adolescence through menopause. Less known is the fact that hormones also control 
many other sensitive bodily functions. Hormonal disruption, especially during foetal or 
early infant development, can impair fertility, learning ability, create behaviour 
disorders, weaken the immune system's ability to provide protection from infectious 
disease as well as cause some types of cancer. The implications of this information are 
staggering, in that threats to fertility and development could endanger the survival of 
whole species, including humans. 


<P>CHLORINE ON THE GREAT LAKES

Gordon Durnil is a leading figure in the Indiana Republican Party, friend of former 
Vice President Dan Quayle, and George Bush's appointee to the International Joint 
Commission (IJC) - an influential advisory body with jurisdiction over the Great Lakes.

<P>In that capacity, he was convinced by Colborn's research that chlorine was the 
common precursor for many of the worst poisons contaminating the Great Lakes. As 
Chairman of the IJC, he recommended an orderly transition process to sunset the use 
of chlorine in major industrial uses on the Great Lakes.

<P>Durnil's firsthand account of his conversion to environmentalism during the anti-
regulatory craze of the Bush/Quayle Administration is called The Making of a 
Conservative Environmentalist. The book is compelling both for its personal honesty 
and its factual integrity.

<P>A lifelong, pro-business Republican, Durnil candidly exposes the strategy of the 
chemical industry to undermine any meaningful effort to address the crisis in the Great 
Lakes. He draws from his deeply rooted social and economic conservatism to support 
his call for a swift response to the threat posed to children by chlorine based 
compounds such as dioxin. As he concludes, toward the end of his book: 'And one last 
word for my conservative colleagues: We should be leading this parade!'.

<P>Dying From Dioxin reaches the same conclusion from a different starting point. 
Author Lois Marie Gibbs lived and raised a family in dioxin-contaminated Love Canal. 
Her first-hand experience of injury to her family's and community's health, and the 
failure of government and industry to respond to this public health crisis, compelled 
her to take up the fight her self. Her campaign to clean up Love Canal first brought the 
world's attention to the threat posed by industrial waste dumps. 

<P>She is unabashedly anti-corporate, but Gibbs nevertheless shares Durnil's passion to 
protect future generations from the threat posed by dioxin, an inevitable waste product 
of industrial chlorine use. Her new book methodically catalogues the extent of the 
known threats from dioxin: 

<P> there is no safe exposure level; 

<P>humans currently carry dioxin in their bodies at levels that have been proven to 
cause serious health impacts in animals; 

<P> this dioxin bioaccumulates in the fat, and 90% of human exposure occurs through 
our diet (e.g. meats, dairy products, and fish); 

<P> dioxin is linked to cancer and hormone disruption; 

<P> children get the biggest exposures of dioxin while in the uterus, while nursing and 
through diet in early childhood (when body weight is low, yet dietary exposure is 
comparable to adult's). 

<P>Gibbs' call for citizen action echoes Durnil's official IJC mandate: halt incineration (a 
major dioxin source), and phase out industrial production and use of chlorine and PVC 
(the leading industrial use of chlorine today). 

<P>It is rare that a passionate social justice advocate, a dispassionate scientist, and a 
conservative policymaker see any aspect of the world in fundamentally the same way. 
That Colborn, Durnil and Gibbs agree on so much when it comes to chlorine and 
dioxin, makes this trilogy of books fascinating from several perspectives. 

<P>Amidst the urgency of their message, they offer some hope for optimism. There is 
emerging agreement about the nature of the problem and direction of future solutions 
rooted in industrial transition. There would seem to be no further excuse to delay the 
transition to a chlorine-free society. 


</td></tr>
</table>
