<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bpress.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>


<P><B>Scotland on Sunday 12th May 1996</B>

<P><B>Mother's milk may not be best</B>

<P>Scientists disagree about the dangers to babies of dioxins that accumulate in women's bodies, writes Jackie Kemp


<P>Choose your poison: that's the unpleasant choice facing mothers feeding babies. Breast has long been seen as best but scientists are falling out over claims that toxic waste builds up in women's bodies and comes out in their milk.

<P>Dioxins, produced mainly through burning plastic waste, are toxic chemicals which get into the food chain. Over time they accumulate at the top of the chain, in humans. The only mechanism which discharges them - breast feeding - passes them straight into babies. 

<P>A first born baby can get as much as 14% of the lifetime safe dose of dioxins in a year of being breast-fed.

<P>Scandinavian scientists claim new research shows that one in ten women have such a high level that they should breast feed for only a few weeks at most. At a conference next month they will try to put pressure on the World Health Organisation to find a cheap test to establish dioxin levels in women.

<P>But in Britain this week The Ministry of Agriculture Fisheries and Food will publish research carried out by the Royal Hospital for Sick Children in Glasgow showing dioxin levels in breast milk have apparently fallen by a third in the last five years. The complicated tests, costing £2,000 each, were carried out on 20 volunteers in Glasgow and 20 in Birmingham as part of a WHO screening programme.

<P>However, although the levels were lower than in previous tests, they still showed babies getting  a level more than 10 times the safe daily dose for adults in Britain. The US, Holland and Germany have now lowered the estimated safety levels to one tenth of the figure used in Britain.

<P>Many experts regard as complacent the view that breast feeding should be encouraged. One of the worlds leading authorities is the Dutch scientists Janna Koppe. She says her work has shown that dioxins in the mother subtly affect a baby's thyroid gland and liver function. It can even make babies less responsive to stimuli. They have diminished potential, she says.

<P>You cannot say who has a high level of dioxins and who does not, says Koppe. There are some statistical indicators. If a woman is in her 30s or older, they will be higher because they accumulate over time.  If she eats a lot of animal fat, particularly fish and dairy products, they will be higher because those are the main source, and if she has never breast fed a baby before they will be high.

<P>At the conference Koppe will call on the World Health Organisation to take the issue more seriously. The WHO is trying to get people to breast feed. They think the information about dioxins will dilute the message. They fear it will be misinterpreted by women, particularly in the Third World. But if women find out in ten years time that they breast fed when perhaps they should not have, they will be very angry.

<P>Koppe says for the vast majority of women the advantage of breast feeding for their own health  and for the baby's health, outweigh the risks. 

<P>What we want to see is a test available for all women so they can have the information about their dioxin level. I would say if a woman's level is rather high she should consider breast feeding for a few weeks only. Women must make up their own minds, but we want them to have all the information they need to do that.

<P>Koppe says women who are worried should avoid animal fat and drink low fat or organic milk in an attempt to help.

<P>The Women's Environmental Network in the UK supports the governments stance. We say women should keep breast feeding, says spokeswoman Ann Link.

<P>I have seen womanise breasts described by some of these scientists as toxic waste dumps. I think that in the language scientists are using there is an element of undermining women and attacking their bodies and what they can do. Breast feeding is best for the mother and best for the baby.

<P>Link and her colleagues call for a huge effort by society to reduce dioxin levels. We believe that dioxins do most damage to babies in the womb. They cause subtle effects on the development of the thyroid gland and the brain - it may be that disorders like hyperactivity and attention deficit disorder are more common now as a result of dioxin damage.

<P>But the added effect of breast feeding is very slight and does nothing to outweigh the advantages to the baby's immune system and the other advantages of it.

<P>She points out that bottle feeding itself produces more dioxin as a by-product of disposing of the plastic.

 </tr>
