<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bpress.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>

<P><H3><KBD>Chemistry and Industry, 7th August 1995, p575.</KBD></H3>

<P>Copyright SCI. Reproduced by permission.
This article was originally published in Chemistry & Industry, 6 May 1996.

<P><img src="../icons/c&imag.gif">           

<P>At the <a href="http://ci.mond.org"> <font color ="#FF0000"> Chemistry and Industry web site</font></a>  you will find daily environmental news, a jobs database, meeting
announcements, and many more articles about chemically-related environmental issues.

<P><H3><KBD>Fears mount over sex chemicals</KBD></H3>


<P>Environmentalists are attacking the UK government for not phasing out chemicals that mimic the female hormones, oestrogens.  A report from the Medical Research Council (MRC) (1) says that such chemicals might be linked to testicular cancer and falling sperm counts.  The government wants further research before it acts.

<P>‘If there ever was a case for applying the precautionary principle (that is, it's better to be safe than sorry), then this must surely be it,’ fulminate Friends of the Earth (FoE), Greenpeace, the Pesticides Trust, the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF), the Women's Environmental Network and the International Society for Stereology, in a letter to The Times.  They argue that phase-outs are worth inconveniencing some companies if they safeguard the health of many people. 

<P>The report by the MRC's Institute for Environment and Health found that deteriorate reproductive health in humans and wildlife might be connected with the many chemicals that either mimic oestrogens or block the actions of the male hormones.  But it stresses that no-one has proved a direct link.  ‘Proof of a cause-effect relationship is likely to remain elusive,’ it adds. 

<P>The report calls for urgent research to establish human exposure levels; to develop tests to identify oestrogen-mimics; and to investigate testicular cancer and sperm quality. 

<P>The range of suspected chemicals is large.  Natural and synthetic oestrogens, such as those used in oral contraceptives and for veterinary use, are obvious candidates.  Many vegetables also contain oestrogen-like compounds. 

<P>Other culprits are industrial chemicals and byproducts whose oestrogen-like properties have mostly been uncovered since 1990.  These include organochlorine pesticides such as DDT and dieldrin; polychlorinated biphenyls; alkylphenol polyethoxylates, which are non-ionic surfactants; and di(2-ethyhexyl)phthalate, a plasticiser for PVC.  Dioxins may cause problems by inhibiting oestrogens, rather than mimicking them. 

<P>Many researchers have found that sperm count and quality have been falling since the 1940s, says the report,  but it points out that this doesn't necessarily mean that fertility is also on the wane. Other male reproductive disorders - from birth and developmental defects to testicular cancer - are increasing in the UK, Scandinavia and Eastern Europe, Australasia and the US. 

<P>Wildlife is also affected. For example, recent research found that effluent from sewage works made male rainbow trout in English and Welsh rivers produce a protein normally only excreted by female fish who are laying eggs.  Other research highlights sex-changes in alligators and whelks. 

<P>The government claims that the report ‘provides no justification for any immediate action on any particular chemicals.’  But it adds that this might change ‘if and when further scientific evidence is available.’  Controls already exist to limit releases of harmful chemicals into the environment, it says. 

<P>The UK Chemical Industries Association agrees.  ‘We need to develop a fuller understanding of exactly what the problem is and its causes,’ says policy director David Culpin.  The industry is funding research and ‘will take a appropriate action if its products are found to be at fault.’ 

<P>But this is not good enough for environmentalists.  WWF consultant Gwynne Lyons says that regulations only apply to specifically ‘prescribed’ substances; many of the compounds in the report aren't prescribed. 

<P>Meanwhile, FoE's pollution campaigner Roger Lilley points out that the government's sustainable development strategy says action can be taken on dangerous pollutants ‘even where scientific knowledge is not conclusive.’  The ability of our species to reproduce might be under threat, he says. 




<P><B>(1)</B> ‘Environmental oestrogens: consequences to human health and wildlife’, £15, MRC/IEH, University of Leicester, PO Box 138, Leicester LE1 9HN.



