<!--SOURCES TABLE--><a name="sources"></a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><tH valign=center><a href="#idc home"><img src="../icons/bpress.gif" width=576 height=72 border=0 align=center></a></td></tr>

<tr><td ALIGN=LEFT valign=top width=576><kbd>


<P><H3>New Statesman and Society, 7 July 1995 pp 29-30
</H3>

<P><H3>Are men on the way out?</H3>

<P>Sex maybe necessary for genetic fitness, but that does not necessarily mean lots of 
able-bodied males, says Ruth Grant. Some animals do without them altogether, 
others reduce them to dependent dwarfs. Now pollutants maybe threatening those that 
are left. 


<P>It's a very little thing, maleness.  Genetically, vertebrate males, including men, hang on 
by the skin of their teeth (or by the appropriate analogy for the dentitionally challenged 
elements of the animal world). Just one gene, 240 DNA bases long in a genome that 
contains billions of bases, differentiates the male of the species from (in computer 
jargon) the default mode, the female. As Steve Jones, author of the Language of 
Genes, has pointed out, the same gene is found in all male mammals and is similar to 
the gene that passes for masculinity in yeast. It has even been suggested that maleness 
is essentially parasitic, that those 240 bases managed to insert themselves in some 
long-ago bacterial coupling and have remained there ever since, as difficult to get rid 
of as a herpes virus and about as much use. 

<P>As it is with the genotype, so it is with the phenotype, the physical expression of those 
genes. The very precariousness of maleness has been emphasised by the suspicion that 
a number of chemical pollutants can mimic the effects of sex hormones, with dire 
consequences for some male animals, including humans. 

<P>Why sex, and therefore males, exists at all is something of a mystery. After all, 
parthenogenesis, where females simply give birth to daughters, would seem a more 
efficient mode of reproduction - no need to find a mate and all the mother's genes are 
passed on instead of half. For plants and insects there are lots of examples. The best 
known would be dandelions and aphids. However, sex and the genetic diversity it 
brings, whether you like it or not, does appear to be necessary to higher vertebrates. 
Among lower vertebrates, a few frogs, lizards and fishes are parthenogenetic but 
among birds and mammals, apart from a few highly inbred domestic fowl, none is 
known. 

<P>Yet, while males may be necessary for higher animals, why are there so many of them 
and why are they so big? After all, one male can normally inseminate large numbers of 
females and, since most males contribute only fleetingly to fertilisation and little or 
nothing to raising the young, why should the male of a species be much more than a 
rare, short-lived carrier of sperm? The first is easy to answer. There are sound 
mathematical reasons why the ratio of the sexes should be equal, which any biology 
textbook should be able to explain. Only in exceptional circumstances does that ratio 
change. 

<P>The other is more problematic. The idea that males are bigger than females is a rather 
mammal-centred one. It is notoriously untrue for, say, spiders and praying mantises, 
where the male often provides the female with dessert after his one and only effort at 
copulation. For most of the animal world, larger females are the norm. Even among 
mammals, while males are generally larger, there are plenty of exceptions, such as 
rabbits and hares, and some bats, seals and antelopes. The biggest animal that ever 
lived was almost certainly a female, since blue whale females are larger than males. 

<P>Those who enjoy putting the male in his place might appreciate the example of certain 
ceratioid angler fishes. These live in the deep ocean, in total darkness, at depths of 
3,000-10,000 feet. They have large, gaping, teeth-filled mouths and lure their prey by 
flashing luminescent light glands. In I922, one of these fishes, a female 26 inches long, 
was found to have a smaller, two-inch long individual, attached to its skin. At first, this 
was assumed to be a juvenile, but a few years later it was realised that it was actually a 
male fish. Furthermore, their vascular (blood) systems were fused. The young one 
was in reality a fully adult, sexually mature dwarf male. Its mouth parts were fused 
with the female's skin and it no longer fed for itself. Several species of these fish 
employ the same technique; in some it is almost impossible to decide where one fish 
begins and the other ends . The reason seems to be that, in these sparsely populated, 
utterly dark waters, the female would find it difficult to meet an unattached male when 
she needed one. Better to have him reduced to the absolute minimum and carry him 
around with you. 

<P>Not that this represents the limit of this particular strategy. One species of the parasite 
Enteroxenos, which lives inside the gut of sea cucumbers, was thought to be 
hermaphrodite since it appeared to have both male and female parts. Then, in I972, it 
was discovered that the “male organ” was actually all that was left of a dwarf male that 
had invaded the female’s body and then lost virtually all its organs except, of course, 
its testes. 

<P>So why is this eminently reasonable strategy - sexual reproduction without the need for 
a load of loafing males constantly demanding attention, eating food and generally 
making a nuisance of themselves - not adopted by most of the animal kingdom? The 
answer seems to be that, since males are necessary, they become actors in the 
evolutionary game, with individual priorities that may not be those of the species, let 
alone those of the female. The greatest number of viable offspring is the ultimate goal, 
for male as well as female. If, for example, it makes sense to be aggressive and fight 
with other males for access to a harem, then body size and strength will matter. (For an 
interesting and amusing discussion of some of these points see Stephen Jay Gould's 
Hen 's Teeth and Horse’s Toes.) 

<P>Bigger and stronger the human male may be, but definitely not tougher. Life 
expectancy for women is 5-10 per cent greater than for men and almost twice as many 
women as men reach the age of 85. The reasons are complex. It seems to be that, 
across a whole range of indicators, the female body is tougher and more resilient than 
the male. A key factor in the expression of gender in the animal body is the balance of 
the sex hormones, primarily oestrogen in the female and testosterone in the male and it 
is beginning to look as if males, including men, are rather more sensitive to external 
hormonal influences than are females . 

<P>For men, this can be seen in a lowering of sperm counts and an increase in testicular 
cancer. Sperm counts in some industrialised countries have halved over the past 20 
years and testicular cancers have increased dramatically, according to Richard Sharpe 
of the Medical Research Council Reproductive Biology Unit, writing in the journal 
Nature last month. In Denmark, the lifetime risk of developing testicular cancer is now 
nearly 1 per cent and the rise has so alarmed the Danish government that it has 
commissioned a report to be published this autumn. Nor is this the only effect. There is 
other, though more equivocal, evidence of an increase in abnormal development of the 
penis (hypospadias) and failure of descent of the testes (cryptorchidism). The cause is 
thought to be the accumulation of industrial pollutants that mimic the effects of 
oestrogen and cause abnormalities in the development of male embryos which manifest 
themselves later in life. The effects are by no means confined to humans, but have been 
seen in animals from alligators to sea birds . 

<P>Naturally, no pollution threat goes unchallenged these days, and Greenpeace produced 
an ad, coyly entitled You're not half the man your father was, accompanied by an 
equally coy picture of a (very small) cherubic willy (see Green Gauge, 23 June). The 
implication was that oestrogen-like chemicals were a threat to the amour propre of the 
present generation of men. Perhaps. Greenpeace did not get where it is by the subtlety 
of its approach and the ad definitely overstated the case, but there is a case 
nevertheless. As Sharpe points out, the list of potential problem chemicals is large. 
More than 30 have been identified so far, ranging from insecticides to combustion 
products and plasticisers used in the making of clingfilm. These compounds are near-
ubiquitous in the environment, albeit at very low levels, but no one knows whether 
they can act cumulatively, so that while individually none may be above the danger 
level, in total they could be. 

<P>And in addition to the oestrogen mimics, there are the anti-androgens, chemicals that 
bind to testosterone and prevent its action. Last month, it was announced that the main 
breakdown compound from DDT in the body (called p,p'-DDE) is a potent anti-
androgen. It has taken nearly 5O years since its first use to discover the anti-androgen 
effects of DDT and, while its use has been restricted or banned for more than 20 years 
in most developed countries, it was used in enormous quantities before then and it is 
still in very wide use in the third world. As Sharpe points out: We can only guess at 
the levels of exposure to DDT this led to in the general population. Male alligators in 
Florida exposed to high levels of p,p'-DDE have abnormally small penises as well as a 
range of other genital abnormalities. 

<P>So what to do? The crux of the problem is the absence of hard data. Neither the 
amounts and numbers of these chemicals in the environment, nor their effects. nor even 
the factor by which male reproductive disorders have increased, are known with any 
degree of precision. The first priority is thus collection of information. As that 
information is gathered, the net will inevitably widen. In particular, we will have to 
address a question that so far appears to have gone completely unasked. Hormones are 
quintessentially behaviour affecting compounds. What effect, therefore if any, does the 
build up of oestrogen-like and anti-androgen compounds in the environment have on 
the behaviour of the human male? It would be interesting to know.  


<P><H3>Re-published with the permission of New Statesman & Society.
</H3>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></body></HTML>
