http://greenpeace.org:80/~uk/science/ge/gebrief.html 193.67.176.1 19970103174540 text/html 9801
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 03 Jan 1997 17:48:19 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 9630
Last-modified: Mon, 04 Nov 1996 19:49:37 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><BODY TEXT="FFFF00" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="../icons/xlogo.gif"><basefont=-3></font><kbd><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace UK science -Genetic Engineering</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><center><!--INTRO TABLE--></a><table border=0 colspan=2 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72></td><td width=504><kbd><P>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE> Greenpeace Briefing Oct. 1996
<H2>By Christmas, 60% of your food could be genetically manipulated</H2>

<B><I>Genetic manipulation is a vast experiment with unknown risks.  We are all about to become a part of  this global experiment, the results of which are unpredictable and irreversible. But it can be stopped.</I></B>

<P>US farmers are now harvesting the first crop of genetically manipulated soya beans.

<P>These soya beans have been genetically manipulated by chemical giant Monsanto, to be resistant to their own herbicide "Roundup". They contain genes from a bacteria, a virus and a petunia. Monsanto have called these beans "Roundup Ready".

<P>Although, this year, less than 2% of US soya beans planted will be Roundup Ready, the plan is to mix them with traditional soya beans and introduce them into many of the hundreds of products which contain soya bean ingredients.  

<P>About 60% of all processed food contains soya bean ingredients.  Everyday foods like bread, margarine, biscuits and cakes often contain soya, as do many baby foods, vegetarian and diet foods, chocolate and beer.

<P>If this goes ahead,  consumers will NOT have the right to choose whether or not they want to buy or eat genetically manipulated food.

<P>There is only one benefit from Roundup Ready Soya beans: they can survive exposure to the chemical herbicide Roundup  (glyphosate). Against this single benefit weigh the risks of genetic pollution and rising dependence on herbicides.

<P>Consumers do not want genetically manipulated material in their food. In a recent poll carried out in Germany, 80% of those questioned said they did not wish to eat genetically manipulated food. Despite the fact that Europe is one of the largest markets for US soya beans, retailers have been told that food ingredients made from natural soya will NOT BE AVAILABLE when this years harvest arrives in a few weeks time.


<H3>What's wrong with Genetic Manipulation?</H3>

<P>Genetic manipulation (also sometimes called genetic modification, genetic engineering or biotechnology), is still very much an experimental science. The results of this experiment are to a large extent unpredictable. 

<P>1) It is impossible to predict exactly what effect a new set of genes in a plant will have, and how they will make that plant behave. Genetically manipulated plants may cross-breed with wild relatives, leading to strains of wild plants taking on some of the characteristics of the genetically manipulated plant. Existing weeds could become more hardy, food crops could be turned into invasive weeds. The consequences of this sort of  'genetic pollution' could be a loss in plant biodiversity as genetically manipulated species drive more delicate plants from their habitat. 

<P>2) Reliance on a bean like the Roundup Ready Soya bean increases the dependency of farmers on a single chemical company and on chemicals in general. We have seen something similar to this before, with disastrous results for many farmers. Under the flag of the "green revolution" farmers in underdeveloped countries were tied into a dependence on chemical fertilisers and pesticides. The capital intensiveness of this new system drove smaller farmers out of business and reduced biodiversity. The introduction of a new technology had unintended social and environmental costs. 

<P>3) The pathway  for agriculture which involves genetic manipulation effectively rules out the chance for a sustainable agricultural system for the future. By encouraging farmers to use genetically manipulated crops often reliant on chemical herbicides, giant corporations such as Monsanto push the farming industry away from the possibility of a more sustainable agricultural system that uses integrated pest management and organic techniques, something which the public is increasingly interested in. 

<P>4) Changes in the protein structure of foods, through the introduction of new genetic material, may trigger off allergies and have other unpredictable health consequences in humans. 

<P>Field trials are currently inadequate. They do not take into account all the factors that may affect the genetically manipulated crop once it is grown commercially. Field trials are regulated in such a way as to minimise opportunity for seed escape, seed carryover in the soil and pollen escape. However, none of these can be controlled once the plants are grown as commercial crops.

<P>With large scale commercial releases of genetically manipulated organisms, extremely rare events WILL occur.   

<P><I>Impacts on the natural environment are irreversible. Once new genetic material is released it is self replicating and can never be contained.</I>

<P><H3>But won't genetic engineering help to feed the worlds hungry?</H3>

<P>The world hunger problem is not one of a simple shortage of food. The world already produces 50% more food than is necessary to feed everyone. The problem is one of poverty and access to food. Many poor people, especially in third world countries just cannot get access to food, no matter how much is produced.

<P>Genetic manipulation of food does not address this problem. Instead it compounds it by reinforcing the trend in which control of food production and marketing is taken away from small farmers and consolidated in the hands of agri-business. Companies that develop genetically manipulated crops use patents to gain monopoly control over them. Hence the 'Roundup Ready' Soya bean (RRS) has been patented by Monsanto and the seed is sold at a premium price that is out of reach of many small farmers. Patents on crops also mean that royalties may be charged if farmers want to keep some seed for their own use the following season, or if they want to exchange seed with neighbours. Seed saving and exchange is crucial to small farmers in the third world with little or no cash but companies involved in genetic manipulation want farmers to buy afresh each year.

<P>Likewise RRS ties soya bean farmers to a particular chemical herbicide and to a single company that makes that chemical. 


<H3>Great genetic failures of our time.</H3>

<P>There have already been a stream of failures which exemplify the unreliability, unpredictability and potential consequences of large scale releases of manipulated crops. For example: 

<P><B>Genetically manipulated cotton</B> was designed to resist attack from caterpillars by producing a toxin in its own leaves. American farmers planted 600,000 hectares of the new cotton strain. But it didn't work. Not enough toxin was produced. Thousands of hectares were lost despite the spraying of large quantities of herbicide to try to save the crop. The damage was estimated at 1 billion dollars. (Nature Biotechnology Vol.14, 1996).  

<P>Another Monsanto product is the genetically engineered "<B>recombinant Bovine Growth Hormone</B>" (rBGH). It is injected into cows to increase milk production. It has side effects on cows health, it's expensive to buy and the United States already produces a surplus of milk. It's use is currently banned in Europe because here too, a surplus of milk is produced. Monsanto have attempted to sue American companies who dared to label their products rBGH-free.
    
<P>The <B>genetically manipulated bacteria</B> "<I>Pseudomondas putida</I>" was intended to degrade the herbicide 2,4-D. It did just that, but unexpectedly broke it down into a substance that killed beneficial soil fungi. These fungi are crucial to soil fertility and protect plants against disease.

<P><B>Soil bacteria</B> "<I>Klebsiella</I>" were genetically manipulated to transform leftover parts of plants (like leaves) into ethanol that farmers could use as fuel. The engineered bacteria thrived in several soil types, but unexpectedly killed off grass (which died from alcohol poisoning) and caused a decrease in population of the beneficial soil fungi which help plants take up nutrients.   

<P>Previous attempts at a genetically engineered soybean included an inserted <B>Brazil nut gene</B>. It was only because Brazil nut is a known food allergen that the manipulated soya was tested for allergenic potential, found positive and withdrawn before it was used in human food.

<P>The giant Swiss corporation Ciba-Geigy is currently trying to get its genetically manipulated corn onto the European market. Approval has so far not been given as 13 EU Environment Ministers have expressed concern over the genetic modification. In the UK official bodies are concerned about the presence of an antibiotic resistant gene. It is feared that this gene could jump to the gut bacteria of animals that eat the corn and result in bacteria resistant to the antibiotic. 
  
<P>Greenpeace opposes agricultural and food uses of genetic manipulation as they involve deliberate releases of  genetically manipulated life forms into the wider environment.   The gains may be small and accrue to particular companies, the risks are unknown and are taken by the environment and society as a whole.<BR>
<BR>

<P>For further information contact Greenpeace at Canonbury Villas, London N1 2PN
                              
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></body></HTML>
