<HTML><BODY TEXT="FFFF00" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="../icons/xlogo.gif"><basefont=-3></font><kbd><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace UK science -Genetic Engineering</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><center><!--INTRO TABLE--></a><table border=0 colspan=2 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72></td><td width=504><kbd><P>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>What are the risks of releasing genetically manipulated organisms to the environment?

<H3>UNPREDICTABLE AND IRRETRIEVABLE</H3>  

The lessons of plants or animals being transferred to new locations, teach us that we are not able to predict how an organism will behave when introduced into a new environment. Often, for example when the Dutch Elm disease fungus was introduced into the UK in beetles in imported timber, the effects may be extremely damaging and widespread.

<P>The loss of elm trees in the British countryside has not only altered the landscape but because barn owls have lost nesting sites and chaffinches song posts, their numbers have declined. A species of butterfly has been almost lost and voles, having reduced predation from barn owls have been one of the few to benefit. It is unlikely that such a complex chain of events could have been predicted  even by computer modelling. Since they are living and have the capacity to reproduce, GMOs once released, will not be retrievable once environmental damage is recognised. Such damage may take decades to become evident.


<H3>EVOLUTION BYPASSED</H3>

<P>The "new" genes in the GMO may spread to its wild relatives, for instance via pollen in the case of plants, and alter their genetic makeup. The natural evolutionary process may be radically altered.

<H3>MORE CHEMICALS IN OUR COUNTRYSIDE</H3>

Many of the agricultural applications of genetic engineering are going to prolong our dependence on chemical inputs. Genetically engineered herbicide resistant crops have been produced. Their immunity to herbicide means that crops can be sprayed with these chemicals with impunity. The use of such crops will probably hasten the emergence of herbicide resistant weeds, which are already an increasing problem, and a new generation of herbicide resistant crop will have to be developed. Good for the agrochemical industry but not for the environment.

<H3>CHANGING THE COUNTRYSIDE</H3>

Under the multitude of different environmental conditions which exist, GMOs may behave very differently from the way they behave in the laboratory or in carefully controlled field trials. They may spread and displace native species and alter our countryside in irreversible ways. This will be possible for both plants and animals. Transgenic fish with a growth hormone gene inserted so they grow more rapidly are being developed. destined for fish farms they will almost inevitably escape and compete with natural populations, where their increased size and growth rate may lead to the displacement of indigenous species.

<P>So genetic engineering brings its own particular risks to the environment. The release of GMOs to the environment may have unpredictable effects and once released they will not be retrievable. Natural evolutionary processes will be bypassed and our countryside changed. Agricultural applications threaten to entrench our dependence on chemical inputs.

<P>But will genetic engineering solve our present environmental problems of pollution and global warming, and will they feed the world?

<H3>TECHNOLOGICAL FIXES - NOT SOLUTIONS TO PROBLEMS</H3>

Industry is designing bacteria to digest pollutants. This sounds wonderful but the pollutants will already have damaged the environment. Our efforts should be focused on pollution prevention rather than cleaning up afterwards.

<H3>AVOIDING THE ISSUES</H3>

Designing crops to grow in hotter climates and algae to consume carbon dioxide also sounds attractive, but distract us from taking active steps now to reduce carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gas emissions.


<H3>NOT REACHING THE PEOPLE IN NEED</H3>

The new crops far from feeding the world are likely to continue to depend on chemical inputs, be expensive and not available to the poor farmers who really need help. In the same way the agricultural "Green Revolution" of the 1970s has failed to prevent starvation neither will genetic engineering. There are more fundamental issues to be addressed.

<P>So far from solving the problems we solve today, genetic engineering will not only bring new threats to the environment but will divert us from the fundamental problems by promising technological fixes which won't help those that need it most.

</td></tr>
</table>
</center></body></HTML>
