<HTML><BODY TEXT="FFFF00" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="../icons/xlogo.gif"><basefont=-3></font><kbd><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace UK science -Genetic Engineering</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><center><!--INTRO TABLE--></a><table border=0 colspan=2 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72></td><td width=504><kbd><P>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>
Greenpeace press release on EU corn decision


<H3>EU COMMISSION OPENS FLOODGATES TO GENETIC HAZARD</H3>
 
Brussells, 18 December 1996 -- Greenpeace has strongly criticised the
European Commission's failure to protect Europe's environment and
citizens' rights when it approved today the authorisation of Ciba
Geigy's genetech maize.
 
<p>For the first time genetically engineered crops can be legally grown,
imported  and used in food in Europe.
"To release a crop which may increase antibiotic resistance in
dangerous bacteria and could increase  pesticide resistance in
insects is one of the most irresponsible decisions the Commission has
taken," said  Louise Gale of Greenpeace's European Unit. "The known
risks to the environment and to human health have apparently been
swept aside by the Commission."
 
<p>"Once more the Commission has given in to pressure from the genetic
engineering industry and the USA. And, once more the Commission has
ignored its duties to protect the environment and  the public's
health".
 
<p>Greenpeace calls on members states to take control of this dangerous
situation in Europe and to take matters into their own hands.
 
<p>"We recommend that Member States use their EU legal rights to ban the
imports and use of this genetech corn and to take the European
Commission to the European Court of Justice for violating Directive
90/220."
 
<p>"Europe is opening the floodgates to widespread environmental and
health hazards. We will take action to ensure that the food and animal
industry reject genetically manipulated products," said international
campaigner Michelle Sheather.
 
<p>Although the Commission's scientific committees have concluded that
the corn is safe, this has not been the opinion of 13 member states
who oposed approval of the corn last June, after advice from their own
scientific advisers.  Greenpeace has pointed out that the Commission's
scientific committees did not predict the disastrous situation arising
from BSE when animal carcasses were allowed to be used as animal feed.
 
<p>Although not approved, at least  hundred thousand tonnes of US corn --
some of it genetically engineered and therefore illegal -- has arrived
and continues to arrive in Europe, including the Netherlands, Belgium,
Finland, Italy, Portugal and the UK.<br>
 
 
 
ends<br><br>
 
 
For further information contact Louise Gale or Isabelle Meister in
Brussels on 00 31 6  534 17 947
 
<p>Note picture editors:
 
Photographs available Greenpeace International. Call James Gillies on
00 31 20 524 9548


</td></tr>
</table>
</center></body></HTML>
