<HTML><BODY TEXT="FFFF00" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="../icons/xlogo.gif"><basefont=-3></font><kbd><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace UK science -Genetic Engineering</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><center><!--INTRO TABLE--></a><table border=0 colspan=2 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72></td><td width=504><kbd><P>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>
Media Transcription Service
(Partners: Susan & David Stott)<br>
"The Sycamores"  2a, Richmond Road, Birkdale, Southport. PR8 4SB<br> 
'phone/fax: 01704 563092 e-Mail: mts@gn.apc.org

M.T.S. Transcript - Ref No.: 4623


<p><b>BBC-2 Television "Newsnight" Wednesday 18th December 1996</b>

<h4>Genetically-engineered corn: Extracts from an interview with Professor Derek Burke (in Cambridge)</H4>

<p>Presenter (Peter Snow): "I am joined from Cambridge by Professor Derek Burke, who
is the Chief Scientific Adviser to the Government on this food issue.

<p>"Professor Burke, you've heard the Commissioner (i.e.,
Ritt Bjerregaard - EU Environment Commissioner). She's consulted three scientific committees, they've come back with their answer and she is persuaded that this stuff is safe. Is it safe?"

<p>Professor Derek Burke:
"Let me first of all reassure many of your viewers about
some of the things that were said earlier in the programme. Nobody is going to eat this corn. It is not the corn you buy in supermarkets, it's not the corn that's used for human consumption, it's the corn that's fed to cattle. Most of the corn we import from the United States is processed and finishes up as pellets. Those pellets are absolutely safe. So we're only talking about corn that is imported that is fed to cattle and we were concerned about that. But even that's not a major problem this year. There's fifteen thousand tonnes going to be imported this year from the US of this unprocessed corn and around point six per cent of that will be the genetically- modified form."

<p>Presenter:
"But let's cut through all this. There are still going to
be products in the shops that are the final result of all this."

<p>Professor Burke:
"No."

<p>Presenter:
"Surely? It can be fed to animals and we'll eventually
find that ending up in the shops?"

<p>Professor Burke:
"The products you'll find in the shops have all been
treated in such a way that the genetic material that we're worried about has been completely degraded. I can reassure your viewers that the products in the shops are safe. What we're concerned about is transfer of antibiotic resistance to cattle and ultimately into the population. This is not a problem of food safety, it's more a problem of medical safety and we were concerned and, as you say, the European Commission has decided that our concerns are not sufficient to hold back the product."

<p>Presenter:
"Well, are you reassured or not? Do you still insist on
what you originally said: that we were concerned - or not?"

<p>Professor Burke:
"Yes, we still hold our original view but you've got to
understand, Peter, that we're all working in areas where our knowledge is limited. We've taken a rather more cautious view, the European committees have taken a less cautious view, but both of us are working in areas where we're not absolutely certain what would happen and I would prefer to be cautious in those circumstances."

<p>Presenter:
"What does that mean, then? Do you think this stuff
should be coming into this country or not?"

<p>Professor Burke:
"That's still my view: that it shouldn't be coming into
this country..."

<p>Presenter:
"So what are you going to do about it?"

<p>Professor Burke:
"Well, I think the EU has now made a decision which is
binding. What we should now do is start to discover what we can do next year, when there will be much more of the genetically-modified corn coming through. And we shall also try and find out whether any of the concerns that our Committee had are real in practice. And there are experiments we can do to actually monitor the effects of the corn on the cattle and I think we should be doing those."

<p>Presenter:
"In the meantime, should you be saying to the Government-
or should the Government be saying on your advice - this stuff is not yet cleared, we don't think it's yet safe, it should be held back until we're satisfied it is."

<p>Professor Burke:
"I think the best people to leave to make the decision
are the food manufacturers and retailers, who are very concerned about this issue - as I am - and who are likely to..."

<p>Presenter:
"One food manufacturer - well, I suppose he's not exactly
a food manufacturer - we heard the gentleman from Ciba-Geigy saying life is not risk-free."

<p>Professor Burke:
"No but you'll find that food retailers are very
sensitive to their consumers. The last thing they want to do is drive people away from their doors. I think they will probably take steps to limit or exclude this GM corn from the UK this year and they'll make a decision later this week. So there are things that can be done to keep Britain free of this problem. Meantime we've really got to settle down and decide how we're going to handle it next year."

<p>Presenter:
"In one word, is this in a sense, if this stuff is not
prevented coming in, is this in the nature of a serious health worry in the long-term or not? How urgently would you try and persuade the Government to take action now?"

<p>Professor Burke:
"It's not a catastrophe, it's not a plague that's coming
upon us but it's something we should deal with because we're going to have other issues like this coming and, as your commentator said, food is now a commodity product, we can't separate out these different things. We're going to have to find ways of handling them."

<p>Transcribed by: Susan Stott,
M. T. S.,
"The Sycamores" 2a, Richmond Road, Birkdale, Southport. PR8 4SB


</td></tr>
