<HTML><BODY TEXT="FFFF00" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="../icons/xlogo.gif"><basefont=-3></font><kbd><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace UK science -Genetic Engineering</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><center><!--INTRO TABLE--></a><table border=0 colspan=2 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72></td><td width=504><kbd><P>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>
<P>This article was originally published in the 14 December 1996 issue of  NEW SCIENTIST. It is republished with permission.

<P><A HREF=http://www.newscientist.com/><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=84 BORDER=0 SRC="../icons/logo.gif"><font color="#ff0000">At New Scientist's web site</font></A> you will find more 
news, features, and a comprehensive database of science jobs updated weekly. 

<P><B> &copy; IPC Magazines Limited.</B>

<H3>Outlaw Corn</H3>

Maize that has been genetically altered is being illegally imported into Europe, according to the European Commission. Marius Enthoven, head of the commission's environment arm, told member states late last month that, since the beggining of October, "4000 to 5000 tonnes of maize have been entering the community market every week".

<p>Most of the maize comes from the US, where about 1 per cent of this years crop is a strain developed by the Swiss based multinational firm Ciba-Geigy, containing a bacterial gene for Bt, an insecticide. As American traders have not been segregating the altered grain, "it is to be expected" that the imports contain "non-authorised Bt maize", Enthoven wrote to member states. 

<p>European Union approval for imports of Ciba-Geigy's maize has been delayed due to British fears that a gene in the plant that confers resistance to the antibiotic ampicillin might jump to bacteria. A decision awaits the advice of three scientific committees.<br>    

<P><A HREF=http://www.newscientist.com/><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=84 BORDER=0 SRC="../icons/logo.gif"><font color="#ff0000">At New Scientist's web site</font></A> you will find more 
news, features, and a comprehensive database of science jobs updated weekly. 

<P><B> &copy; IPC Magazines Limited.</B>


</td></tr>
</table>
