<HTML><BODY TEXT="FFFF00" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="../icons/xlogo.gif"><basefont=-3></font><kbd><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace UK science -Genetic Engineering</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><center><!--INTRO TABLE--></a><table border=0 colspan=2 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72></td><td width=504><kbd><P>

<!--INSERT TEXT HERE>
<H3>Retailers and Food Manufacturers. Who is doing what?</H3> As of 22 Nov 1996<BR>

<P>Unilever UK are say it is not possible to avoid using genetically engineered soya in their products (Flora, Blue Band & I Can't Believe Its Not Butter margarines, Magnum, Cornetto, Solero and other ice creams, Birds Eye frozen foods). This is strange as Unilever Germany have stated that they will not be using soya until they can be assured of natural sources for the 20 million bushels they use each year. 

<P>Meanwhile Kraft Jacobs Suchard are putting their customers  first. The fourth biggest food producer in Europe, are showing that it is not necessary to use genetically modified soya. Their products include Maxwell House Coffee, Angel Delight & Birds Custards deserts, Philadelphia & Dairy Lea cheeses, Terry's chocolates and Vitalite margarine. On November 4th 1996 they faxed the following statement to Greenpeace International:

<P><I>We would very much agree with you that the circumstances surrounding the introduction of genetically modified soya into the European market are totally unsatisfactory from everyone's perspective - producer, consumer, processor and food manufacturer.

Currently, and for the foreseeable future, all soya based ingredients in KJS's products in Europe will be derived from conventionally grown soya. Any change in that practice in future will most assuredly be disclosed.</I><BR>
<BR>


<P>Among UK retailers, Sainsbury's are doing the least. Earlier this year, in a leaflet that accompanied genetically engineered tomato purée, they promised; "If Sainsbury's are to sell further products developed with the aid of genetic modification, these will be labelled." They are now intending to break this promise. On the 18th September 1996 Sainsbury's withdrew instructions to Nestlé regarding  segregation of genetically engineered soya and labelling of products containing it. They later announced "we have been forced to accept that we won't be able to label (soya products) separately." <a href="arthur.html">(Article in <I>The Independent </I> 21.10.96)</a> 

<P>Iceland Frozen Foods are at the moment the only  UK retail chain making a serious effort to ensure their customers right to buy natural food. They say "we have contacted all our suppliers and requested immediate details of their supply chain.......we are now pursuing details of suppliers for 1998 and beyond".
 
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></body></HTML>
